GCAT	War in eastern Zaire is affecting an increasingly wide area, with more people fleeing and ever greater numbers going hungry, aid workers said on Friday. Spain, one of the backers of a proposed international intervention force in Zaire, said hundreds of thousands would die of hunger before effective help arrived. Food riots hit the eastern city of Goma on Friday morning. Armed rebels fired into the air to beat back more than 1,000 hungry people trying to seize the last food in a U.N. warehouse. "I have had nothing to eat today and nothing but water yesterday," said 60-year-old Fessu Mahkenya. No food has entered Goma, which has an estimated population of about 200,000, since rebel forces seized the city late last week. Virtually all its shops and hotels have been looted. An emergency health committee in Goma appealed on Friday for agencies to intervene and supply medicine and medical equipment. Goma's last foreign aid workers fled to Rwanda last Saturday after fierce battles which killed more than 400 people. "The whole international community is called to immediate action at the highest level before it is too late," said Jean Nicholas Kasereka Busara, who heads the city's health committee. "This tragedy will become far worse unless urgent measures are taken," said the committee, adding that 300,000 Zaireans had been hit by the conflict, which entered a fourth week on Friday. A Spanish government spokesman in Madrid said hundreds of thousands would die before effective aid arrived in the region. "The plan is going to work. The U.S. and international community will send troops," said the spokesman. "But it will be too late anyhow. Now people are starving, they are dying from hunger. When these troops reach Kindu (Zaire), it will be too late. Hundreds of thousands will be dead at that time." A complex multi-sided war in eastern Zaire has cut off more than one million Rwandan refugees from the outside world and also driven more and more uprooted Zaireans to hunger. A Spanish aid worker who fled Zaire on Wednesday told a meeting in Nairobi of virtual mayhem in the east as some 175,000 refugees fled two camps after looting aid agency warehouses. U.N. officials quoted him as saying competing armed groups of Zairean soldiers, Rwandan Hutu militiamen and refugees were rampaging in the region, looting camps and Zairean villages. He said the 175,000 refugees who fled Kahindo and Katale camps headed west through wide lava fields, which emit dangerous gases, and some died from lack of food and water. "We were amazed to see some of them climb up mountains. We could see the campfires at night," said the aid worker, twice threatened with execution by former Rwandan troops. Weeks of hand-wringing by governments and aid agencies have so far produced no international consensus on what can be done. But diplomatic efforts on Friday concentrated on Rwanda, a key player because of its backing for the rebels in Zaire. U.N. special envoy Raymond Chretien on Friday started talks in the Rwandan capital Kigali with the country's leaders to seek their support for a U.N. force in eastern Zaire. "Without Rwanda's support, the whole operation could end up very, very messy or even impossible to launch," a U.N. diplomat told Reuters. The Rwandan Hutu refugees, half of them under 16, include tens of thousands of former Rwandan army troops and militiamen who fled their homeland in 1994 after the genocide of up to one million Tutsis and moderate Hutus. Armed Hutus, fearing death if they return to Rwanda, now guard what is left of the refugee camps in Zaire and have denied access to outsiders since an insurrection involving Tutsis and other Zaireans cut them off from foreign aid. On Thursday Zairean villagers near the huge Mugunga camp west of Goma said Rwandan Hutu fighters seized about 100 local children to use as human shields in case of a rebel advance on the camp. The food riots in Goma showed that Zaireans themselves, not just the Rwandan refugees, are caught up in a tragedy of growing proportions. Aid workers said on Friday the conflict was affecting wide stretches of the eastern Zaire borderlands and many villagers were fleeing into the bush and refugees into lava fields and up mountains. A U.N. spokeswoman in Geneva said on Friday the U.N. refugee agency had so far not received satellite photographs requested from Western states in late October to track the refugees.
ECAT	Ukrainian banks began receiving Treasury bill payments from the Finance Ministry several hours late on Thursday, and the central bank chairman promised there would be no more delays. Representatives of Bank Ukraina and TK Kredit bank said payments for interest and principal on nine- and twelve-month T-bills arrived just after 5 p.m. (1400 GMT). The ministry's payment to banks of 4.116 trillion karbovanets ($23.3 million) was due on September 18 although the ministry usually effects payments the morning after the due date. It was the third time in less than a month that the ministry has been late on its payments. "Today the issue was discussed with the prime minister and it was raised before the president, about the ministry's failure to fulfill its obligations," central bank chairman Viktor Yushchenko told reporters. "I think that measures have been taken that will guarantee that this issue is closed forever," he said. Yushchenko did not elaborate on the measures. A Finance Ministry spokesman said he could not explain the delay. On August 29, the ministry delayed a $23 million payment for half a day and on September 11 a similar delay occurred with a $22 million payment. Ukraine has replaced the karbovanets currency with the hryvnia, but some calculations on T-bill transactions are still being conducted in the old currency. The hryvnia, unchanged at 1.76 to the dollar since its introduction on September 2, equals 100,000 karbovanets. --Irene Marushko, Kiev Newsroom +380 44 229 2264
ECAT	Chile's Imacec economic growth index climbed a moderate 5.0 percent in September over the same month last year, the Central Bank reported. The new figure brought growth in the first nine months of the year to 7.0 percent over the same period last year, the bank said in its biweekly report. The Imacec, a kind of preliminary barometer of gross domestic product growth, rose 5.7 percent last month. The September figure was on the low end of most expectations and gave a new sign that economic growth was slowing in Chile due to restrictive Central Bank monetary policies. --Roger Atwood, Santiago newsroom +56-2-699-5595 x211
GCAT	French President Jacques Chirac said on Friday he saw a "revolution" in Europe in its growing acceptance of a need for a social model to protect its citizens from unemployment and poverty. Chirac, speaking two days ahead of a parliamentary election in France, also said Europe needed to look harder at ways of reviving weak economic growth, which he blamed for joblessness and exclusion of many from mainstream society. France has long fought for Europe to maintain much of its system of welfare and worker protection, rather than adopting the free market policies of the United States which some believe would help bring down its record unemployment. Chirac said the idea of a "social model" was gathering support, and noted plans to make legally binding a commitment to fighting unemployment through a revision to European Union treaties. Britain's new Labour government has also agreed to sign up to the European Union's social chapter, which sets minimum standards for workers, reversing years of resistance by the outgoing conservatives. "If we succeed in getting the idea of a European social model taken on board, it is a revolution," he told a news conference during a summit of EU leaders in the Dutch seaside town of Noordwijk. Chirac said he had stressed the need to tackle weak growth during the summit. "Europe is the only region in the world where growth is weak," he said. "We have to go a bit further to look for solutions to this problem of inadequate growth and its social consequences." He said only one European leader had called for greater labour force flexibility to reduce joblessness -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair -- and was greeted with silence. And while Europe needed to reduce the social charges which weighed too heavily on the cost of labour, it must avoid the kind of full liberalisation which would fragment society. France's centre-right government, campaigning for re-election in the two-round vote on May 25 and June 1, has been fighting to fend off charges by the opposition Socialist party that its policies would exacerbate unemployment and poverty through new austerity measures. Chirac's comments appeared meant to underline the commitment of the mainstream right-wing in France to work actively to boost growth and tackle unemployment.
GCAT	President Bill Clinton's decision to certify Mexico as a U.S. partner in the war on drugs drew strong bipartisan criticism in Congress on Friday along with a pledge to try to overturn the action. "The law requires the president to certify that Mexico has 'cooperated fully with the United States, or taken adequate steps on its own' to combat drug trafficking. I do not see how such an assertion can be made," Sen. Dianne Feinstein said. "I now intend to work with my colleagues to prepare and submit a resolution to disapprove this decision in the Congress," Feinstein, a California Democrat, said in a statement. Such a resolution would have to be passed by both the House of Representatives and the Senate and sent to Clinton. If the president vetoed it, as he almost certainly would, it would have to be passed again by a two-thirds majority in order to become effective. "I believe that a bipartisan majority in Congress will overturn the president's certification of Mexico. I will work to make that happen," Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms, a North Carolina Republican, said. "Have we received some cooperation from Mexico?" asked Feinstein. "Undoubtedly. President (Ernesto) Zeillo and many others are working with us in good faith. But have we received full cooperation? Not even close," she said. "We cannot continue to allow the drug cartels to operate out of Mexico with a wink and a nod by the Mexican government," Idaho Republican Sen. Larry Craig said. New Jersey Democrat Sen. Robert Torricelli said the decision would be difficult to explain to U.S. law enforcement officers. "I genuinely regret this decision," he said. He said he believed Colombia, which was decertified, made more progress against drugs last year than Mexico. Feinstein, Craig and Torricelli were among 40 senators who sent a letter to Clinton this week urging him to decertify Mexico. House members, including Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri, have also called for decertification because of widespread government corruption. "Recent events make it clear that certifying Mexico at this time is the wrong message to send to the drug kingpins. It says business as usual can continue," Gephardt said. Sen. Joseph Biden, a Delaware Democrat, said he was disappointed by Clinton's decision. New Mexico Republican Sen. Pete Domenici said Mexico must prove itself as an ally to avoid decertification next year. Congressional opposition to Mexico's certification intensified after the arrest last week of Mexico's anti-narcotics chief, Gen. Jesus Gutierrez Rebollo, accused of taking bribes from a drug kingpin. Critics in Congress said they feared Gutierrez might have passed on sensitive information to drug cartel leaders. They also complained that Mexico refused to honour U.S. extradition requests for cartel leaders and failed to cooperate with U.S. drug agents operating in Mexico.
MCAT	EU green rates for the German Mark, the Dutch Guilder, the Belgian franc and the Austrian schilling are to be devalued with effect from January 1, the UK's Home Grown Cereals Authority said.   The new rates are as follows - 1 Ecu equals 40.0486 Belgian francs (old rate 39.9502), 1.94386 German Marks (1.93805), 2.18167 Dutch guilders (2.17413) and 13.6782 Austrian schillings (13.6364) Also on January 1, the Irish punt will enter its fifth and final confirmation period ahead of a possible revaluation on January 11, 1997. And sterling will enter the fourth of a possible five confirmation periods, ahead of a possible revaluation on January 21, 1997. So-called "green" or agricultural conversion rates are used in EU farm policy to convert institutional prices, subsidies and levies into the national currencies of the EU member states. --Christopher Lyddon, London newsroom +44 171 542 7928
ECAT	South Korea's entry into the OECD club of rich nations would speed up the government's deregulation drive, analysts said on Saturday. But critics and opposition parties warn against the adverse impact of further prying open local markets to offshore competition, especially on small and medium-sized industries. Friday's decision by the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) to invite South Korea into the Paris-based group of industrialised nations has met enthusiastic applause from finance ministry officials. Seoul predicts the long-sought invitation will be swiftly ratified by South Korea's 299-seat National Assembly, in which President Kim Young-sam's ruling party has a slim majority. "I see little problem at the parliament as opposition parties would not want to see the nation's image hurt by a rejection," Hyun Jung-taik, Director-General for the ministry's International Economic Policy Bureau, told Reuters. The government's optimism appeared justified on Saturday after the main opposition party announced it would reconsider its stance on entry into the 28-member OECD, backing away from a vow on Friday to block the move in parliament. "There has been no change in our stance that it's too early for the nation to join the club," said Chung Dong-young, a spokesman for the National Congress for New Politics party. "But now that the decision was made, we see the necessity for reconsideration," he added. Critics fear OECD membership will only hamper the economy by triggering a rush of foreign competition which could squeeze local small to medium sized firms while raising the risk of a volatile share market by attracting more offshore funds. "Smaller firms have owed much of their business to various protective policies by the government. But now, the government would not be able to continue this," said Lee Hahn-ku, president of the Daewoo Research Institute. The Citizens Coalition for Economic Justice, one of South Korea's major lobby groups, said it would mount nationwide campaign to block ratification of OECD admission. "Entry at this time, when financial industries are not prepared for foreign competition, would only stir chaos," said Ra Young-sam, a senior official at the coalition. "It's absolutely premature and we will block it." Since the early 1990s, South Korea has taken steps to slowly open its markets, offering to announce new measures to speed up the process if it won OECD membership. On October 1, the ceiling on foreign ownership in local stocks was raised to 20 percent for most South Korean listed companies from 18 percent. The government has pledged to expand the ceiling by three percentage points every year by 1999. Foreign investment in unsecured corporate bonds issued by small and medium-sized firms will be allowed from late 1998. Analysts said the huge gap between South Korea's long-term interest rates, now hovering over 12 percent, and the lower rates of most OECD-member nations could attract a rush of speculative funds into South Korea. "Whether we gain or lose from the admission will depend on how well the government can prepare for every possible scenario," said Lee of Daewoo. An OECD statement on Friday said South Korea would be the 11th largest exporter in the OECD zone and accounted for about 2.5 percent of world exports, a position which had been enhanced through liberalisation of its own import controls. South Korea would be the second Asian nation after Japan to become a member at the club. From the wider Asia-Pacific area, Australia and New Zealand are also members of the OECD.
MCAT	United Arab Emirates shares resisted a wave of selling pressure in the week to Thursday to end without any significant price changes, brokers said. They said buying interest remained low for the second week running as most investors focused their demand on a 209 million dirham public offering by a new UAE insurance firm. "Subscription in Al-Khazna Insurance Company which started on Tuesday was the centre of attention," one broker said. He said small investors resorted to selling some recently- acquired shares as the 12-day subscription period was too short for them to arrange alternative funding to buy into the new flotation. But shares managed to hold recent levels. Dubai Investment Co (DIC) was the exception, with its share price ending half a dirham lower at 12.5 dirhams. Other share prices were unchanged. The unofficial National Bank of Abu Dhabi 27-share index ended the week fractionally lower at 2,333.02 points from 2,335.06 the previous week. -- Dubai Newsroom  9714-626990
