CCAT	RBC Dominion Securities, a unit of Royal Bank of Canada, said on Tuesday that it has formed a strategic alliance with SMK Securities Ltd and acquired a 10 percent stake in the South African firm. Following this initial investment, SMK's management and Boland Bank will each own 45% of SMK Securities. "The agreements signed contemplate RBC Dominion Securities increasing its ownership interest in SMK Securities to 50% over the next two years," the Toronto-based brokerage firm said in a statement. The value of the transaction was not disclosed.
CCAT	Europe's network of internet companies is set to consolidate over the next 18 months, with smaller service providers being swallowed up by telecoms firms and larger providers, an internet conference heard on Monday. Chris Champion, analyst for the Yankee Group telecoms consultancy, said Europe's internet network had grown up as a patchwork of operations with no single company dominating. "There is no dominant pan-European player," said Champion, "But I expect a handful of them to emerge over the next 18 months. There aren't any at the moment because it's a nascent market compared to the United States." Champion told the conference that, unlike in the US, much of the European internet "backbone" infrastructure was still largely in academic and non-profit hands, although commercial firms were involved in building and running those backbones. He saw cross-border deals emerging as telecoms companies, often with dominating positions in their home markets, looked abroad for more internet business. "The bigger players, which are the telecoms players and the internet alliances, haven't really moved out of their home markets yet. I expect this to happen very soon," he told Reuters in an interview after his presentation. Consolidation would happen as the bigger players hunted down the potential revenues on offer, perhaps looking for acquisitions and beefing up alliances. Champion estimated that the 3.2 million European internet-using households currently generated around $640 million a year in access business. He projected that by 2000 Europe would have 16 million internet households generating over $3.0 billion. "Europe has woken up late. You could say that 1995 in the US was the year of the internet and internet hype. We really didn't get going until 1996. In a sense we're more subtle and don't fall for the hype and do things at our own speed." Other reasons for the relatively slow European internet roll-out were comparatively low personal computer ownership rates and high local phone charges, Champion said. He tipped operators such as UUNet Technologies Inc of the US, Global One, the venture linking Deutsche Telekom, France Telecom and Sprint Corp, and the AT&T Unisource telecoms grouping to emerge as major competitors in the growing European market. -- Keiron Henderson, Amsterdam Newsroom +31 20 500 5000
GCAT	France expressed horror on Friday after a bomb killed up to four people in a cafe in Tel Aviv and urged all sides in the Middle East to show restraint to prevent further violence. "The French government learned with horror and consternation of the heinous attack that has just been committed in Tel Aviv. It expresses it sympathy to the families of the victims," the Foreign Ministry said in a statement. It also voiced concern over violence in Hebron and Jerusalem, where Palestinians are protesting against the construction of a disputed Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem. "The government also expresses its concern and dismay in the light of the serious incidents in Jerusalem and Hebron," the statement said. "It launches an appeal for reason to triumph over passion and to avoid all acts, measures or remarks that could aggravate the situation and increase tension," the statement said. "The logic of peace and concertation can and must triumph," it said.
GCAT	POSSIBILITY OF ANOTHER OFFICIAL RATE CUT LOOMS A slight rise in the official unemployment rate to 8.8 percent has prompted speculation that the Reserve Bank will again cut official interest rates. Figures out today show an extra 40,000 people joined the ranks of the unemployed last month, despite a fall in the participation rate. Senior economist with BT Australia, Rory Robertson, says these figures, and other recent economic indicators, demonstrate how difficult it is for the economy to improve. Mr Robertson says economic data remains weak, and the market is putting immense pressure on the Reserve to again lower rates. Meanwhile, the Federal Opposition's employment spokesman, Martin Ferguson, says the rise in the jobless rate shows how badly the Government is failing unemployed people. Mr Ferguson says it appears as if some sections of the community are giving up hope. He says the Prime Minister needs to show leadership if the hard decisions on policies to encourage employment growth are to be made. - - - - BEAZLEY SAYS PM MUST GUARANTEE NEWCASTLE'S FUTURE The Federal Opposition Leader, Kim Beazley, has told a rally of workers in Newcastle it is Prime Minister John Howard's job to demand BHP continues steel-making in the city. Mr Beazley, New South Wales Premier Bob Carr and ACTU leader, Jennie George, have told workers pressure has to be maintained on BHP and the Federal Government to ensure a future for manufacturing in the region. BHP workers marched on the steelworks after the rally. Mr Beazley says its the Prime Minister's duty to ensure the future of manufacturing in Newcastle. - - - - MOORE: EFFORT REQUIRED TO COMBAT RACIST TAG FOR AUSTRALIA The Federal Government has backed a call for the tourism industry to take action to counteract damage to Australia's reputation caused by the racism debate. The Australian Tourist Commission believes comments by Independent MP, Pauline Hanson, will have negative long-term effects on how Australia is perceived, especially in Asia. Tourism Minister, John Moore, says the Government has made clear its position on Pauline Hanson's views, and it is up to all Australians to reinforce the nation's image as a friendly and welcoming country. Mr Moore has also accused some Asian interests of capitalising on the race debate in Australia. He says it sometimes pays Australia's competition as a tourist destination to play-up perceived racism in Australia. - - - - SEARCH FOR KERRY WHELAN HOMES IN ON NATIONAL PARK The search for clues to the disappearance of Kerry Whelan is focusing on an old mining area in the New South Wales southern highlands. The 39-year-old vanished from a carpark in Parramatta more than five weeks ago. Police say the search of the Morton National Park is in extremely rugged and dangerous terrain. So far today, nothing of value has been found. Tomorrow, police will start searching the 60 abandoned mines in the area, and police divers have been placed on stand-by. - - - - LESSONS FROM BLACKHAWK COLLISION WILL "MAKE ARMY MORE RESILIENT" The chief of the army says the Blackhawk helicopter disaster is a reminder of the dangers faced by young Australians responsible for defending their country. A memorial service in Canberra today marked the first anniversary of the collision near Townsville, which killed 18 servicemen flying a night-time anti-terrorism exercise. The ceremony, at the Royal Military College Chapel, is one of several being held around the country. Army chief Lieutenant General John Sanderson told the gathering there were many reasons not to forget the Blackhawk disaster. He said it will be a constant reminder of the demands placed on military personnel both in training and in war. Lieutenant General Sanderson said the memories and lessons may be hard, but they are lessons nevertheless which add to the resilience and strength of the Army. - - - - CRICKET: BICHEL'S ASHES TOUR OVER Fast bowler Andy Bichel's Ashes cricket tour has come to an end after a prolonged back injury, which has limited the Queenslander to bowling just five overs since the tour began. The Australian selectors will not call for a replacement. Bichel will remain in England on holiday with his wife, who arrived yesterday. Coach, Geoff Marsh, has told Channel Seven Jason Gillespie is unlikely to play in the second test at Lords, saying his inclusion after having torn his hamstring, would be too risky. -- Reuters Sydney Newsroom 61-2 9373-1800
