ECAT	Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin Wednesday lauded the state of the global economy, saying it was in better shape than it has been in a long time. In remarks before the annual meetings of the International Monetary Fund and World Bank, Rubin said "the fundamentals of the world economy look as solid as they've been for a long, long time." He said America too was enjoying solid growth with low inflation. "I believe that if we continue to follow the right policy path in this country, we can have solid growth and low inflation on balance over the long term."   Rubin told the gathering of 181 countries that much of the success in the recent period reflected what is now a widespread consensus on the best economic policies to follow. "That consensus is to open markets, not close them, free business to compete, not restrain them, reduce deficits, not sustain them, and invest publicly in people, infrastructure and other areas critical to future productivity," he said. He said the U.S. was committed to meeting its financial responsibilities to the multilateral lending organizations and pledged the administration's "fullest and upmost effort" to work with Congress to achieve that.   Rubin praised World Bank President James Wolfensohn and IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus for "lifting the fight against corruption to the top of the agenda." He called corruption a major impediment to economic development. Rubin also urged the IMF and Bank to work together to help shore up banking systems in emerging market economies, saying that too often banking problems undermine economic growth.
ECAT	Eleven economists polled by Reuters in a survey issued on Friday forecast an average 2.1 percent year-on-year rise in Danish consumer prices for March, down from February's 2.2 percent. The estimates ranged from 1.9 percent to 2.3 percent. The analysts foresaw the rise from February to March at an average 0.4 percent, with estimates in the +0.2-+2.7 percent range. There was no monthly rise in February. The estimates were based on the domestic calculation method. The national statistics office releases the Danish March CPI data based on both EU and domestic formulas on April 23. --Stig Pedersen, Copenhagen newsroom +45-33969659
ECAT	Honduras on Thursday announced deep budget cuts under a program designed to win new credits from the International Monetary Fund (IMF). The government agreed to trim its operating budget by 20 percent, saving some 450 million lempiras ($35 million) in 1997, even as this impoverished Central American country has been rocked by a series of strikes and social protests. "These measures are aimed at guaranteeing control over public spending and at a fiscal deficit of 3.5 percent of gross domestic product (GDP)," Central Bank President Hugo Pino told reporters. Honduras's budget deficit was 3.4 percent of GDP in 1996. The agreement clears Honduras to receive $120 million to $140 million in credits this year, Pino said. The loans are crucial considering the entire operating budget is $994 million. The agreement reached on Thursday came after the government and the IMF last week failed to reach a more stringent three-year spending plan for the government. Under that IMF-preferred plan, Honduras would have had to cut deficit spending to two percent of GDP in order to receive $200 million in IMF loans this year. Such deep cuts are political impossibile in a country where resources already are stretched to the breaking point. "That's just not possible considering the conditions that the country is in," Pino said. Even so, Honduran officials were hailing the more modest agreement as vital to the Honduran economy.
MCAT	Germany's IBIS DAX index of German shares ended the day in positive territory on Wednesday, but the prospect of further gains this week was ruled out by a market rendered jittery after a long period of record highs. "It's not particularly hectic out there at the moment, but then these are nervous times. We've got a meeting of the Federal Reserve next week and the British elections coming up to make everyone jittery," a trader said. The 30-share IBIS DAX index ended electronic trade at 3,305.72 points, up 16.13 points or 0.49 percent, while DTB DAX futures were up 13.5 points at 3,309 points. "The triple-witching later this week also makes the market very superficial and any gains tend to be based on movements in derivatives," the trader said. Traders said that weaker performances on Wall Street were also dampening sentiment, but said the current slow-down or correction was "not unhealthy". "People will pick up stocks on the way down," a trader said. Among shares in the news was the engineering group Preussag AG, which ended up 18 marks at 459.80 marks, as merger mania in the steel/engineering group lifted the share 4.07 percent. Focus has centred on the steel industry since Fried. Krupp AG's launched a 13.6 billion mark takeover for Thyssen AG. Since then Krupp has proposed cooperation talks with Thyssen. The news also boosted Mannesmann AG, which ended up 18.50 marks at 641.50 marks. A slightly weaker dollar at 1.68 marks also impacted on sentiment. Shares in German drugs group Schering rose initially after it revised its sales and profits forecasts for 1997, fell amid afternoon profit taking, but re-emerged to end the day up 5.20 marks at 162.30 marks.
