MCAT	The Athens bourse closed slightly higher on Friday with market watchers expecting stabilisation and active block trading to continue by end-96. "We see a market stabilisation. However, we expect a possible small decline in the share index, in the beginning of January. The public appers to be cautious," said Marietta Petropoulaki of ATE AEDAK. She added that she expects the stabilisation trend to continue in the first three months of 1997. "I expect January to be a month of moderate performance and the first signs of improvement to appear around March," said Petropoulaki. George Chrisochoidis, managing director of N. Chrisochoidis Securities, said he expected the stabilisation trend to continue. "The financial results of banks and several big Greek companies have been very impressive. Their dividend yields are expected to be high and their stocks quite attractive," Chrisochoidis said. As soon as the investment public regains confidence in the stock exchange, after audits on the Delta Securities scandal are completed, people will start reinvesting in stocks especially at current prices, he added. The Athens general share index closed up 0.14 percent or 1.34 points at 934.46 from Tuesday's 933.12. It opened at 932.85. Trading volume fell to 11.5 billion drachmas on volume of 5.3 million shares in active block trading. Block trades of Intertech, Alpha Leasing, National Investment Bank, Teletypos and National Bank took place. Losers led gainers 101 to 81 with 36 issues unchanged on 218 traded. Banks gained 0.89 percent, construction lost 0.25 percent while small caps declined 1.07 percent and investment shares dropped by 0.29 percent. The Merrill Lynch call spread warrant on OTE with a strike price of 3,800 drachmas was quoted at the same price at 569.00-587.00. Shares of OTE telecom the underlying, lost 20 drachmas at 4,205. The recently launched ING Baring Financial Products American style call warrant based on a basket of six bank stocks was quoted at $8.33-$9.33. The strike price is set at $99.60 and the warrants expire October 8, 1997. The Morgan Stanley Hellenic Blue Chip Warrant, which has a strike price of 100 marks, was quoted at 3,341-3,543 drachmas. --Margarita Sotiropoulou, Athens Newsroom +301 3311812-4
ECAT	Guatemala's trade deficit for the first three quarters of 1996 was $726 million, down 23 percent from the same period last year, Central Bank President Willy Zapata said Thursday. The deficit for the same period in 1995 was $944 million, Zapata told a news conference. Zapata said a 32 percent increase in the value of non-traditional exports so far this year is largely responsible for an increase in export income and the lower deficit. The value of cloth and thread exports during the first three quarters of this year increased by 64 percent over the same period in 1995. Cotton and cotton derivatives showed an increase of 176 percent. Honey and minerals both showed increases of over 200 percent. The total value of exports rose only 2.3 percent, to $1.58 billion, in the first nine months of 1996 from $1.54 billion in the same period this year. Zapata blamed international prices for the decreased value of most of Guatemala's traditional exports such as sugar, coffee and meat. Comparing the first three quarters of 1995 and 1996, export volumes have not decreased for bananas, coffee, sugar or petroleum. The value of coffee exports was off 17.3 percent despite a 23.6 percent increase in volume exported through September 1996, he said. A slowdown in Guatemala's economic growth has slowed imports, which also affected the trade balance, Zapata said. In the first nine months of the year, total imports were $2.31 billion compared to $2.49 billion in the same period in 1995. While imports of combustibles and construction materials increased, there was an 11.3 percent drop in imports of consumer goods and a 9.7 percent drop in imports of raw materials for industry and agriculture. --Fiona Ortiz, Guatemala City bureau, +502 251-5718
MCAT	Canadian government bonds were the top performing market in the week ended February 13 while a shaky Italian market registered the worst losses, according to Salomon Brothers data on Friday. Canadian bonds notched up a 1.20 percent return in the week and were up 0.81 percent in U.S. dollar terms at a time when the U.S. currency made advances against most major currencies. Canadian dealers said the domestic bond market was encouraged by strength in U.S. Treasuries but outperformed their neighbours who were swamped with supply. There was also some optimism ahead of a federal Canadian budget next week. Swiss bonds came in second with a 1.13 percent return in Swiss francs, while third-placed British gilts returned 0.99 percent in sterling. Italian BTPs were the only market in the main Salomons government bond index to show a loss in local currency terms, with investors losing 0.10 percent in the week. In dollar terms, Italian debt showed a 2.24 percent loss. Concerns about Italy's fiscal situation and residual worries about its progress towards European monetary union weighed on Italian debt, analysts said. The overall Salomon index was up 0.56 percent in local currencies and down 0.43 in dollar terms. After Canada's robust performance, the only other markets to make gains for dollar-based investors were U.S. Treasuries with a 0.69 percent return, Britain with 0.39 percent and Sweden with 0.31 percent. Except for Italy, most European bond markets turned in decent performances. Dutch debt returned 0.84 percent in the local currency, France and Denmark made 0.76 percent gains, Sweden made 0.73 percent, Belgium 0.71 percent, Spain 0.59 percent and German Bunds 0.58. Japanese government bonds turned in a relatively weak performance, showing a modest 0.11 percent return in yen and a 0.79 percent loss in dollar terms. Salomon's bond index is calculated using all government bonds with over one year to maturity, weighted for market capitalisation. Only bonds freely available to institutional investors and with a certain minimum amount outstanding are included. Returns take account of price moves and accrued interest. --Adam Cox, International bonds unit +44 171 542 6784
GCAT	Britain expressed grave concern on Thursday at the upsurge of violence on the West Bank and Gaza Strip and urged Israeli and Palestinian leaders to show "statesmanship" to halt the fighting. The Foreign Office said fighting, in which 33 Palestinians and 10 Israelis have died, had left the Middle East peace process in a precarious state. "Actions such as the opening of the tunnel along the Western Wall and the recent demolition of a Palestinian community centre in Jerusalem have cause suspicion and disquiet," the Foreign Office said in a statement. "We call on Israeli and Palestinian leaders to exercise the statesmanship required and to step back from confrontation and return to the past of trust and reconciliation." Reflecting the acute anxiety in Britain, Prime Minister John Major sent messages to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian President Yasser Arafat urging restraint. His office said he also telephoned Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and sent a message to Jordan's King Hussein. A Foreign Office spokesman referred to Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind's comments on Wednesday in which he expressed concern about the impact of the violence on the Middle East peace process. "It is very worrying, very disturbing," Rifkind told CNN. "It is going to be very, very important to give the reassurance and to give the signs of tangible progress that can reduce the temperature and get matters under an even keel." Rifkind said it was important that Netanyahu had met Arafat, establishing a personal relationship. But he said there was a need for progress in three crucial areas: -- opening up Palestinian areas sealed off by Israel with "very disturbing" economic consequences. -- redeployment of Israeli troops from the West Bank town of Hebron, as foreseen in interim peace agreements signed by the previous Israeli government. -- a resumption of Israeli-Syrian peace talks, crucial to a comprehensive settlement in the region. Rifkind said Britain had recognised a need for a "period of quiet reflection" for Netanyahu, who took office in June, to establish his government's position on a range of issues. But he added: "Now you can't have that going on indefinitely. There is a momentum to the peace process and I think there is now a renewed sense of urgency that Mr Netanyahu's government must spell out the Israeli position and actually enter into the negotiations in a constructive way. "I think that is what they want to do but I am not yet persuaded that they have clarified even in their own minds exactly what their strategic objectives might be."
CCAT	The Egyptian state on Sunday offered for sale by auction at least 200,000 shares in Egypt Company for Mechanical and Electrical Projects (KAHROMICA), 10 percent of the company's total equity. The shares on sale can be increased to a maximum of 1.8 million shares, representing up to 90 percent of equity, the state's Holding Company for Electric Power Distribution and Construction said in an announcement. New shareholders will be eligible for the cash distribution for the financial year 1996/7, which ends on June 30. It did not say how much the coupon would be. Sealed bids should be addressed to the head of the financial, administrative and economic affairs sectors at the holding company in Medinet Nasr, northeast of Cairo. The offer will close at noon (1000 GMT) on Thursday, May 15, said the holding company, which owns KAHROMICA. Misr International Bank (MIBank) and the brokerage firm International Investors will act as agents for the offer. More details are available from MIBank. $1 = 3.395 pounds -- Esmat Salaheddin+ 20 2 578 3290/1
