MCAT	Late Tuesday LME trading saw copper and aluminium spring to life, with both markets probing higher in the final minutes of the kerb to end firm. But the late uptick tended to disguise an otherwise drab day's trading, with volumes low-key and interest only patchy. Other metals were slow throughout the session, ttraders said. "Copper was bought late because it was obvious that it was going to be a good chart close. Ally (aluminium) got through resistance and then set off short covering," one floor trader said. The copper market spent most of the session just above $2,500, having recorded advances in early trade after a reasonable stock fall. The late jump took the the market to $2,514 a tonne, up $26. More significantly, the backwardation widened throughout the session, and was around $85, basis cash/threes, by the close, against under $70 on Monday. July onwards is looking tight, some traders said. Aluminium similarly saved its best till the end, with the market making a determined effort to wear down the resistance above $1,610, and last business was at $1,617, up $14 from Monday. Traders said aluminium was boosted by LME warehouse and IPAI producer stock falls today, as well as signs that the contango may have started to contract again. June date pricing takes place next Monday, and the contango could narrow back in to around $15 again soon, from a current $20. Nickel trading slowed during late afternoon, but prices remained steadier up to the kerb end. The market continues to watch for fresh developments at strikebound Inco, Sudbury, where the current stoppage could run into the annual summer holiday shut-downs, some traders said. Prices subsided from above $7,300, but still finished at $7,290, a $40 gain from the previous kerb. Zinc recovered some poise after Monday's correction to last week's run-up to 4-1/2 year highs, although the market is still some way off re-challenging its highs. Last trade was at $1,363, up $7 from yesterday. Tin ran out of upside impetus in mid-afternoon, and settled back under liquidation to close at $5,590, up $10. The market was also affected by a widening in the contango, although upcoming tightness may not be diffused yet. Lead business was featureless from the outset - hence little deviation from overnight levels. Prices closed at $640, against Monday's kerb close of $641. Alloy was quiet, and three months was indicated at $1,470/80 a tonne, little different from Monday. --Martin Hayes, London newsroom 44 171 542 8080
GCAT	Murders of children aged between seven and 16 in Brazil's biggest city Sao Paulo soared to 239 in the first five months of the year, a newspaper said on Saturday. A survey by Sao Paulo police found 91 percent of the victims were involved in the city's booming trade in crack and cocaine, daily Correio Braziliense said. "The number is impressive because in all of 1996, 337 children were murdered," said police inspector Elisabete Ferreira who heads a unit dedicated to crimes against minors. Eighty-five percent of the victims came from shanty-towns and most had dropped out of school. "In the streets they met other adolescents and learned to steal, to take and sell drugs and to join gangs," the police officer said. Of the 239 minors killed so far this year, 38 were girls and the survey found that an increasing number of them had been tortured and sexually abused before being murdered, Ferreira told the newspaper.
CCAT	Popular clothing retailer Gap Inc. posted record fourth quarter profits Thursday in line with Wall Street estimates. Gap earned $171.2 million, or 62 cents a share compared with $154.6 million, or 54 cents a share for the comparable year-ago period. Sales rose 10 percent to $1.67 billion from $1.52 billion. Analysts predicted the retailer would earn 62 cents a share, according to First Call. Gap, which owns Gap, GapKids, Banana Republic and Old Navy stores, said it opened 203 new stores in 1996, and plans to open at least 275 new stores this year. "Our results demonstrate the strength of our balanced portfolio of apparel brands, with Gap, Banana Republic and Old Navy all improving their profitability in 1996," said Millard S. Drexler, Gap Inc. president and chief executive officer. Analysts were pleased with the performance. "They are executing their retail business very effectively and they've had some very appealing merchandise that was attractive and sold at regular prices," said Richard Jaffe, analyst at Schroder Wertheim & Co. "A lot of things came together, the Old Navy business performed well and the apparel was absolutely on target." Jaffe said the record earnings may be hard to maintain but Gap could grow earnings in the mid-teens range. Gap's earnings per share have grown at a compound annual rate of 22 percent over the last three years and 21 percent over the last 10 years. Stacey Pak, an analyst at CS First Boston, also expects earnings will slow. "The first half of 1996 was so good ... that it's hard to beat that, it's hard to even meet that," she said. Experts said the company's long term propects are good given Old Navy's strong growth potential in the United States and the possibility of strong international growth for the overall company. For the year, Gap earned $152.9 million, or $1.60 a share, on sales of $5.28 billion. A year earlier it earned $354.0 million, or $1.23 a share, on sales of $4.39 billion. Drexler said the company was committed to boosting shareholder value through share repurchase programmes and growth in the core business. Gap stock fell $1 to $33.25 in early afternoon trading on the New York Stock Exchange. Analysts attributed the fall to profit-taking.
