MCAT	Slovenian shares slipped on Tuesday, continuing to correct after steep rises over the past three weeks, but traders said they were confident the market could resume its upward trend later in the week. "It was mostly domestic investors who were selling today, trying to realise their short-term profits," said Robert Rudolf, a trader at brokerage Moja delnica. The seven-share SBI index fell 15.33 points or 1.21 percent to 1,254.60. Overall, five shares fell, nine rose and one was steady, while another nine were untraded. "Compared to recent big jumps these declines over the past two days are very small," said Milos Pavlic, a trader at brokerage ABH. Turnover fell to 464.3 million tolars from 591.6 million. Bank SKB was the most actively traded share, firming 1.41 percent to 41,580 tolars on volume of 4,477 shares. Construction company GPG was the leading decliner, falling 4.88 percent to 7,800 tolars on volume of 10 shares. Preferred shares of bank Hipotekarna banka Brezice were the biggest gainer, firming 4.21 percent to 3,740 tolars on volume of 135 shares. -- Novica Mihajlovic, Ljubljana newsroom, 386-61-125-8439
GCAT	All 18 supporters of ousted minority party leader Megawati Sukarnoputri, detained here in a clash with the army on Saturday in Indonesia's second city, had been released by early Sunday, a party official said. Sucipto, head of the East Java branch faction of the Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) that still backs Megawati, condemned the attack on 500 party members who on Saturday marched on the offices their rival faction in Surabaya, East Java. "Those that came did not bring weapons. They came to protest because up to now the government has been ignoring the aspirations of the mass of PDI members in East Java," Sucipto told a news conference on Sunday afternoon. Party officials said six people were injured when the protest was dispersed by the troops on Saturday afternoon. The PDI split after a government-backed congress in June elected deputy parliamentary speaker Surjadi to head the Christian-Nationalist party, ousting Megawati, the popular daughter of Indonesia's founding president Sukarno. Megawati, who says the congress was illegal, maintains she is the party's rightful leader and she apparently still enjoys widespread support among party members. On July 27, police sparked the worst rioting in more than 20 years in Jakarta after they forcefully evicted Megawati supporters from PDI headquarters, sparking disturbances in which at least five people died. Protests by PDI party members opposing Surjadi's leadership have continued around the country since June with one group of Megawati supporters earlier this month marching on Surjadi's official residence in Jakarta and chaining its front gate. Sucipto denied the protestors had attacked the military and thrown stones at the troops dispatched to protect the offices of the Surjadi faction. "We were only throwing plastic bottles of water," said one. Political analysts say there is concern about stability ahead of next year's general election in May and the possibility of rising protests from disaffected PDI members.
CCAT	First National Bank Holdings Ltd said on Wednesday its sale of Protea Furnishers Ltd's debtors book back to that firm will result in a loss to the bank of around 50 million rand in the second half of the year. "The Profurn book has been sold...with effect from April 1, 1997. Resulting losses are estimated to be in the region of 50 million rand and will be reflected in the second half of the financial year," FNB said in a statement. It was announced last month that Profurn had repurchased its furniture financing business, including the debtors' book and staff, from FNB for about 270 million rand. The transaction sees FNB becoming Profurn's largest shareholder with a 22 percent stake. FNB, battling with hefty bad debts, last year also sold a portion of its FirstPref debt financing unit back to McCarthy Retail Ltd in December last year. The date of the transfer was April 1, 1997. FNB said on Wednesday losses in the FirstPref operation totalled 136.8 million rand. -- Johannesburg newsroom 27 11 482 1003
ECAT	AMBAC Indemnity Corp said Wednesday it qualified for bond insurance the following two municipal issues scheduled for competitive sale today: --Eaton County, Mich., $2.295 million water supply and sewerage district bonds. --Salem, Ore., $6 million general obligation bonds. --U.S. Municipal Desk, 212-859-1650
MCAT	London robusta coffee futures continued to drift lower as origins stepped up sales but light manufacturer and trade buying helped slow the descent. Traders said volume remained fairly modest as most major players, exhausted after a prolonged rally, were sidelined or scaling down their commitment. "The big boys are either out or trading on smaller scale," said one. Benchmark May finished $30 down at $1,735 a tonne after ranging between $1,728 and $1,765. Volume totalled 4,608 lots. There was some spread trading in May/Sept which changed hands at $10-$15. During the day, the London market showed little reaction after New York's arabica futures re-tested the 205.50 cents a lb on May, now seen as a major hurdle. "We are waiting on the States really. London sitting here, drifting slightly lower and volume is nothing special while people scratch their head to try to figure out what's going on," said one. New York's May continued its choppy session, trading at between 199 cents and 205.50 and not breaking either way. Technically the New York market remained bullish although it's a bit overdone. "I think the market is getting its breath and if it gets above 205.50 and closes above that, we could see more fund and spec buying coming in." Roaster interest in New York is dying a bit as roasters have either finished their fixings or are awaiting for much lower prices. With only a week left to go before the spot March contract goes off the board, its open interest was still relatively high at 1,131 lots -- or the equivalent of about 300,000 bags of coffee -- against certifiable coffee of 35,083 bags. While London's direction hinges on New York, any new rally in London is likely to be short-lived as fundamentally, robustas are over supplied. Technically, the market is running into layers of heavy resistance in place since the last major bull run in early 1996. But May has to come down to at least $1,650 or $1,600 to confirm the downward reversal. There were no fresh fundamental inputs but traders were keeping an eye on producers' talks due in London on March 22. Indonesia, part of a six-member Association of Coffee Producing Countries (ACPC) technical group, said on Wednesday the grouping should consider the interest of consumers following the sharp hike in bean prices. Ivorian Commodities Minister Guy-Alain Gauze reiterated that the grouping would abide by its decision to cut an extra 1.3 million bags of coffee in the first half of 1997. -- Jalil Hamid, London newsroom +44 171 542 4985
CCAT	Australian transport group Mayne Nickless Ltd said on Thursday that it was confident it would meet its plans for earnings before interest and tax (EBIT) for the full financial year to June 30.   Mayne earlier reported a net profit of A$43.14 million for the six months to December 31, down from A$50.06 million a year earlier. Earnings before interest and tax slipped 0.7 percent to A$101.4 million. Sales eased 6.3 percent to A$1.38 billion. "Our underlying EBIT has improved year on year, but for the latest half year we've booked higher goodwill charges due to an accounting standard change," managing director Bob Dalziel said. "Whilst reductions in our corporate overheads have been initiated, these have not been implemented as quickly as we expected, and have lagged behind the business divestments and restructuring that have occurred," he said.   "I remain optimistic, however, that overall EBIT plans for the year will be met," Dalziel said. Dalziel said the result was in line with the company's operating plans and reflected the restructuring of its European and Australian contract logistics and Australian time critical express groups which he said would continue through 1997. "Importantly, we are encouraged by the early signs from the restructuring of the Australian time critical express business," he said.   "As a consequence of this work we determined late last year to pursue a "get big" strategy in our selected markets." Dalziel said Mayne believed that significant size in each of the geographic markets in which it operated was fundamental. "Logistics in Europe is highly competitive and we have observed that there is a consolidation of the market taking place," he said. "This is reinforced by our investigation of possible acquisitions in France. In addition, out customers are increasingly looking for pan-European solutions and larger networks," he said.   "In November 1996 management, therefore, decided to explore all options ranging from acquisitions to the identification of a party who is pursuing growth in European logistics," he said. "To date we are encouraged by our assessments that we will be able to profitably participate in the consolidation process." Among the divisions, Health Care of Australia had revenue of A$342 million, up 50 percent on the prior corresponding period.   "The increase was partly attributable to a full half contribution from businesses that were part of Australian Medical Enterprises which the company acquired in October 1995, including St George Private Hospital in Sydney," Mayne said. Earnings before interest and tax totalled A$44 million, up 48 percent from a year earlier. Time critical express reported revenue of A$598 million, down three percent, largely due to the strength of the Australian dollar, Mayne said. EBIT fell 15 percent to A$24.66 million. Contract logistics reported revenue of A$444 million, down one percent, also due the dollar's strength, it said.   EBIT was flat at A$38 million. Mayne also announced that Optus Communications, in which it has a 25 percent stake, had earnings before tax of A$59 million for the period, up from A$7 million a year earlier. Mayne plans to float off or sell the stake. -- Sydney Newsroom 61-2 9373-1800
ECAT	Malaysia's broad monetary aggregate, M3, expanded by 22.7 percent year-on-year in 1996 against 22.3 percent in 1995, the central Bank Negara said in its annual report for 1996 on Friday. During the year itself, the M3 aggregate fell sharply due to a tightening of monetary policy. "M3 growth ended the year with 22.7 percent from a high of 27 percent at the end of March and April," the annual report said. Similarly, M2 growth moderated to 20.9 percent from a peak of 27.9 percent at the end of April, 1996, and 24 percent in 1995. However, M1 expanded at a faster 18.3 percent in 1996 against 11.7 percent in the previous year. "This is a rate (of M3 increase) we would feel uncomfortable with, particularly since it came from credit growth," said a spokesperson of Bank Negara at the annual report presentation. "We would be more comfortable if it is below 20 percent, but we don't do monetary targetting," she said. -- Kuala Lumpur newsroom (603-230 8911)
ECAT	Australian business conditions remained relatively subdued in the June quarter, consistent with underlying growth of 2.5 to three percent, the latest National Australia Bank (NAB) quarterly business survey has found. The NAB said that in aggregate terms, trading conditions improved slightly during the second quarter of 1997, but profitability performance deteriorated a little further and there was continued job shedding.   Conditions across sectors and states remain mixed, NAB said. "Construction, transport and storage and property services have turned around over recent quarters and are improving modestly," NAB chief economist Alan Oster said in a statement. Financial and personal and recreational services continued to perform relatively well, and there was a marked improvement in retailing mainly due to better trading conditions. "Manufacturing and wholesaling continue to perform poorly," Oster said, adding that mining, a previously good performer, had reported poor conditions in the quarter for the first time since late 1995.   On a state basis, Victoria and Queensland experienced small improvements, while Western Australia reported poor conditions for the first time since mid-1993. The weakest conditions continued to be experienced in South Australia, NAB said. The NAB survey also included a measure of current business conditions, and found it less optimistic than the traditional measure based on future expectations. In the June quarter, "actual" confidence was negative three, compared with expectations of 14 points in the previous survey. Confidence for the September quarter eased to 10 points, reflecting deterioration in small and medium sized firms.   The survey found conditions were expected to improve in the third quarter, but Oster noted that this may be too optimistic given current activity levels, continued de-stocking intentions and subdued forward orders. Employment fell in the quarter, against expectations. "Current labour shedding is also more pronounced in large businesses - with the latter indicating that further downsizing is expected over the next year," Oster said. Labour costs growth fell to 0.7 percent from over one percent, moderating in all sectors except construction and financial services.   However, there remain concerns about wage pressures over the next year in construction and transport and storage. About 40 percent of respondents covering about 70 percent of employees in the survey, expected to complete wage agreements in the next year, with wages expected to rise by 3.5 percent. Firms in construction anticipated outcomes of five percent or more. Overall, a weakish labour market is expected to prevent any generalised wage pressures, and firms anticipate sizeable productivity offsets in wage agreements. Further out, output and profitability conditions are expected to improve over the next year, but not employment.   Moderation in June quarter price pressures to 0.07 percent, from 0.24 percent in March, together with reported poor profitability levels indicated a continuing economy wide squeeze on margins, and pointing to a good quarterly inflation result NAB said. After the survey, NAB had lowered its GDP forecast for 1997/98 (July/June) to 3.25 percent from 3.5 percent. Although NAB expects the second half of calendar 1997 to be stronger than the first half, short-term weakness in activity is seen keeping the unemployment rate around 8.75 percent, before it falls progressively in 1997/98.   Inflation will remain subdued in 1997, but underlying inflation will be rising in 1998 and wage pressures were unlikely to fall below four percent, NAB said. NAB also said official interest rates were likely to be cut from their current 5.5 percent level in the next month, before heading moderating higher during 1998. -- Sydney Newsroom 61-2 9373 1800
GCAT	A man wielding a sledgehammer on Friday badly damaged the Auld Mug, the America's Cup yachting trophy that Team New Zealand won in 1995, police said. They said a man dressed in a suit walked into the Royal New Zealand Yacht Squadron in Auckland where the cup is housed, and went unchallenged to the room where the cup is displayed in a glass case. The man pulled out the sledgehammer and began striking the glass case in a frenzied attack, police spokeswoman Joanne Gibbs said. Gibbs said the man arrived at the squadron rooms at the Westhaven marina about noon, possibly with the sledgehammer hidden in his suit. "The next thing they know he is smashing at the cabinet the cup is in. He has been arrested and is helping us down at central (station) with our inquiries," Gibbs said. The man was slightly injured by broken glass from the cup cabinet. Police did not identify the man but described him as a Maori whom they believed to be some sort of activist. They did not say if any charges had been filed against him. A spokesman for the Royal New Zealand Yacht Squadron said the cup was badly damaged around the mid section. "It is quite extensively damaged to the main centre piece." No estimate of the damage was immediately available, but the cup was insured for US$2 million when it was held by the San Diego Yacht Club. Sir Peter Blake, who masterminded the Team New Zealand challenge to wrest the cup from the San Diego Yacht Club in May, 1995, was reported to be devastated by the attack. Club commodore John Heise said Sir Peter was "understandably shocked and dismayed, particularly that we have gone out of our way to make the cup available to New Zealanders who want to look at the cup". Other trustees had been inclined to lock it away. "We have taken the attitude that it is New Zealand's cup and New Zealanders can look at it. It is very disappointing that something like this can happen to it." Heise said it was sickening to see the badly damaged cup lying half in and half out of the case. The cup was likely to be sent back to the manufacturers, Garrards, in England, for repairs. He said the company apparently still had the original drawings of the trophy, which was made about 1850. Heise said until it was sent back to Garrards, it was impossible to say if the cup could be successfully restored. The Auld Mug is up for grabs again in the year 2000.
CCAT	United Airlines, a unit of UAL Corp, said Tuesday its December passenger load factor rose 1.6 points to 69.0 percent from 67.4 percent a year ago. It said available seat miles gained 3.6 percent to 13.76 billion from 13.28 billion, and revenue passenger miles advanced 6.0 percent to 9.49 billion from 8.95 billion.   Year to date, United's load factor rose 1.2 points to 71.7 percent from 70.5 percent in 1995. Available seat miles gained 2.8 percent to 162.65 billion from 158.24 billion, and revenue passenger miles increased 4.5 percent to 116.55 billion from 111.54 billion. ((-- Chicago Newsdesk 312 408-8787))
CCAT	Shares in Seondo Electric Co Ltd, a maker of emission control devices, went limit-up on prospects of good earnings as demand for environmental products  rises, brokers said. Seondo rose 4,900 won to its limit of 87,800 in morning trading.
GCAT	Indonesia's Foreign Minister Ali Alatas on Monday called for an emergency meeting of southeast Asian foreign ministers to discuss Cambodia, which is teetering on the brink of civil war. "I think there is a need for ASEAN foreign ministers to gather, even though only for a short period, to discuss the situation in Cambodia," he told reporters at parliament. Cambodia, together with Laos and Burma, is due to join the seven-nation Association of Southeast Asian Nations at the regular, annual meeting of foreign ministers in Kuala Lumpur last this month. But Alatas said he was trying to contact Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi, the current ASEAN chairman, "on possibility of ASEAN foreign ministers meeting on this issue". ASEAN currently comprises Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. Both Alatas and President Suharto called for an end to the fighting in Cambodia. "The president said the situation in Cambodia should be resolved peacefully and the parties involved should restrain themselves," Indonesia's ambassador-at-large Nana Sutresna said after meeting Suharto. Long simmering rivalry between Cambodia's co-prime ministers, former communist party chief Hun Sen and Prince Norodom Ranariddh, erupted into fighting in the capital at the weekend. Suharto also discussed Cambodia with visiting Japanese vice-foreign minister Kazuo Ogura. "We discussed the situation in Cambodia, and we hope ASEAN will be able to make a positive contribution in finding a solution to the problem," Ogura told reporters. Alatas said Indonesia was following developments in Cambodia with great concern and urged "all parties to immediately cease their recourse to armed force and to solve whatever problems they may have through dialogue". "We really think that the situation is quite serious, and we are frankly disappointed that despite the commitment and the assurances they have given to us, to ASEAN, this conflict still reaches this proportion," he said. He said any ASEAN agreement on Cambodia would come from a consensus between the member countries. "We see this problem as an internal matter which is a conflict between two parties, and ASEAN will decide its steps together," Alatas said.
ECAT	The Labor Department's Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) on Friday defended its key Consumer Price Index from criticism made late last year by a blue-ribbon commission. In a report responding to the Boskin Commission study, BLS researchers questioned several of its assumptions and rejected many of its conclusions point by point. The commission, headed by Stanford University economist Michael Boskin, concluded in December that the CPI overstates inflation by about 1.1 percentage point per year. In its response, the BLS charged the Boskin commission with making numerous inaccurate inferences based on faulty or incomplete data. The paper also noted that the BLS is engaged in several programs to improve the accuracy of the CPI. "The BLS specifically rejects several of the estimated quality or new goods biases, in cases where the commission presented new evidence," the BLS study's authors said. The paper was released at a hearing of the Joint Economic Committee of Congress, which had requested a BLS response to the Boskin report.   The BLS partially agreed with Boskin that the CPI's failure to account for switching between similar goods when prices move has artificially inflated the index. And it agreed that upper-level substitution bias adds about 0.15-percentage point to CPI annually. But the paper disagreed that lower level substitution bias adds up to 0.49 points a year. "The commission fails to mention several strong assumptions about the distribution of price changes that they implicitly use," the report stated. The BLS also disputed Boskin's assertion that unmeasured quality gains in new and improved goods add 0.61 percentage points annually to CPI. The BLS highlighted shelter, apparel and upkeep, and new and used cars -- which Boskin said together account for 0.16 of the 0.61 points -- citing lack of evidence and poor estimates. "In each of these cases, there are significant problems with the inferences drawn by the commission," the report said. Estimates of a 0.34-point bias in medical care and high-tech consumer goods involved "some degree of speculation and extrapolation," the BLS report continued.   In addition, the paper said its current experimental CPI, which uses a geometric rather than an arithmetic mean to account for substitution bias, lowers the growth of CPI by about 0.25 percentage points a year. The BLS agreed with Boskin's recommendation that CPI should be fashioned as much as possible as a cost-of-living index. Many key U.S. economic inputs, including tax payments and entitlement spending, are tied to CPI. But the paper asserted that current efforts to improve CPI would take years to bear fruit, and may never catch up with the mercurial U.S. economy. "The solutions to many CPI measurement issues ... must await methodological breakthroughs in economics or improved availability of data," the report concluded. ((-- Chris Stetkiewicz, 202-898-8377 ))
GCAT	Australian legspinners Michael Bevan and Shane Warne grabbed seven wickets between them to demolish the West Indies' batting lineup before tea on the first day of their fourth test match on Saturday. Left armed legspinner Bevan took four wickets in a startling 28 ball spell that utterly mesmerised a tentative and distracted West Indies middle and lower order. West Indies capitulated to be all out for 130 just over an hour after the lunch break, having gone to lunch at 82 for five on what was generally seen as a good batting pitch. This is the West Indies second lowest total against Australia at the Adelaide Oval since 1951/52, when they scored 105. It is their fourth batting collapse in a row on this tour. Australia made a solid start to their first innings and were 29 for no wicket at tea against a depleted West Indies pace attack. Bevan, in his first match as a recognised bowler, finished with four for 31. He has previously played as a batsman who bowled occasionally, but was selected for this match as a second spinner after a dramatic improvement this season. The 26 year old had started poorly, bowling too full and wide to the West Indies top order who were only too happy to drive him to the boundary. But once he found a good length, the West Indies just could not cope with his bouncy leg-spinners that approach medium pace on occasion. Warne was also in destructive form, taking the prize wicket of an in-form Brian Lara before lunch with his first ball to the left-hander, delighting a capacity crowd of over 20,000 at the tree-lined and sun-drenched Adelaide Oval. Warne took two wickets for seven runs in his first two overs, including that of Chivnarine Chanderpaul who has been the West Indies' most consistent batsman on tour. He finished with three for 42. The West Indies are expected to struggle to dismiss Australia cheaply on a pitch settling into a good batting wicket. Strike fast bowler Curtly Ambrose, the chief destroyer for the West Indies in their third test win in Melbourne, was forced to withdraw at the last minute after failing a morning fitness test with a strained groin. The West Indies have also lost paceman Kenny Benjamin, who returned earlier this month with a side strain. Ambrose and Benjamin have been replaced by Cameron Cuffy and Patterson Thompson, who have three test matches of experience between them. Australia lead the five test series 2-1 and only need to draw or win this match to retain the Frank Worrell Trophy, which they won in 1995 in the Caribbean when they were the first team to beat the West Indies in a test series for 15 years.
CCAT	Brokerage UBS lowered its recommendation on French glassmaker Saint-Gobain to 'sell' from 'neutral' and cut its earnings estimates for the group, fund managers said on Friday. UBS judged Saint-Gobain's 1996 results disappointing and believes the stock overvalued, they said. Natwest Sellier maintains its "hold" recommendation on Saint-Gobain after the group announced 1996 results in line with its expectations, one broker said. It believes that despite a "sharp improvement" in other sectors, the poor situation of the building sector will hurt glass activity. Dupont Denant maintains its "overperform" recommendation" on the stock. Saint Gobain said on Thursday 1996 net attributable profit would be 4.32 billion francs, up slightly from 4.21 billion last year. Saint Gobain was off 0.24 percent to 846 francs at 1055 GMT. -- Paris newsroom +331 4221 5432
ECAT	South Korea's finance ministry said on Wednesday it would try to minimise damage to the financial markets as a result of troubles at the Kia Group by maintaining flexible money supply. "We will supply money flexibly lest Kia's troubles cause concerns within the financial markets," a ministry statement said. Repurchase agreements would be used to ease instability in the short-term money market. The central bank supplied one trillion won through repurchase agreements on Tuesday and an additional 500 billion won on Wednesday.   The ministry also said it would strengthen its financial support to Kia's subcontractors. "We will ask financial institutions to extend repayments of loans to Kia's subcontractors," the ministry statement said. The central bank would raise funds through sales of monetary stabilisation bonds to support the subcontractors' operating expenses On Tuesday, local banks launched a rescue of the Kia Group, which ran into financial troubles due to slumping sales in its carmaking flagship and heavy investments in its steel unit.
ECAT	Italian Treasury Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi said on Saturday that consumer price inflation was now firmly in a range of 1.5 percent to 1.8/1.9 percent year-on-year. "Inflation is now clearly in a range of 1.5 to 1.8/1.9 percent," Ciampi told reporters as he left to attend a meeting of Group of Seven finance ministers. Economists estimated that Italian consumer prices would rise 1.5 percent year-on-year in June after the release of preliminary inflation data by five sample cities on Friday.
ECAT	Venezuelans will soon begin to reap the benefits of improved economic growth has the improvements of the the past year begin to reach them, Planning Minister Teodoro Petkoff said. "Most people still haven't begun to climb the slope, but they're not going to start sliding down it either," Petkoff said in an interview on Union Radio. "People have put their first foot on the hill...over the course of the year they'll begin to climb."   Petkoff was speaking on the eve of the first anniversary of President Rafael Caldera's speech on April 15 last year when he launched a tough package of IMF-sponsored reforms, called Venezuelan Agenda. The reforms -- backed by a fortunate spike in international oil prices -- have led to falling inflation, rising international reserves, renewed international confidence and improved growth prospects, with the economy set to grow 3.3 percent this year after shrinking 1.6 percent in 1996. But the measures also caused rising unemployment and a series strikes that rocked Venezuela earlier this year.   "This year will see significant wage increases and, shortly, a new higher minimum wage. People will soon be feeling better in their pocketbooks," Petkoff said. As part of a ground-breaking reform of the crumbling social security system now under congressional discussion, all Venezuelan workers will soon receive advances on accumulated severance payments. The payments, called "prestaciones", or literally "borrowings", work as a sort of pension scheme under which workers receive a lump sum when they leave a job. The amount depends on the number of years worked. Petkoff added that, despite the fall in March inflation to 1.6 percent -- the lowest in five years, inflation was still too high. "...it has to come down further, although if you compare it with 12.6 percent in May last year, it's pretty good," he said. Central Bank officials have said that pending salary increases will add some five percentage points to year-end inflation, officially targeted at 35 percent. ((-- John Paul Rathbone, Caracas newsroom, 582 505 2600))
GCAT	South Africa's cabinet will decide within weeks whether to challenge Egypt and arch-rival Nigeria for a permanent seat on the U.N. Security Council, Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad said on Thursday. Pahad told Reuters South African envoys from New York, Vienna, Geneva and Addis Ababa, seat of the Organisation of African Unity (OAU), had met recently to discuss the expected contest for Africa's first permanent seat on the Security Council. "We will put options to the ministers and they will have to take the final decision, but one of the options will be whether South Africa should contest the seat and the cabinet will have to decide that very soon," he said in an interview. A U.N. working group is discussing reforms including the proposed expansion of the 15-nation Security Council, of which the United States, Britain, Russia, China and France are the permanent members with the right to veto council decisions. The United States has backed the inclusion of Germany and Japan and three permanent seats for the developing world, but has not said which Third World countries should join. The OAU has called for two permanent seats for Africa alone and an additional two seats that will rotate among other countries on the continent. The existing permanent members have all said they would not tolerate any dilution of their veto powers, but have not agreed what powers the new members should have. "As part of the OAU and the Non-Aligned Movement, we support the position that there should be no differentiation between permanent members. Either the veto must go completely or all members should have the same veto powers," said Pahad. He said the OAU had asked members not to declare their interest in Security Council seats until an internal discussion was complete, but that Nigeria and Egypt had publicly announced their intention to vie for the seat. South Africa has been at loggerheads with Nigeria since President Nelson Mandela called for sanctions against military leader Sani Abacha's government after the execution of writer Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other democracy campaigners in 1995. Diplomatic sources in South Africa and Zimbabwe said recently Nigeria was opposing South Africa's bid to host the Olympic Games in 2004. "There is a very strong feeling in international circles that if there are one or two seats for Africa, South Africa should contest," Pahad said. "But we have to look at the implications in terms of human resources, financial implications and general responsibility. The cabinet will have to decide whether we are willing to take on these very significant obligations." Pahad, who is generally far more visible than elderly Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo, said a permanent seat would commit South Africa to greater financial and manpower contributions and could involve greater involvement in peace-keeping operations. "Of course, being a permanent member of the Security Council also means you're in the big league and advantages come with that in terms of interacting with the major powers on issues of international importance and the ability to influence, if necessary, important decisions," he said.
ECAT	Australian Treasurer Peter Costello said on Wednesday that it was the government's policy to keep interest rates low. The Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) earlier announced a 0.5 percentage point reduction in official cash interest rates to 5.0 percent, the fifth rate cut in a year.   "Having got interest rates down, I can assure you it is very much part of our policy to keep them there," Costello told reporters. He said the rate cuts announced in late 1996 were still working their way through the economy and that the benefits of the remaining two rate cuts were yet to materialise. The central bank began lowering rates last July, with two cuts in the final few months of 1996, one on May 23 this year, and again on Wednesday. Each time it reduced the official cash rate by 50 basis points.   "Interest rates work their way through the economy on a 12 month to 18 month delay," Costello said. "What that means is that we are now - business is now -- just starting to feel the benefits of rate reductions that were occurring in the latter part of last year," he said. -- Sydney Newsroom 61-2 9373-1800
CCAT	TeleCheck Services, a unit of First Data Corp, said Saturday that same-store sales rose 3.6 percent on Friday compared to the day after Thanksgiving a year ago. The day after Thanksgiving is traditionally the busiest day in terms of shopping traffic.   "One day does not make a season, however, and with this good start, TeleCheck anticipates a 2-to-4-percent same store sales gain during the entire holiday shopping period," William Ford, TeleCheck's senior economic advisor, said in a news release. Sales rose 9.3 percent in the Southwest, 5.6 percent in the Mid-Atlantic region, 4.4 percent in the West, 3.9 percent in the Southeast and 3.3 percent in the Midwest, TeleCheck said. Sales in the Northeast fell 3.9 percent, according to the survey of checks written at 15,000 TeleCheck subscribers, TeleCheck said. The figures are not adjusted for inflation. --Reuters Chicago newsdesk, 312-408-8787
