ECAT	The Cahners Business Confidence Index (CBCI) rose to 67.4 in August from 65.3 in July, according to a report by Cahners Economics. "Business confidence has responded favorably to the likelihood the Fed will remain on the sidelines for several months to come," the report said. Sixty-nine percent of the 400 manufacturers surveyed rated current business conditions as "good/excellent." Four of seven CBCI components rose in August. The employment portion climbed farthest, gaining 2.7 points to stand at 67.5.   Readings of inventories, production and marketing spending increased in August as well. Of the three individual indices that fell, capital spending turned in the greatest decline, slipping 2.2 percent to 75.2 in August. More than 60 percent of respondents said policies aimed at economic growth should be the presidential candidates' first economic priority, the report said. Fewer than 20 percent of respondents said controlling inflation should be first priority, it said. The CBCI is computed monthly from a telephone survey of 400 senior and mid-level managers in the manufacturing sector. --Scott Gerlach, 212-859-1868
ECAT	Employers have grown more confident about taking on new workers in coming months, reflecting their outlook for steady economic growth in 1997, according to a survey of business economists released Sunday. In a quarterly survey of 127 members of the National Association of Business Economists, about 42 percent said their companies plan to increase hiring over the next six months. That's up from 24 percent in October's survey. Roughly half of the economists said they expect the economy to continue growing at an "average" pace, compared with 44 percent in the previous survey. NABE President Mark Dadd said the survey did not ask for specific growth forecasts but he pegged "average growth" at about 2.5 percent a year. "This is a pretty solid rate of growth for this stage in the expansion," Dadd told Reuters. "The expansion looks secure." Another 42 percent of those surveyed forecast sluggish growth, while the rest were evenly split between strong growth and recession. The survey of the group's members, who include economists from a broad range of U.S. companies, found that demand for products and services increased markedly in the fourth quarter and more than compensated for a third quarter slowdown. Despite the higher demand, businesses have had difficulty raising prices in a competitive business environment, the survey showed. Only 21 percent reported increased selling prices for their goods and services, while 14 percent reported falling prices. Continued shortages of skilled labour were reported at about half of the firms surveyed. Despite the lengthier expansions of recent years, most of the economists surveyed "still firmly believe in business cycles," the group said. "Business economists don't believe the business cycle is dead, it's merely slumbering," said the NABE's Dadd, who is also chief economist for AT&T Corp.
MCAT	LIFFE coffee futures regained some strength after early sharp falls to end Tuesday mixed with some nearbys returning to the positive territory. Traders said a technical upward reversal in New York after Monday's heavy sell-off also inspired renewed buying in London in the afternoon. "We may have seen lower levels in New York. The market needs a short-term correction on the upside," said one trader. London's benchmark May was driven to an intraday low of $1,610 a tonne before staging a rebound to a peak of $1,708. It closed just $8 up at $1,698. Other traded positions were $40 down to $12 up. The market had earlier failed to meet its pre-opening expectation of $100-$200 down based on the steep decline on the New York arabica futures overnight. Roasters stepped up buying in the morning as prices made their way lower. Jobbers were seen on the selling side but they retreated as the market turned around. "This initiated speculative buying and roasters also paid up," said one trader. "Funds which had been selling in last few days were not willing to sell at higher prices." The market's volume reached a modest at 5,099 lots. Active May/July switches were traded from $3 to $12. On the charts, May faces a key support at $1,600 and the upside target is seen at the double top of $1,820-$1,825. Broker GNI said earlier on Tuesday the recent retail price increase by major U.S. and European roasters could be a dampener to the recent explosive rally in bean prices. "We have been saying for some time that prices are due to fall due to the recent roaster price increases," it said in a commentary. "The question now is how far can they fall before trade buying comes in and the specs start going long ahead of the (Brazilian) frost season." The U.S. Green Coffee Association data released after the New York market had closed on Monday showed a larger-than-anticipated rise of 204,000 60-kg bags to 1.54 million bags in February from January. The market had anticipated an increase of 50,000 to 100,000 tonnes. -- Jalil Hamid, London newsroom +44 171 542 4985
MCAT	*Dlr/yen down but above 112.90 low. Treasury's Rubin supports strong dollar after early Bentsen remark knocks below 113. *Dealers see good appetite for dollar/yen at lows, Japan public fund rumored bidding for dollars on way down. *Dlr/mark, Swiss lose ground after early long liquidation. *U.S. assets turn down, hurting dollar, despite good jobs data. The dollar closed lower against most leading currencies after former United States Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen said a stronger dollar could harm U.S. exporters. Bentsen, in an interview with Reuters Financial Television, said he was "comfortable" with the dollar's current strong exchange rate. But, referring to the dollar's value against the yen, he added: "If it continues to rise and goes substantially above this, of course, it puts us at a competitive disadvantage. I would prefer not to see it increase in value." After briefly trading below the important 113 yen threshold, the dollar recovered somewhat when Robert Rubin, the administration's current Treasury chief told reporters at a press conference "we believe in a strong dollar." "Bentsen's comment pushed it lower but then Treasury Secretary Rubin made a comment which took the dollar back up," said Kisoo Park, senior foreign exchange dealer at Bank of Boston. "I would presume Rubin carries more weight." The dollar ended at 113.35/45 yen on Friday, down from 113.67/70 yen at the open and at 1.5135/45 marks, off from 1.5185/90 marks. Bentsen served as Treasury Secretary for the first two years of the Clinton Administration. During his tenure at the Treasury, many currency traders thought he favored an informal cap on dollar/yen around 113. Bentsen gave some the impression of adhering to a policy of benign neglect of the dollar, believing a weaker U.S. currency would force trade concessions from Japan and spur sales of U.S. goods there. But while traders said Bentsen's remarks may have a fleeting impact on the market, they come amid a recent chorus of complaints about the dollar's strength. "The only thing it does signal is that there is still a body of opinion in the United States that does think the dollar is too strong at the moment," said Chris Iggo, an international economist at BZW/Barclays Bank in New York. Many large U.S. coroporations, particularly the three largest U.S. auto manufacturers, have recently voiced concern over the damage a strong dollar could inflict on foreign demand for U.S. made goods. The dollar was lifted earlier against the mark and extended its recent advance against the Swiss franc to a 20-month high at 1.2778 Swiss after a tame report on U.S. payroll growth briefly hoisted the U.S. bond market. The Labor Department showed that the unemployment rate remained steady at 5.2 percent, while non-farm payrolls increased 210,000 in October, after falling 35,000 in September. The data was very close to Wall Street forecasts. "The dollar got a slight boost from the bonds, but I don't think the bonds turning (lower) made the dollar go down," said Mark Remigio, a vice president at Bank of Tokyo Mitsubishi. The dollar could not hang on to gains versus the mark, which firmed in Asian trade after a German central banker, speaking in Singapore, said there was no need for a mark-damaging reduction in German interest rates. The dollar fell to 1.2690/00 Swiss francs from 1.2715/25 and to Canadian $1.3335/40 from C$1.3366/71. The pound touched $1.6445, its highest level since March 1995, but closed at $1.6360/70, off from $1.6373/80. The Australian dollar stood a $0.7889/94, up from $0.7883/88 at the open. -- Alden Bentley 212 859 1667
MCAT	Shares ended higher in massive volume on Tuesday with the HEX index tacking on more than two percent after Nokia powered up on its report of sharply higher first-quarter earnings, brokers said. The general HEX index rose 2.51 percent to 2,930.53 points and volume was a very lively 1.26 billion markka, 71 percent of which was in Nokia. The FOX derivatives and portfolio benchmark rose 2.33 percent to 1,019 points. "This has been Nokia's day," one broker said. Nokia added 20.90 markka, or more than six percent, to close at 321.90 markka. Both Nokia shares were traded heavily, with the combined volume rising above 900 million markka, to account for more than 70 percent of total bourse turnover. A higher open from U.S. stocks and bonds, and for Nokia on Wall St, bolstered sentiment late in the session, brokers said. "This now looks very bullish. If U.S. bonds stay up there and stocks follow them, then tomorrow could be quite a day," one broker said as the U.S. markets opened higher with help from Q1 employment cost data. Forestries, banks and metal shares added width to the rise, with the sub-indices up 1.07 percent, 4.06 percent and 0.98 percent respectively. Steel group Rautaruukki added 2.70 to end at 46.50 in heavy 65 million markka volume after it yesterday set its share offering price at 42.00 markka per share. As the market closed, Rautaruukki said it would up its public offering from four million shares to 7.4 million. Insurer Pohjola ended 1.00 markka higher at 148.00, helped by news that it was pursuing its plans to absorb Suomi insurance by buying Suomi's Salama shares, brokers said. The largest banking group Merita closed 0.80 markka higher at 17.20 after touching 17.20 in fairly lively trade, helped by the downward shift in interest rates late in the session, brokers said.
ECAT	Singapore has revised its forecast of 1996 gross domestic product (GDP) growth down to about six percent, and the city state registered annual growth of 3.2 percent in the third quarter, Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong said on Tuesday. The Ministry of Trade and Industry (MTI) had previously forecast 1996 growth at between seven to eight percent, and in the first and second quarters the economy grew at annual rates of 11.4 percent and 7.5 percent respectively, according to revised figures released by Lee. Lee was speaking at a trade awards ceremony.   Lee said MTI expects 1997 growth of between five to seven percent, assuming the key electronics industry picks up in second half 1997, as the industry consensus forecasts. A recent Reuters poll of 11 economists had found their forecasts averaging 6.4 percent growth for 1996 GDP. Most expected growth in the third quarter to average slightly over 3.0 percent year-on-year. Export-driven Singapore has been hit by a worldwide slowdown in the critical electronic sector, which accounts for 44 percent of value added in Singapore manufacturing.   "A major reason for this downturn is the weak performance of manufacturing, particularly the electronics industry and related supporting industries," Lee said. He said several other manufacturing industries are also weak, including ship-repair, printing, petrochemicals and pharmaceuticals. Lee said the MTI assessed the current slowdown as cyclical rather than secular. "It reflects a cyclical slowdown in external demand, rather than structural problems in the Singapore economy."   He said: "Externally, there are also positive signs that the current slowdown will not be too severe or prolonged," citing expected growth in the United States, Japan and China and an industry consensus the electronics slowdown has hit bottom. Given that assessment, Lee said there was no need for drastic policy adjustments, although the situation should be monitored. "Meanwhile we should maintain an even course, and accept slower growth for a few quarters until external demand picks up again," Lee said.   "The current slowdown has not changed our longer term assessment -- that Asia is set to boom for the next 20 years, that we are well placed to take advantage of this regional prosperity, and that we can aim to grow by 6-8 percent per year over the next decade," Lee said. -- Singapore newsroom 65-8703080
CCAT	Shares in Ascend Communications Inc dropped by nearly two points in after-hours trade Tuesday after the networking solutions company released earnings results that were under expectations, traders said. Dealers said Ascend traded at 52 after the bell, below an unofficial close of 53-7/8. The company posted second quarter earnings of $0.31 per share before merger costs, compared with $0.23 per share for the year ago period. According to First Call, analysts' consensus forecast the earnings results would come to $0.36 per share.   Also causing commotion after the bell was Intel Corp, the world's largest semiconductor manurfacturer. Dealers said Intel traded at 83 after-hours, well above an unofficial close of 80-29/32, also after releasing second quarter earnings performances. The company reported earnings of $0.92 per share on revenues of $6.0 billion, compared with $0.59 per share on revenues of $4.6 billion for the year-ago period. Analysts had forecast that Intel would post earnings of $0.90 per share.   Elsewhere, Amgen Inc edged downward by 1/4 point, hampered by second quarter earnings of $0.72 per share, compared with $0.64 for the same period in 1996. Dealers said the biotechnology company's stock price fell to 57 during a busy after-hours trading session, down from 57-1/4 at the U.S. market close. "It's still pretty heavy after the bell," a trader said late in the session. The accelerated trading followed an equally busy day on Wall Street. The Dow Jones Industrial average jumped 53 points to close at 7976, while the Nasdaq Composite added 18 points, rising to 1542. The New York Stock Exchange said session one volume was 40,400, compared with 104,600 on Monday. Session two volume fell to 629,189 from 3,801,339 the previous day.
