GCAT	A century by captain Shivnarine Chanderpaul frustrated the Indian bowlers after they had made a mess of Guyana's upper order batsman during the second day of their four-day match on Saturday. Guyana had been reduced to 95 for five when the West Indies test batsman came in. An unbeaten 103 by Chanderpaul allowed Guyana to reach 214 for six at the close in reply to India's first innings total of 341 all out. Chanderpaul and Vishal Nagamootoo, who was not out 20 at the close, added 83 runs in an unbeaten seventh wicket partnership. Dodanarsiah Ganesh was the pick of the Indian bowlers with three for 46 off 15 overs. Earlier, India, resuming at 294 for five overnight had, not for the first time during their tour, collapsed after appearing to be in a dominant position, losing their last five wickets for only 47 runs. Paceman Reon King, who took three wickets on Friday, was the scourge of the Indian batsman, taking a further four to finish with figures of seven for 82.
CCAT	Only eight percent of German retailers plan to lengthen their store hours in November to take advantage of a more liberal law, according to a survey by a business information agency. Of the 1,800 retailers surveyed, 37 percent plan not to extend their hours at all, while the remainder will wait and see how things develop, said Helmut Roedl, president of the Verband der Vereinte Creditreform. The change will do virtually nothing to create new jobs, Roedl said. Most retailers plan to use part-time employees to meet greater demand, rather than hire new full-timers. The German government, hoping to boost the economy, enacted a more liberal shop opening hours law in June, over objections from the industry and unions. -- Terence Gallagher, Bonn newsroom, 49 228 26097150
MCAT	This week's active U.S. Plains feedlot cattle sales broke week-to-date record high levels, according to the U.S. Agriculture Department. Texas Panhandle/western Oklahoma feedlots by Wednesday had posted a week-to-date figure of 141,600, topping the previous record of 136,800 set for the week ended February 22nd this year, USDA said. Kansas feedlot sales for the week through Wednesday were 118,800, above the 115,059 level set the week ended July 28, 1995, according to USDA. Daily record highs remained intact despite Wednesday's active sales. The record high level for daily sales in the Panhandle area is 104,800 set February 22 this year, and the daily record high in Kansas at 88,000 was set last September. There were 96,600 head reported sold Tuesday in the Panhandle and 70,100 in Kansas. Cattle marketing weeks run from Friday through Thursday and one reason for this week's big volume was large purchases of cattle Friday last week left over from the previous week's showlists, USDA marketing sources said. About 20,000 head were sold in the Panhandle area on that day and 35,000 in Kansas. Cattle sales on Fridays are typically light, sources said. --Bob Janis, 312-983-7347--
MCAT	Interbank rates were mostly unchanged on Monday with very few borrowers and lenders in the market, dealers said. Market liquidity had improved further following maturities of a 420-million ringgit long term government bond issue and a 500-million ringgit Bank Negara bills issue last week, but borrowing by some large banks, which were believed to be short of funds, had kept rates steady. "I don't see much movements over the next few days. There's no new Bank Negara bills issue or maturity this week," said a dealer with a Malaysian bank. One-week money was at 6.50/90 percent against 6.5/7.0 on Friday and three-week was unchanged at 7.10/20 percent. One-month money at 7.25/30 percent, three-month at 7.30/35 and six-month at 7.35/40, were all unchanged. Dealers said maturity of a 900-million ringgit long term government bond issue on May 15 could exert some pressure on rates again. "If the issue is not rolled over, rates may come off again," said another local bank dealer. There have been rumours that the central bank will announce a fresh Malaysian Government Securities (MGS) issue. The overnight interbank rate is expected to trade between 6.0 and 7.0 percent. It closed on Friday at 6.5 percent. The overnight rate shot up to 8.7 percent last Wednesday due to borrowing by big banks. Interest rate futures on the Malaysia Monetary Exchange were also steady. At 0300 GMT, the benchmark three-month Kuala Lumpur Interbank Offered Rate (KLIBOR) December contract was unchanged at 92.66, or an implied yield of 7.34 percent. June and September were untraded. -- Syed Azman (603-206 2323) .
GCAT	U.S. special envoy Bill Richardson will fly to Paris on Wednesday to consult with France about the "endgame" in Zaire, as rebel forces approach the capital Kinshasa, a State Department spokesman said on Tuesday. Richardson, U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, has been shuttling between the Zaire factions and neighbouring countries trying to avert a bloody end to the Zaire conflict. He was in South Africa on Tuesday for talks with Vice President Thabo Mbeki. "We want to make sure we're coordinating with the French during the endgame in Zaire," State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told Reuters. "It's only a matter of time. The writing's on the wall," said Burns, who was accompanying Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on a trip to Mexico by President Bill Clinton. The rebel forces of Laurent Kabila say they are less than 50 miles (85 km) from Kinshasa and have appealed for government troops to surrender to avoid a bloody takeover of the capital. Diplomatic sources say the front line is more like 125 miles (200 km) from Kinshasa. Zaire President Mobutu Sese Seko, whose resignation the rebels have demanded, will travel to Gabon for an African mini summit on Wednesday but a spokesman said he would return to his capital two days later. U.S. officials say their differences with France over Zaire have narrowed in recent weeks as Paris has moved away from its long-standing support for Mobutu. Despite seizing the diplomatic initiative by sending Richardson to Zaire, Washington has appeared anxious to pay homage to France's traditional role in the region. France on Tuesday expressed deep concern over rebel threats to take Kinshasa by force if necessary and renewed its appeals for a peaceful transition.
ECAT	The Australian economy was mixed, with some areas including the manufacturing sector flat, Prime Minister John Howard told Perth radio. He had been asked about interest rates and whether the economy was weak.   "The economy is mixed. There are some areas that are flat, some areas of manufacturing are flat," Howard said. "Parts of the service industries are good; there are some signs of a housing and construction recovery but areas of manufacturing are flat and retailing, to say the least, is modest," he said.   Asked about the possibility of the Reserve Bank cutting interest rates following its monthly board meeting today, Howard said, "If the Senate passed our budget intact that would help the interest rate climate." "Having said all of that prime ministers always like to see low interest rates, but what happens with monetary policy is ultimately a matter for the Reserve Bank," he said. Asked about claims that the economy was weak and a rate cut was needed, Howard said: "The things that drive interes rate levels are myriad -- the level of inflation, the rate of wage increases, as well as activity and views about employment."   "They are all things that have to be taken into account and I don't think it probably helps the process of orderly decision making for me to be talking about what ought to happen with interest rates tomorrow," Howard said. On Monday, opposition Labor Treasury spokesman Gareth Evans said it was clear economic activity was very subdued and the Reserve Bank should cut interest rates immediately to kickstart jobs growth. Official cash rates were last cut by 50 basis points to 7.0 percent on July 31. -- Sydney newsroom 61-2 9373 1800
ECAT	Investors have largely ignored the efforts to liberalise the economies of the 12-member Southern African Development Community (SADC), officials said on Wednesday. Now the trade group, struggling for a place in the global market, is looking beyond the recipes of the World Bank and International Monetary Fund (IMF) for improvement. "Most SADC member states have implemented policies which according to the World Bank and the IMF are necessary for the positive contribution of foreign investment to economic development of the SADC countries," said Phakamani Radebe, Deputy Director of SADC's Finance and Investment Sector Coordination Unit (FISCU). "What we have now learned is that although liberalising our economies is essential, in itself it is not sufficient, and SADC countries need to build domestic and regional productive capacity as the basis for their own long-term development," he added. Radebe believes SADC needs to find out why the desired level of direct foreign investment has not been achieved. Fresh from preliminary discussions in advance of the 1997 SADC consultative conference, being held in the Namibian capital Windhoek, Radebe said most regional economies still suffered from lack of basic infrastructure and from a narrow production base. "The current environment in the SADC region is too weak to guarantee that the region will benefit from globalisation", he said. This year's conference, which formally starts on Thursday, will put a special emphasis on improving productivity. "Productivity levels and trends will be crucial in attracting foreign investment and enhancing the competitive edge of southern African companies", SADC Executive Secretary Kaire Mbuende said. SADC's finance and investment sector has conducted three studies to help lay the foundation for further development in the region. These include a study of macroeconomic policies in the region, the possibility of a regional bank or financial mechanism to close the funding gap when donor money dries up, and the promotion of investment in the region. Radebe said a study on the setting up of a regional bank would be completed in June. Abraham Pallanayo, director of SADC's trade and industry sector said the region also needed to expand trade among its own members as well as cross border investment. He said although the volume of trade among member countries had improved since South Africa joined SADC, more was needed towards establishing a free trade area within eight years. SADC countries signed a trade protocol last year which is aimed at establishing a regional free trade area in the next eight years. SADC comprises Mauritius, Angola, Lesotho, Swaziland, Zambia, Zimbabwe, Namibia, Mozambique, Tanzania, Malawi, South Africa and Botswana.
