ECAT	Finance Minister Theo Waigel said on Friday Germany's high unemployment justified an increase in the 1997 budget deficit contained in the 1997 supplementary budget. "The high unemployment justifies the rise in the 1997 deficit," Waigel told a news conference after Chancellor Helmut Kohl's cabinet approved the 1997 supplementary budget.   The cabinet approved Waigel's 461 billion mark ($263 billion) draft budget for 1998 and a supplementary budget for 1997 that enlarges the deficit. The supplementary budget for this year raises the projected deficit to 71.2 billion marks from an original plan of 53.3 billion, but the government has said it still expects to qualify for European economic and monetary union (EMU). The cabinet approval sets the stage for parliamentary debate on the bills, expected in special sessions in August or September. Opposition Social Democrats have already attacked the government bills as shaky and lacking in credibility. Since the 1997 deficit exceeds government investment, the government must now, under the constitution, make a declaration that the excessive deficit is being used to combat an imbalance in the economy. -- Bonn newsroom, 49+ 228 260 97150
GCAT	Sri Lanka will launch a $4 million campaign to attract investors and tourists by stressing that a 13 year-long ethnic war has been largely limited to the country's north and east. Media and Tourism Minister Dharmasiri Senanayake told a news conference on Thursday the government had to counter moves by separatist Tamil guerrillas to tarnish Sri Lanka's image. "Presently we suffer from a problem of disinformation," he said. "These reports are exaggerated." Tourist arrivals to the Indian Ocean island dropped by 39.6 percent in April from a year ago, the Ceylon Tourist Board said. Sri Lanka had 403,101 tourists last year. The armed forces have battled the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam since 1983 in a war largely contained in the north and east and away from attractions such as the southern beaches, the central hill country and the ancient kingdoms in the north-central region. The rebels, however, have also hit economic targets. A suicide bomb attack on the Central Bank in Colombo in January killed almost 100 people.
ECAT	The Bank of Israel will raise its key lending rate by 0.5 percentage point at the end of the month, Israel Discount Bank said in an economic forecast released on Monday. The base rate stands at 12.7 percent on an annual basis. Economists at Discount said real short-term rates calculated according to the capital market's inflationary expectations had dropped from 6.5 percent in mid-June to 4.2 in late July. This, coupled with the 15-percent rise in M1 money supply in the last 12 months, would prompt the central bank to raise its lending rate, it said. "These developments point to a significant erosion in the level of monetary restraint," said the bank. "For this reason, economists at the bank estimate there is an increased chance the Bank of Israel will raise its monetary tender rate already at the end of this month by around 0.5 percent," it said. Discount expects the consumer price index to rise 0.7 percent to 0.8 percent in each of the next two months. It said 1997 inflation would reach 9.5 to 10 percent. The government has set a 1997 inflation target of seven to 10 percent. Finance Minister Yaacov Neeman said on Sunday inflation this year was running at 9.5 to 10 percent. The bank forecasts the 1997 budget deficit at 11 billion shekels ($3.1 billion), or about 3.1 percent of gross domestic product (GDP). That would exceed the government's 2.8-percent target by 1.5 billion shekels. It said partial second-quarter economic figures point to continued GDP growth of 2.5 to 3.0 percent. "Gross domestic product is expected to grow in the second half of 1997 and in 1998 at a three-percent annual rate," the bank said. - Jerusalem newsroom 972-2-5370502 ($ = 3.518 Israeli Shekels)
