GCAT	At least four people were killed and several injured on Friday when police opened fire on a violent mob in India's commercial hub of Bombay, police officials said. They said the situation was later brought under control at Ghatkopar, about 15 km (10 miles) from the city centre.   Police said trouble started when a statue of leader Bhimrao Ambedkar, known as the father of the Indian constitution, was found garlanded with shoes, viewed as an insulting gesture. A mob surrounded the statue and pelted police with stones when they tried to push through the crowd to the statue. The mob held up traffic on a busy highway during the morning rush hour and set fire to at least two private vehicles, police said. Ambedkar is treated like a god by lower classes in India's rigid Hindu caste society.
MCAT	Britain's FTSE 100 index opened mixed on Monday, with sterling's strength, interest rate concerns and continued pre-Budget nerves keeping investors wary, dealers said. Attention was focused on the futures market, they said, after the September contract dived to a discount to spot on Friday, dragging down the FTSE. The blue-chip index opened 3.1 points firmer at 4,597.0, helped higher by a leap in National Westminster Bank shares, up 30p at 776-1/2 on press reports that it could be the subject of a bid from Barclays Plc .
GCAT	Safer techniques for the diagnosis of certain prenatal disorders may be on the horizon, according to an article on Friday in the British medical journal, The Lancet. A study of 43 pregnant women revealed the presence of foetal genetic material in the mother's plasma, a location that previously had been overlooked, according to researchers from Britain, Italy and Hong Kong. As a result, it should become possible to screen women early in pregnancy for abnormalities carried by the father using a simple blood test, the researchers wrote. "It would mean that a proportion of women might be spared an invasive genetic diagnosis," said Dr. James Wainscoat of John Radcliffe Hospital near Oxford. A common invasive technique for detecting foetal abnormalities is amniocentesis. Under this procedure, foetal cells are obtained by inserting a long, hollow needle into the womb. This procedure carries the risk of miscarriage. In their study, the researchers sought to find out whether the blood of pregnant women could provide the same type of genetic information for detecting abnormalities as had been discovered in the blood of cancer patients. Wainscoat said the study's findings were "very surprising" in so far as they highlighted the importance of the mother's blood plasma as a source of information. "People had never anticipated that DNA (genetic material) from the foetus is mostly present in the plasma rather than in the cellular part of the blood," he said. Traditionally, the plasma has been discarded in certain research protocols, he added. Wainscoat said the study's findings could result in the use of simple, harmless screening tests for foetuses thought to be in danger of inheriting an abnormality from the father. However, if the foetus were found to be at risk, a further and probably invasive diagnosis would be necessary. The screening test would not be effective if mother and father carried the same abnormality, he added.
CCAT	Chubb Corp declined comment on a published report that a company run by Patriot American Hospitality Inc Chairman and Chief Executive Paul Nussbaum has agreed in principle to acquire the assets of Chubb's real estate unit. The Wall Street Journal said Patriot American Management & Leasing Co, a private firm, had agreed in principle to acquire Chubb's Bellemead Development Corp for about $1 billion. Patriot American was not available for comment.   Last Friday Chubb said it had entered into an agreement with a prospective buyer to perform due diligence and that it anticipated executing a contract for the sale of substantially all of its commercial properties. In October Chubb said it had hired Goldman Sachs to help it evaluate strategic options for its life insurance and real estate businesses. Last month Chubb reached a definitive agreement to sell its life insurance business to Jefferson-Pilot Corp for $875 milion cash.
MCAT	COMEX and NYMEX precious metals futures ended lower Tuesday, despite rumors of central bank activity, with the volume in COMEX copper exceeding the volume in COMEX gold. "There was very little of note going on in precious metals today, other than some rolling of May silver positions into the July contract," FIMAT New York trader John Tyree said. COMEX June gold settled down $1.50 an ounce at $343.40, after trading a $345.10-342.90 range. Estimated total COMEX gold volume was only 11,000 lots.   Bullion banks were the main sellers, rather than the funds, traders said, amid rumors of unconfirmed rumors of European central bank activity, traders said. But the Dutch central bank denied it had been selling gold. In January this year the Dutch central bank confirmed it had sold 300 tonnes of its gold reserves in late 1996. Daily momentum oscillators in June gold, such as a standard nine-day relative strength indicator (RSI), have recovered from the oversold levels seen after last week's slump to contract lows, but the momentum downtrend had not yet reversed, analysts said. Meanwhile, the contract's five-day moving average remained well below both its 21-day and 55-day average, suggesting the renewed downtrend was still intact. In the bullion market, spot gold was quoted $341.10/60 compared to the London Tuesday afternoon fix at $341.60 and the New York close Monday around $342.70/10. While physical offtake is seen robust below $340 an ounce, concerns about the possibility of another rise in U.S. interest rates at the next Federal Reserve FOMC meeting on May 20, as well as worries about further European central bank activity are likely to limit any advance in gold, analysts said. In producer news, South Africa's Free State Consolidated Gold Mines Ltd Freegold said Tuesday a fire at its Western Holdings No 1 shaft had hit about six kilograms of production and there could be further losses. Meanwhile, workers went on strike at South Africa's East Rand Propietary Mines Ltd. COMEX May silver ended down 2.0 cents at $4.715, after seeing a $4.770-4.705 range. Estimated total COMEX silver volume was 21,000 contracts. Open interest in COMEX silver fell a sharp 2,130 lots Monday to 99,266 contracts, after climbing to its highest levels since August last year on Friday at 102,323 contracts. Silver prices have also changed little in the past few days, after finding support around $4.70 in the bullion market last week, following a slide to two-month lows. Fundamentals in silver are more bullish than for gold, analysts said. Despite rising mine production since 1995, consumption is expected to reach record levels in the U.S. and India this year, while COMEX stocks have declined by nearly 50 percent since 1994. NYMEX July platinum ended down $4.10 an ounce at $376.40, while NYMEX June palladium lost $1.00 to $154.75, on light profit taking, but the physical market remained very tight, traders said. PGM lease rates remained high in Zurich, traders said, with the physical market likely to stay very tight until Russian supplies to Japan resume. The fundamental outlook for PGMs remains the most bullish of any metals in the precious metals complex, analysts said. Heavy supplies of platinum and palladium from Russia last year swamped the market, but Russian PGM exports have fallen sharply this year after the breakdown of the Russia/Japan supplycontract talks in December. The large supply/demand surpluses of the past three or four years are now being absorbed and automotive demand is rising quickly, analysts said. --email: clive.mckeef @ reuters.com ((Clive McKeef, New York Commodities Desk,+1-212-859-1641))
CCAT	Nomura Securities Co Ltd said on Monday that it had downgraded Yamazaki Baking Co Ltd to a "2" rating from its previous "1". In its three-grade rating system, Nomura assigns a "2" rating to issues whose values it sees moving within 10 percentage points in either direction of the key 225-share Nikkei average over the following six months.
CCAT	Stock in MCI Communications Corp was six percent higher on Friday on renewed rumors that either GTE Corp or British Telecommunications Plc was to buy the company. None of the companies would comment, citing policy on market speculation. MCI stock was 1-1/2 firmer at 26-5/8 at 1200 EST/1700 GMT and topped the Nasdaq actives list. "I've heard this GTE rumor before and it doesn't make sense," said analyst Richard Klugman of brokers PaineWebber. He said GTE is already offering long distance to its own customers and does not want to buy MCI's customer base.   Analysts see more logic to the BT side of the rumor, as the British carrier already has a 20 percent stake in MCI and the two companies share Concert, a joint venture serving multinational corporations' communications needs. However, BT is blocked from increasing its MCI stake very far by a federal rule on foreign ownership of U.S. telecommunications and media assets, they said. "I don't think you can get around rule 310 B however you do it," Klugman said of the 1934 legislation that bars a higher stake.   -- Nick Louth, New York Newsroom 212 859 1712
