MCAT	ARA spot fuel oil bunkers rose again on Friday, drawn upwards by firmer paper numbers rather than strong fundemental demand. Marine diesel and gas oil prices were also higher, boosted by recent IPE futures gains. Dealers said Rotterdam 380 cst was seen around $103-104 delivered with 180 cst about $3-4 higher. Spot bunker enquiries were seen to be around 10,000-15,000 tonnes. Hamburg market followed on the tail of higher ARA prices, but demand was slow. "I don't know whether they (shippers) have been scared off (by the higher prices) or whether it's a typically quiet Friday," said one trader. In the Mediterranean, bunkering was steady, but unexceptional. Prices were broadly unchanged, but holding a firmer tone. Some shortages were seen in Italy and Spain and there was little sign of suitable spec cargoes. Fujairah bunkers were firmer, buoyed by good demand and congestion difficulties until the end of next week. Cape Towan was out of fuel and will not be quoting until the second week of September. Durban prices were also stronger up at $107-$111 ex wharf. -- Matthew Jones, London Newsroom, +44 171 542 8980
MCAT	Base metal prices ended an uncertain Tuesday LME session mixed, although market-leaders copper and aluminium were softer with sentiment turning negative, traders said. Elsewhere, the volatile nickel market was firmer, tin continued its correction, but lead and zinc were unimpressive as summer slowdown factors held sway. "The mood and the good sentiment has disappeared from the metals," one said. Nickel was the major mover today, and trading remained volatile during the afternoon. Prices continued to whip around, albeit above support levels to finally end at $7,180, up $155. Traders said the wide price moves were due to opposite fundamental developments, with overnight news of the strike at Inco's Sudbury facilities driving the market higher. Subsequent news that Russia's Norilsk was looking at a 20 percent increase in production this year took the heat out of the rally. But in the short-term, caution over the Inco strike is likely to restrict the downside, they said. Copper also fluctuated throughout the session, but in a tighter range and mostly towards the lower end of the band. There was reasonable support around $2,470/75 again, but a covering rally in mid-afternoon was soundly rebuffed around $2,500. "These bounces are getting smaller and not too convincing," the trader said. Talk that China may be a seller of copper, rather than a hoped-for buyer, was an unnerving factor, with some saying stocks may rise in the Far East soon. Last three months trade was at $2,479, down $6 from the previous kerb. Cash/threes was marginally softer at $56/60 backwardation. Aluminium was pummelled by fund liquidation and spread lending operations, against a background of increased availability in Europe. Again, the market was unwilling to hold a key upside level at $1,600, and by the close prices were back at $1,578, an $18 loss. In lead, there was little significant action, with price movements dictated by the overall trend. Last business was at an unchanged $626. Zinc met good buying ahead of a test of anticipated support around $1,310/15, although there continues to be concern over Chinese deliveries in Singapore. Nevertheless, last trade was at $1,334, up $4 from Monday. Tin continued to build on Monday's corrective rally from 14-1/2 month lows, helped by the upturn in consumer business those levels fostered. However, the market is wary of talk of Russian stockpile metal being shipped to the West. Last trade was at $5,680, up $40. The alloy market was stable, and closed at $1,475/80 a tonne. --Martin Hayes, London Newsroom 44 171 542 8080
GCAT	(Compiled for Reuters by Media Monitors) THE AUSTRALIAN Former world champion Australian swimmer Hayley Lewis looks to abandon her swimming career to pursue triathlons. Lewis ceased training in January to rejuvenate herself and do some triathlon races, but has since turned this off season training into a serious pursuit. Page 18. -- Australian Rules footballer Tony McGuinness and the Sydney Swans yesterday resolved their dispute over the Club's failure to nominate the former Adelaide captain in their draft two weeks ago. It is believed the Swans and McGuiness's manager, Greg Griffin, negotiated a settlement for as much as $100,000 in Adelaide at the weekend. Page 18. -- Melbourne Knights soccer sweeper, Joe Simunic is considering an offer which would make him the highest paid player in the 20-year history of the national soccer league. Simunic, 18, confirmed yesterday new Ericsson Cup club-in-waiting Carlton have approaced him with a deal believed to be around A$100,000. Page 17. -- THE SYDNEY MORNING HERALD Australia's spin duo of Shane Warne and Michael Bevan caused a massive upset in South Africa's batting on the final morning at the first cricket Test in Johannesburg, delivering the Australian cricket side to victory by an innings and 196 runs. Warne's 4-3 and Bevan's 4-32 saw the final four wickets fall in just two overs. The final five wickets fell for three runs as South Africa collapsed from 5-127 to 130 all out. Page 48. -- Australia's Test cricket matches and one-day series against England later this year are unprecedentedly popular, with the first four days of the second Test - June 19 to 22 - already sold out, as is the third and final one-day match on Sunday, May 25. Pag 48. -- An ongoing feud between some of Macedonia's top players and national coach Djoko Hadjilevski should give Australia the upper hand in their World Cup soccer warm-up match next week. Macedonia will be without five key foreign-based players, including forme Inter-Milan striker Darko Pancev. Page 47. -- THE AGE Australian distance swimmer Daniel Kowalski, due to defend his 1995 world shortcourse titles in the 400 metres freestyle and 1500 metres freestyle, may need to withdraw from the world shortcourse championships in Sweden next month because of an inflamed soulder. Page 14. -- Australian Football League Brownlow medallist Michael Voss could play his first game since last year's semi-finals in Brisbane's Ansett Cup quarter-final against St Kilda at Waverly Park next Sunday night. Voss was a late withdrawal from last tear's preliinary final against North Melbourne because of a sprained ankle. Page 14. -- Australian tennis sensation Mark Phillippoussis slammed the fastest serve of his career in his first-round victory at an ATP event in Arizona yesterday. In his defeat of wildcard entrant Tommy Haas of Germany, 2-6, 6-3, 6-4, Philippoussis smashed a serve of 222.4 kilometres per hour. Page 14. -- THE HERALD SUN Australian horse trainer Lee Freedman will recommend star filly Merlene be retired after she pulled up distressed in a trial at Flemington yesterday. Last year's Golden Slipper winner was operated on for breathing problems shortly after winning the AJC Sies' Produce Stakes at Randwick in early April last year, and has not raced since. Page 86. -- Coca-Cola has become the new sponsor for Tennis Victoria's junior development program. Under the four-year deal, tens of thousands of dollars will go into category one and two development squads run by tennis associations and clubs throughout the State. Pge 77. -- Australian Madison cycling champions Brett Aitken and Stephen Pate may not represent Australia at the world championships in Perth - even if they blitz the field at Bendigo on Sunday. The pair are favourites to win the 100 kilometre Bendigo Madison, yet erly indication do not mark them as certain selections for the Australian team. Page 79. -- THE DAILY TELEGRAPH North Queensland rugby league player Tyran Smith has escaped penalty on a high tackle charge but will serve an automatic one-match suspension if he goes into the sin-bin this season. Super League's opening premiership round resulted in commissioner Jim Hal sending warning notices to four players following kicking and high-tackle incidents. Page 70. -- Juggler's managing owner Peter Horowitz has delayed until today a decision about taking on Octagonal in Monday's A$1.25 million Australian Cup at Flemington. Trainer Gai Waterhouse will meet with Horowitz today and should have a decision by the end of their talks. Page 66. -- Penrith rugby league club's point scoring centre Ryan Girdler will play against Canberra at Bruce Stadium on Sunday with a fractured left hand. Girdler suffered the injury while playing the Perth Reds last Sunday and there were fears he might be out of acion for as long as six weeks. Page 68. -- Reuters Sydney Newsroom 61-2 9373 1800
GCAT	Following are some major events to have occurred on August 25 in history: 325 - The Council Of Nicaea ended with the adoption of the Nicene Creed, establishing the doctrine of the Holy Trinity. 1270 - King Louis IX of France, who led the Seventh Crusade against Egypt in 1248, died. 1530 - Ivan IV (Ivan the Terrible) born. He was proclaimed the first Russian Tsar and 1547 and was noted both for his debauchery and strict religious observances. 1580 - Spanish forces under the Duke of Alva defeated the Portuguese at the Battle of Alcantara, securing Portugal as a Spanish realm. 1718 - The city of New Orleans, Louisiana, was founded and named in honour of the Duke of Orleans of France. 1744 - Johann Gottfried von Herder, German critic, philosopher and author, born; he influenced Goethe and development of German Romanticism. 1819 - James Watt, Scottish inventor and developer of the steam engine, died. 1822 - Sir William Herschel, German-born English astronomer who discovered the planet Uranus, died. 1825 - Uruguay declared its independence from Spain. 1830 - A revolt broke out in the French-speaking provinces of the Netherlands against union into Belgium. 1841 - Emil Theodar Kocher, Swiss surgeon, born; he won the  Nobel Prize in physiology and medicine for his research on the thyroid gland in 1909. 1862 - William Cooper Procter, founder of Procter and Gamble  soap manufacturers, born. 1867 - Michael Faraday, British physicist, chemist and electrical pioneer, died. 1873 - John North Willys. U.S. manufacturer and diplomat, born. He founder Willys-Overland Auto Co., in 1907, developers of the "Jeep" and was U.S. ambassador to Poland 1930-32. 1875 - Captain Matthew Webb became the first person to swim across the English Channel. 1883 - Under the terms of the Treaty of Hue, France assumed the protectorate over Annam and Tonkin in what is now Vietnam. 1912 - Former East German leader Erich Honecker born; he created the most potent and hated symbol of a divided Europe when he built the Berlin Wall in 1961 at the height of the Cold War. 1918 - Leonard Bernstein, U.S. composer and conductor, born. 1919 - George Wallace, U.S. Democratic politician and former governor of Alabama, born. A two-time presidential contender and once the symbol of Southern resistance to desegregation, he was paralysed from the waist down by a would-be assassin's bullet in 1972. 1921 - The United States and Germany signed a peace treaty ending the state of war between them. 1930 - Sean Connery, Scottish film actor, born. Shot to fame when he was chosen to play James Bond, the hero of Ian Fleming's novels. 1936 - After a five-day show trial, 16 opponents of Stalin were executed in Russia. 1940 - Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia were incorporated into the Soviet Union. 1940 - The British Air Force dropped their first bombs on Berlin in an overnight raid. 1942 - The Duke of Kent, youngest brother of King George VI, was killed in a plane crash during a war mission to Iceland. 1943 - Lord Louis Mountbatten was appointed Supreme Allied Commander in Southeast Asia (World War Two). 1944 - Paris was liberated when the local German commander General Choltitz surrendered to the allies. 1961 - Brazilian President Janio Quadros resigned after only six months, claiming "terrible forces came forward to fight me". He went into exile in Australia. 1964 - Kenneth Kaunda became president-designate of Zambia, formerly Northern Rhodesia. 1967 - A new constitution came into effect in Paraguay, now celebrated each year by a public holiday. 1967 - The leader of the American Nazi Party, George Lincoln Rockwell, was shot dead. 1975 - In Rhodesia, formerly Southern Rhodesia, talks between the white minority government and black leaders opened in railway carriages near Victoria Falls. 1978 - The Turin shroud, once venerated as the burial cloth of Christ, went on public display for the first time in 45 years. 1988 - Direct talks between Iran and Iraq began in an attempt to stop their Gulf War. 1989 - After a 12-year, four-billion-mile (six-billion-km) space journey, Voyager 2 flew over the cloudtops of the giant planet Neptune and its moon Triton, sending back photographs of swampy areas, frozen lakes and craters. 1991 - Byelorussia (Belarus) declared independence from the Soviet Union.
