GCAT	A Red Cross official walked into the besieged Japanese ambassador's house in Lima early Saturday and was still inside over half an hour later, witnesses said. The man, wearing the white vest of the Red Cross, was seen by reporters as he strolled into the residence, where Marxist rebels are holding 72 hostages, just before 2 a.m. local time. There was no explanation for the visit at such an unusual hour, and an official at the Red Cross office in Lima gave no information. Reports varied as to whether the man was carrying anything. In the past, visits by Red Cross doctors to the residence have led to speculation about ill health among the hostages or the roughly 20 Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA) rebels holding them. None of the hostages have been reported acutely ill recently. But a few suffer from diabetes, heart disease or other chronic illnesses, and several are reported to be suffering from stress-related disorders.
CCAT	The Polish Securities Commission (KPW) has cleared for public trade all 1,170,000 in Polish food processor PEPEES SA, including the 152,100 shares to be sold to the public, the KPW said in a Thursday statement. PEPEES president Artur Baldowski told a news conference on Thursday that the shares to be sold to the public were currently owned by the firm's 33-percent owner, National Investment Fund No.3 in Poland's mass privatisation scheme. The shares are due to be offered with a minimum price at a special bourse session on April 18. Baldowski said PEPEES, which netted six million zlotys in 1996's first half on 75.6 million zlotys in sales, seeks a main market listing. -- Warsaw Newsroom +48 22 653 9700
MCAT	Slovenia's SBI index firmed 0.59 percent on Wednesday on stepped-up turnover but traders see the market consolidating its gains from the recent rally. "Today's turnover is close to what we can call normal and it's mostly on the back of foreign activity," one broker said. The SBI index rose 8.28 points to 1,405.0. Since June 26, when the central bank announced its decision to relax rules for long-term foreign investors, the blue-chip index has risen 13.5 percent. Overall eight shares rose, seven fell and two were flat, while 10 were untraded. Turnover rose to 314.4 million tolars from 280.8 million. Drug maker Lek had the highest turnover, jumping 3.29 percent to 32,020 tolars on volume of 4,094 shares for total turnover of 129.7 million. Market participants said Lek's good business performance and future outlook could drive the share price up to 35,000 in the next few weeks. Brokerage Dadas was the top gainer, surging 10.19 percent to 5,840 tolars on volume of 57 shares. Bank Probanka led decliners, tumbling 7.84 percent to 20,690 tolars on volume of 160 shares. Traders attributed the fall to a technical correction. -- Ljubljana newsroom, 386-61-125-8439
CCAT	The profits of three of the four major petrochemical companies in eastern China dropped sharply in 1996 due to duplication of facilities, the official Economic Daily said on Wednesday. However, officials attributed the profit drop to reasons such as sluggish market demand and rising international prices for crude oil. Over capacity and lack of cooperation had reduce the competitive strength of the four petrochemical firms based near Nanjing, capital of eastern Jiangsu province, and eroded profits, the Economic Daily said. However, the newspaper did not give figures for the decline in the profits of Yizheng Chemical Fibre Co Ltd, Yangzi Petrochemical Co and Jinling Petrochemical Co. The Nanjing Chemical Industrial Corp reportedly made a profit. Citing problems of over capacity, the newspaper said Yizheng Chemical Fibre, under the Chinese General Association of Textile Industry, planned to expand its PTA capacity to 600,000 tonnes before the year 2000 from a current 20,000 tonnes a year to meet its own demand, it said. Yangzi Petrochemical Co, a subsidary of the China National Petrochemical Co (Sinopec), with 600,000 tonnes of existing PTA production capacity could not sell its output to Yizheng and was now devloping its refining capacity, it said. However, the refining capacity of Yangzi had already reached 5.0 million tonnes a year while Jinling Petrochemical Co, also a Sinopec subsidiary, had refining capacity of 7.0 million tonnes, it said. Both were already unable to work at full capacity because of shortages of raw materials, it said. However, an official of Yangzi attributed the drop in profits to sluggish market demand rather than overlapping output. Pre-tax profits of Yangzi fell to 1.554 billion yuan this year from 4.5 billion yuan in 1995, he said. The pre-tax profits of Jinling declined to 1.414 billion yuan this year from 1.8 billion yuan in 1995, a company official said by telephone. He said rising international prices of crude in 1996 and heavy loan repayments had cut into profits last year. The profits of Yizheng dropped sharply in 1996 compared with the previous year, a company official said in a telephone interview. He refused to give a reason, saying the final profit figure would be issued in April. -- Beijing Newsroom (8610) 6532 1921
MCAT	Dealers marked down prices of some Russian shares in the hope of speculative gains later after news President Boris Yeltsin had ordered a complete government reshuffle on Tuesday, but traders said the fall was short-lived. At 1130 GMT Rostelekom  slipped off its early highs of $4.10 to $4.02, LUKoil  fell to $14.40 from $14.43 and Norilsk Nickel was $6.56 after $6.75. Yeltsin ordered a full reorganisation of the government, leaving only Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and First Deputy Prime Minister Anatoly Chubais in place. The bulk of the government will be formed within one week, he said in a decree. Traders said the news was a good opportunity for short-term speculation for Russian brokers. "Shares went down while people are having lunch. When New York opens we shall go up again," said IFCI-Moscow Partners chief trader Alexei Abdurakhimov. "Chernomyrdin and Chubais are staying and the rest of the people in the government are not very important for the market." Traders said Western investors were not worried by the coming reshuffle, taking no action on the market. "Prices are changing in different directions. I have an impression that price changes are not connected to the presidential decree. I canot see any hasty actions on the part of investors," said Regent European Securities trader Alexander Fonarkov. --Olga Popova, Moscow Newsroom, +7095 941 8520
