ECAT	District of Columbia said its sale of $168.87 million general obligation bonds was postponed to Oct 3 from Sept 26. "The District expects that the sale of the bonds will occur on or about Oct 3 and close on or about Oct 8," Anthony Williams, chief financial officer for the city, said in a press statement. Williams said the city will announce the extended sale date and closing date over news wire services at least 24 hours before the sale date.   The sale was postponed to give Congress more time to enact a bill that would waive a current 30-day congressional review requirement for pending D.C. bond sales. Questions should be directed to Thomas Huestis, deputy chief financial officer for D.C., at 202-727-6055. --Vicky Stamas, 202-898-8314
GCAT	President Mobutu Sese Seko supports sending a multinational force to Zaire to help get relief to refugees and help them return home to Rwanda, a U.N. envoy said after meeting him on Wednesday. Envoy Raymond Chretien quoted Mobutu as saying he would do his utmost to maintain calm in his country to let the multinational force work.   "President Mobutu told me Zaire would do everything possible to maintain this period of calm so that the multinational force discussed in Nairobi may be able to rapidly allow for food to reach refugees and help them return to their home countries, including of course Rwanda," Chretien said. "He was very clear, very categorical," Chretien told reporters after the meeting at Mobutu's French Riviera villa. He said the period of calm Mobutu mentioned referred to the unilateral ceasefire declared by Rwanda-backed Tutsi rebels fighting Zairean troops. An eight-nation African summit in Nairobi on Tuesday called on the United Nations to send a "neutral" protection force to create havens from which refugees could go home along safe corridors.
ECAT	Australia's prospects for improved growth through 1997 were enhanced on Friday when February retail trade data showed that consumers appeared to have returned to the stores following a disappointing Christmas. But while improving, there was no danger that the economy was accelerating at such a speed as to require the brakes to be applied in the form of a rate rise yet, economists said. Retail trade rose 0.8 percent in Feburary, official figures showed. It was seen as a strong figure because it followed a very large 2.7 percent rise in January retail trade.   "Today's result represents the second consecutive month of strong retail sales, suggesting that consumers have now returned to the shopping malls they deserted in the second half of 1996," Nomura Research senior economist Andrew Pease said. Economists said the data fitted in with anecdotal evidence that spending had picked up from early in 1997, and which had remained strong into March and April. "Consumer spending has been the missing link in the economic recovery," Commonwealth Bank senior economist Michael Blythe said. "It looks like it's coming back strongly."   The February rise took retail trade to 4.4 percent above its trough of last September. Over the past year, retail trade was up 3.3 percent, its highest annual increase since last August. "Numbers like this indicate that we've passed a turning point in the economy and an acceleration is underway," SBC Warburg senior economist Guy Bruten said. The strong start to the year in retail trade follows trade data on Thursday showing that exports have also been strong in the first two months of year, and economists said both should make solid contributions to first quarter growth.   However, the data on the day was not all one-sided. The retail trade data showed some patchiness across sectors, and seperate figures showed the building approvals fell 3.7 percent in February. A small fall had been expected after the very strong 10.4 percent rise in January but not only was the fall larger than expected, the composition of the fall suggested more weakness than economists had been factoring in. The January rise was dominated by rises in multi-dwelling approvals, which had been expected to unwind while approvals for private houses were expected to strengthen.   Instead, private houses were down 5.6 percent while other dwelling units fell 1.6 percent in February. "There is a housing recovery out there,it just isn't very robust yet," Bankers Trust chief economist Chris Caton said. The net result, economists said, was that while growth would lift through 1997, it would not be at a rapid pace. Accordingly, there was no need for monetary policy to be adjusted. "Economic conditions are improving but are still a long way short of justifying anything other than a 'leave rates on hold' stance from the Reserve Bank," Westpac economist Stephen McNabb said. -- Sydney Newsroom 61-2 9373-1800
CCAT	Northern Telecom Ltd Chief Executive Jean Monty said on Tuesday the company's revenues should grow by 15 to 20 percent in 1997. "We still maintain that we can meet our targets and that the revenue growth will be in the minimum mid-teens. So it's probably going to be between the 15 and 20 percent range," Monty said in a telephone interview. He said Nortel's balance sheet looked solid in the first quarter and added that the company should soon announce the sale of customer financing debt, including the US$1.2 billion vendor financing of the Sprint Corp wireless contract.   "The balance sheet remains very strong with a low debt ratio at 26 percent. We will announce pretty soon the layoff of major customer financings, which will give us even more dry powder for the longer term in terms of doing more business," Monty said. "(The Sprint deal) is done. We're going to announce that in the next couple of weeks," he added. Monty said the long delay in getting the financing deal done was due to its complexity. "It's a billion dollar deal," he said.   "And what's interesting about that is when you compare that to Lucent (Technologies Inc's) growth...they showed their growth in the U.S. market for operators at around 21 percent," Monty said. Nortel's earnings per share were US$0.41 versus US$0.32 in the prior year period. Monty said he was pleased with the growth rate given that it was paired with strong sales growth. "So earnings, after-tax margins, remained solid at the same level as last year even in the face of significant growth in revenues. Usually when you grow your busines that fast, you can see some softening of margins," Monty said.
