CCAT	The China Construction Bank extended new loans totalling 129 billion yuan in 1996, a rise of 16.8 percent from the previous year and the biggest increase in recent years, the China News Service said on Tuesday. At the end of 1996, the bank's deposits totalled 1.1018 trillion yuan, an increase of 284.1 billion yuan during the year, or a rise of 36.7 percent, it said. The rate of increase in deposits ranked first among China's main state-owned banks, it said. The report attributed the increase in deposits to the bank's strategy to focus its services on large-scale enterpries in big cities. The bank's profits reached 2.76 billion yuan last year, it said but did not explain whether the figure was pre-tax. ($1 = 8.3 yuan) -- Beijing Newsroom (8610) 6532 1921
ECAT	Portugal's budget deficit for January and February rose a year-on-year 34 percent to 142.3 billion escudos, the Finance Ministry said.   The Finance Ministry said in its monthly budget analysis that the January to February period was not directly comparable with the same period last year since the 1996 budget only came into effect from April. During the first quarter of 1996 a supplementary 1995 budget had been in effect.   The deficit excluding interest charges on public debt rose 29 percent in the first two months of this year to 71.5 billion escudos as a result of increased capital transfers. Current revenue rose 19.9 percent to 731.1 billion escudos while current spending rose 20.6 percent to 802.6 billion. -- Lisbon editorial +(351-1) 3538254
CCAT	Like trying to squeeze more juice out of a ripe tomato, Campbell Soup Co. announced Thursday it would buy back stock, cut jobs and expand overseas in efforts to boost profits in the mature food industry. "We are poised for breaking away from our competitors in the food industry," Chairman David W. Johnson said in announcing the initiatives to securities analysts in New York. Campbell said it had authorised $2.5 billion in share repurchases, including a $1.5 billion "dutch auction," was planning to eliminate about 650 jobs, and would buy Erasco Group, the leading canned soup company in Germany. Germany ranks as the largest commercial soup market outside the United States. The announcements came a day after Campbell reported a sixth consecutive year of record sales and earnings. They follow a steady record of cost cutting under Johnson, who took over as Campbell president in 1990 and was named chairman in 1993. The company said it will close or reorganize a number of manufacturing operations across North America, resulting in the elimination of 475 jobs. It will also cut 175 positions at its headquarters in Camden, N.J. "Competition remains fierce," Johnson said, "so we must make strategic moves to maintain our leadership position and to grow Campbell to the next performance level." Campbell's stock was at $72, up $4.50, in late trading Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange Thursday. Analysts said the moves had a good chance to pay off. "The bottom line is that we expect earnings to improve," said Deutsche Morgan Grenfell analyst Tim Ramey, in raising his rating on Campbell's stock to buy from hold. Paine Webber analyst George Staphos said, "They hit on several themes that are important for food companies in terms of how they can control earnings over time." "I think the prospects are good," he said. Analysts said Johnson told a meeting in New York that Campbell aimed to steadily improve earnings while increasing sales growth from recent levels. On Wednesday, Campbell said its profits rose by 15 percent to $802 million for the year ended July 28 as sales expanded by 6 percent to $7.68 billion. "What he (Johnson) would like to see is sales growth on the order of 8 percent," said Fourteen Research analyst Sally Schaadt. Ramey said earnings growth targets appeared to be around 15 percent to 16 percent annually. Campbell said it would consolidate production of Ramen noodles -- closing an operation in Georgia -- sell poultry processing plants, end seasonal production of tomato paste at a plant in Sacramento, Calif., and make other changes to improve asset use. These moves will result in an after-tax charge of about $160 million this fiscal year and will result in savings of $200 million over the next two years, Johnson said. The company will also make a number of product and marketing changes to spur growth, he said. These include a new line of premium ready-to-serve soups, new frozen soups and faster roll-out of the Franco American Superiore range of premium canned pasta products. In addition, Campbell announced plans to increase its advertising spending substantially, mainly for its soups, Pepperidge Farm snacks, V-8 vegetable juice and Swanson frozen foods. Central to Johnson's strategy is his declared aim to move Campbell's financial performance into what he called the "Best of Show" category -- outpacing the entire food industry to perform in the top ranks of branded consumer goods firms. This may be a tall order given the maturity of the industry, Schaadt said. But plans to continue seeking expansion of the soup market -- such as through the introduction of a premium line of soups in glass jars -- indicate that Campbell is thinking along the right lines, she said. "If the market itself can be expanded, he (Johnson) is going to get most of it," she said.
MCAT	The Casablanca stock exchange ended its two-hour session on Tuesday with a 0.40 percent increase led by the four stocks traded on the electronic system, a market analyst said. The all-share index closed at 601.09 points, up from 598.64 points on Monday, he said. "Banque Marocaine du Commerce Exterieur, Fertilizer firm, oil refinery and steel mill accounted for the main chunk of the trade on the official market," a broker at ABN-AMRO Finance said.   The four stocks were introduced in electronic trading early March. rose 16 dirhams to 578 dirhams with 9,033 shares traded. jumped 48 dirhams to 299.5 dirhams with 3,671 shares exchanged. was up 15 dirhams to 547 dirhams with 3,629 shares. was the most active share with 22,450 shares changing hands.   Market activity was disrupted on Tuesday as the stock exchange's new headquarters were inaugurated in presence of Crown Prince Mohamed. The trading session took place late in the afternoon instead of the usual morning session. ONA Group, Morocco's largest private conglomerate, remained unchanged at 760 dirhams. Its subsidiary Financiere Diwan also rose nine dirhams to close at 339 dirhams. Volume on the official market totalled 111 million dirhams from 76.6 million on Monday. Trade was made up 332 deals involving 103,612 shares valued at 97,637,731 dirhams and 23 deals involving 5,549 privatisation bonds (worth 13,428,660 dirhams. The volume for the unofficial market stood at 44.2 million dirhams from 24.5 million on Monday. ($1= 9.35 dirhams) - Rabat newsroom +212-7 72 65 18
GCAT	At least 14 people including leftist rebels and civilians died in fighting across Colombia, officials said on Wednesday. Counterinsurgency troops killed three members of the National Liberation Army (ELN), the second largest guerrilla force, in two separate clashes in northern Cesar and northwest Antioquia provinces on Tuesday, military sources said. Meanwhile, in eastern Casanare province three insurgents of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), Colombia's oldest and largest rebel army, died in fighting. In the trouble-torn, banana-growing Uraba region in Antioquia, four peasants were killed by suspected leftist guerrillas, police said. The area has long been the scene of bitter conflicts between rebels and right-wing paramilitary groups battling for control of lucrative contraband routes. Three other peasants were murdered on Tuesday afternoon in unexplained circumstances near the town of Maceo, also in Antioquia province, police said.
