ECAT	Saudi Arabia's real deficit in 1996 stood at 17 billion riyals ($4.5 billion), down from a projected 18.5 billion riyals, a Finance Ministry statement said on Monday. The statement said real spending in 1996 was 194 billion riyals, up from the projected 150 billion riyals. Real revenue stood at 177 billion riyals up from the 131.5 billion forecast. It said the rise in expenditure was "mainly due to the measures taken in the year to pay the dues of farmers, contractors and companies...where seven billion riyals were paid to farmers and more than 15 billion riyals were paid to individuals, contractors, importers and other companies." "These measures had boosted confidence in the national economy and were also reflected in the development the kigndom is witnessing in different sectors," the statement said. It was issued by the official media after the announcement of the 1997 budget, which forecast a 17 billion riyals deficit. The arrears had been accumulating since the 1990-91 Gulf war mostly due to the high costs of the war and the weak oil prices, but in the past year, cash payments have been made and special bonds issued to meet the dues. Economists in the kingdom say the government has started meeting current payments on time.
ECAT	South African Reserve Bank Governor Chris Stals said on Tuesday that the 1996 current account deficit would be well below the 1995 level of 10 billion rand.   "The deficit for 1996 was well below the 1995 level of 10 billion rand," Stals told reporters at a media briefing. "What is more important is to note that the deficit calculated on a seasonally adjusted annualised basis peaked at about 15 billion rand in the second quarter of 1996, before declining to 8.5 billion rand in the third quarter and to a level less than five billion in the fourth quarter of last year," Stals Said.   He said the net inflow of capital from abroad plunged to below five billion rand in 1996 from about 20 billion in 1995, which he said was not enough to cover the current account deficit over the calender year 1996. "The result was that the relatively low level of official gold and foreign exchange reserves came under some pressure, and a very vulnerable situation was exploited by a number of speculative attacks on the rand," Stals said.
MCAT	German Bund futures will add to their recent gains over the next few sessions, feeding off a flurry of debt-positive news released on Thursday. Analysts said data published early in the session confirmed the German economy was staging only a frail recovery, helping back up the Bundesbank's later announcement that it expected no monetary policy change in the foreseeable future. The DTB June future reached an earlier high at 101.13, but had returned to 100.88, up 21 basis points on the day, by 1421 GMT.   With a larger than expected drop in February retail sales figures earlier, and a far weaker March Ifo business climate survey than predicted, some Bund market analysts expressed surprise that the DTB future had not managed to hold its own better. But they said these two factors, combined with the Bundesbank's decision to leave its key rates unchanged at the regular fortnightly council meeting, had helped to underpin the market, ensuring it did not dip below zero for the session. "The market has been a bit of a mixed bag all day," said Robert Eller, a futures broker in at ABN Cicorp in London.   "The future has been breaking up and down through this neckline (at around 101.00 to 101.13) all session and it is making players a bit nervous," he said. But he added that he was targeting 102.27 for the June futures within the next two weeks. Bundesbank president Hans Tietmeyer, speaking at a news conference following a regular policy-setting council meeting, said he did not expect any change in German interest rates in the foreseeable future. Tietmeyer added that although M3 money supply growth had been strong, this was no threat to German inflation.   "Tietmeyer's complacency in saying that M3 poses no inflationary danger reinforces the perception that the Bundesbank's rates will remain on hold until into 1998," said one analyst. He said this stance was further justified by the 'fits and starts' picture of the German economy offered in the Ifo survey. The March index of business sentiment fell to 92.4 from 93.6. Economists had been forecasting a rise to 94.00. Despite a generally upbeat mood for Bunds, the 10-year cash yield spread between German and U.S. debt slimmed to 116 basis points by late European trade from 120 at Wednesday's close.   But bond strategists said there was no reason to believe this underperformance would be anything other than short-lived. With economic activity muted, interest rates on hold, and inflation under wraps, German debt would prove more attractive than U.S. Treasuries in the medium term, they said. -- Frankfurt Newsroom + 49 69 7565 1246
MCAT	The Chinese yuan closed up at 8.2982 against the U.S. dollar on Friday from Thursday's 8.2991 with little impact seen from the news that four foreign banks had been granted the right to do yuan business, traders said. The authorities announced on Monday that four foreign banks with branches in Shanghai had been granted approval to do local currency business. Dealers said the news had no influence on today's movement of the yuan which stayed in a narrow range just above 8.3000 in dull trading.   The yuan opened slightly higher at 8.2989 and hit an intra-day low of 8.2990 early in the session. It then rose slightly to move around 8.2985 before a high of 8.2980 just before the close. Trading was dull, with most done at about 8.2985, traders said. "Most people stood on the sidelines in the last session of 1996," a dealer said. "The news on the foreign banks had no direct impact." "Foreign banks beginning to do yuan business will make the foreign exchange market more active next year," a second dealer said.   Dealers expect the yuan to move around 8.2980 when trading resumes after the New Year Day holiday. The yuan closed slightly down at 7.2000 from 7.1600 in extremely dull trading against 100 Japanese yen and up at 1.0723 from 1.0726 against the Hong Kong dollar. -- Shanghai newsroom (86-21) 6279-7004
MCAT	Sweden's National Debt Office said on Tuesday it would invite bids from the market for an auction of seven-day Treasury bills worth 15 billion crowns. The auction will take place on April 9. All bids must be received by 0900 GMT on April 8. The paper will run from April 9 and mature on April 16. The lowest accepted bid volume is 100 million crowns. -- Belinda Goldsmith, Stockholm newsroom +46-8-700-1017
GCAT	The European Union is considering breaking off high-level meetings with Iran and excluding top Iranian officials from its borders, according to a proposal to be discussed by EU foreign ministers next week. The proposal, drafted by senior political officials from EU capitals, accuses Iran of conducting state terrorism and reaffirms the suspension of the EU's "critical dialogue" policy with Tehran. "Progress can only be made if the Iranian authorities respect the norms of international law (and) refrain from acts of terrorism," a draft statement says. The 15-nation bloc on April 10 recalled its ambassadors and suspended its policy of trying to bring Iran closer to the West through talks after a German court found that the Iranian government was involved in the murder of Kurdish dissidents. In practice, this meant cancellation of one relatively low-level meeting of officials in May. But the move represented a significant shift towards the United States' view that Iran should be treated as a pariah state. U.S. officials have been touring EU capitals to discuss Iran ahead of the foreign ministers meeting in Luxembourg next Tuesday and Wednesday. Under the proposal to be put to the ministers, the EU would suspend all bilateral visits by ministers to Iran or by Iranian officials in the 15 EU countries. EU governments would also work together to ensure that visas were not granted to "certain senior members of the Iranian hierarchy" and that Iranian intelligence personnel were excluded from EU member states, implying possible expulsion. Diplomats said it was not clear how many of the new measures would be agreed by the EU ministers, although there was no question of lifting the suspension of the critical dialogue. "There are a number of states...that do not want to upset Iran," one diplomat said. He said there was concern in some EU capitals that turning up the heat on Iran while it was preparing for elections could play into the hands of Tehran hardliners. The ministers are expected to send their countries' ambassadors back to Iran. The advocacy group Human Rights Watch said on Friday it had written to the EU ministers urging them to tell Iran that the resumption of normal relations was dependent on Tehran taking steps against agents murdering political dissidents. Iranian opponents of Tehran's Moslem rulers have urged the EU to break off its remaining links with Iran and impose sanctions. They plan a large demonstration in Luxembourg on Tuesday. In Paris, a French appeals court on Friday upheld prison sentences passed last year on two men for supplying Iran's secret services with information aimed at helping to kill opponents in France. Mojtaba Mashhady, 39, a French citizen of Iranian origin, was jailed for seven years. Iranian Hossein Yasdenseta, 37, was given three years.
MCAT	The Bangladesh taka closed steady at 42.2250/42.2350 to the dollar in quiet interbank trading, compared with the previous 42.2200/42.2400, dealers said. The taka was mostly stable after opening at 42.2230/42.2400 on lower demand for dollars because of the weekend closure of international markets. "Few deals were done in dull trading," said one dealer. Interbank call money rates closed down at 4.0 percent to 4.25 percent, compared with the previous 4.25-4.75 percent.
GCAT	These are the leading stories in the Moroccan press on Thursday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy. LE MATIN DU SAHARA - Cabinet meeting discusses agriculture and says despite efforts to improve infrastructure, output is still dependant on changes in weather. - Transport workers decide to cancel planned two-day strike after meeting Prime Minister Abdellatif Filali. - Interior Minister Driss Basri meets representative of French housing group Bouygues over building of Casablanca subway. First eight km (five mile) stretch will be financed by French donation. L'OPINION - Truck loaded with gas containers explodes in Casablanca. - Lack of rain worries farmers as weather forecasters see no immediate change. AL-BAYANE - Statistics Directorate survey shows that jobless graduates of both sexes, aged between 25 and 40, are tempted to migrate. - South Korean Daewoo finalises purchase of Hyatt Regency hotel. AL-MAGHRIB - Two European Union officials expected in Rabat on March 31 to discuss preparations for Euro-Mediterranean foreign ministers' meeting in Malta in April. - Iraq mounts diplomatic offensive to gather Arab countries support. LE QUOTIDIEN - United States state department issues critical report on freedoms and justice in Morocco. L'ECONOMISTE - Liberalisation of sugar and oil imports last year hampered by ministry circular telling firms to postpone price increases because of the political, social and economic environment.
ECAT	The UK harmonised index of consumer prices (HICP) rose 1.6 percent in the year to April, the Office for National Statistics said. This compared with 1.8 percent in the year to March. The HICP is calculated in each member state of the European Union in the context of the convergence criteria for a single currency laid down in the Maastricht Treaty. International comparisons will be released by Eurostat on June 6.
GCAT	Rashaan Salaam rushed for a second-quarter touchdown, Jeff Jaeger kicked two field goals and the Chicago Bears' special teams made several big plays in a 15-13 victory over the Minnesota Vikings on Monday. The Bears (3-5) trailed 3-2 after the first quarter, but scored 13 consecutive points in the second period. Salaam's one-yard scoring run, which capped a seven-play, 58-yard drive, was sandwiched between field goals of 41 and 44 yards by Jaeger that made it 15-3 at the half. Jaeger's second field goal was set up by Mark Carrier interception of a Warren Moon pass. The Bears picked up their first two points on a safety when Kevin Minniefield blocked a punt and punter Mitch Berger knocked the ball went out of the end zone. Chicago's special teams came up big again in the fourth quarter when Sean Harris blocked a field goal attempt that would have put the Vikings ahead by one. Minnesota scored the only points of the second half in the third quarter as Moon found Qadry Ismail on a 54-yard touchdown strike to make it 15-10. The Vikings added a 43-yard Scott Sisson field goal to close the gap to 15-13. Dave Krieg completed 23-of-35 passes for 187 yards with two interceptions for Chicago. Moon was 15-of-26 for 218 yards with a touchdown and interception before suffering a mild right ankle sprain in the third quarter. Chicago linebacker Brian Cox made a huge play in the closing minutes when he stripped backup quarterback Brad Johnson at the 31 and recovered the fumble himself to seal the win for the Bears. The Vikings fell to 5-3, dropping two games back of first-place Green Bay in the NFC Central Division by losing for the third time in four games.
GCAT	These are the leading stories in Albania's main newspapers on Tuesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy. KOHA JONE - The leftist coalition of Socialist, Social Democratic and Democratic Alliance parties won two third of parliament seats. - Socialist Party leader Fatos Nano will be the premier and secretary-general Rexhep Mejdani is likely to become president. - Kavaje town, once the stronghold of the Democrats, turned into a Waterloo for their leader Tritan Shehu who could win only 29 percent in Sunday's runoff. GAZETA SHQIPTARE - Interim Prime Minister Bashkim Fino left for Spain to attend the NATO summitg on alliance enlargement and have talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton. - Two electoral commission members were killed and another two injured in the northern town of Shkoder on Sunday's runoff. - The paper wonders if President Sali Berisha or Genc Pollo will take over the leadership of the Democratic Party after its chairman Tritan Shehu resigned. - Democratic Alliance Party leader Neritan Ceka is seen as the new parliament speaker while Social Democratic leader Skender Gjinushi will be the foreign minister in the cabinet that Fatos Nano is expected to lead. - Italy will offer some 300,000 lire ($176) to every Albanian refugee who would agree to be repatriated. ALBANIA - Democratic Party chairman Tritan Shehu resigned following the defeat of his party in June 29 elections. - Hundreds of monarchy supporters held a demonstration in central Tirana, claiming the majority of Albanians had voted for the monarchy restoration in a referendum on June 29. - The paper bitterly attacks the Alba multinational force, saying it failed to help the country get out of crisis. INDIPENDENT - The paper says that dozens of people were killed or injured across the country over the weekend due to lawlessness and violence. - Central Electoral Commission has yet to officially announce whether referendum on the monarchy restoration was defeated. ZERI I POPULLIT - Albania badly needs a parliament and government which want to work for the better of the country, the OSCE special coordinator for early elections in the Balkan country Catherine Lalumiere said. - Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis hailed the victory of the Socialists in the June 29 elections and said it would help bilateral relations.
GCAT	A Moslem guerrilla faction claimed responsibility for the killing of Algerian union leader Abdelhak Benhamouda, whose death was mourned on Saturday by Algerians who staged a one-day work stoppage in his memory. The Algerian Jihad Islamic Front (FIDA), which is widely believed to be a small Moslem guerrilla group operating mainly in Algiers, said it carried out Tuesday's shooting. "The FIDA announces its responsibility in the attack which targeted Abdelhak Benhamouda, a man who placed himself in the service of the military junta," said a FIDA statement carried by leading Algerian newspapers on Saturday. In the statement, signed by the group's military commander in Algiers, Ahmed Abu Elfida, the group vowed to stage more attacks against the government and its supporters. A better-known Algerian guerrilla group, Armed Islamic Group (GIA), has also warned it will kill more Algerian personalities, residents said, quoting GIA warnings pasted on walls recently in the Algerian capital. Local authorities, aiming at thwarting Moslem rebel car bomb attacks in Algiers, on Saturday announced that vehicles were no longer allowed to stop in the streets of Algiers during the day, Algerian radio said. Offenders of the stop ban, from 7.a.m (0600 GMT) until 7.p.m (1800 GMT), risk losing their driving licences or the police impounding their vehicles. The radio said the ban would go into effect next Wednesday. More than 55 people died in eight bombings in Algiers and surrounding towns in January, according to official statements which blamed Moslem rebels for the explosions. Employees in Algeria, except for those in emergency services like hospitals, stayed away from work on Saturday to mourn Benhamouda, Union Generale des Travailleurs Algeriens (UGTA) officials said. Benhamouda was secretary-general of the UGTA, Algeria's one-million-strong workers' union umbrella. Schoolchildren were sent home on Saturday morning and main offices and shops were closed in Algiers, said residents speaking by telephone. President Liamine Zeroual, in a move dismissing guerrilla threats, on Saturday invited legal opposition parties for talks on parliamentary elections planned for the first half of this year, his office said in a statement. The talks would be held on February 11 to discuss the formation of an independent committee to oversee the polls, said the statement carried by the official Algerian news agency APS. Algeria has been without an elected parliament since 1992 when the authorities cancelled a general election in which Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) had taken a huge lead. The Algerian government bars the now outlawed FIS from fielding candidates to run in the next parliamentary polls. According to official figures, nearly 200 people have been killed in Algeria in massacres and bomb attacks since the Moslem fasting month Ramadan started on January 10. Algerian newspapers put the figure at more than 250. About 60,000 people have been killed since the authorities in January 1992 cancelled the general election.
ECAT	Dade Coutny, Fla., could see an $80 million cash reserve carryover suplus for fiscal year 1996, which ended Sept 30, county officials said Tuesday. A combination of increased property tax revenues and increased property tax values as well a reduced spending in some areas contributed to the projected surplus, said Alex Penelas, Metroplitan Dade County executive mayor, in an interview with Reuters here. The final tally will be known when the county makes its mid-year budget adjustment for fiscal 1997 in the next few weeks, Penelas said.   Penelas, elected to the newly created position Oct 1,  is in New York City to meet with the media, tourism groups, bond raters and investors to discuss Dade County's new government structure as well as Miami's fiscal problems. The county has sold almost $600 million in debt in recent months, including a $437 million water and sewer bond issue. The county debt is rated A1 by Moody's Investors Service Inc and A-plus by Standard & Poor's Corp. Penelas noted that while Miami is an integral part of Dade County, its fiscal problems have not adversely affected the county's overall financial stability. The biggest challenge facing Dade County is the welfare program and how to deal with about 40,000 people coming off the welfare rolls as federal reforms begin to take effect, Penelas said. --U.S. Municipal Desk, 212-859-1650
CCAT	Stockbroker Vickers Ballas Holdings Ltd said on Wednesday it was proposing a one-for-one bonus issue. It said in a statement accompanying its 1996 results the bonus issue would result in an increase in its issued share capital by Singapore $60.88 million to S$121.76 million. The bonus issue was proposed in view of the good performance of the group and "the resultant increase in the capital base of the company will support the growth in business operations and asset base of the group," the statement said.   Vickers also proposed to increase its authorised share capital to S$200 million from S$100 million currently. The company reported that its 1996 net profits rose 41 percent to S$48.55 million. --Singapore newsroom (65-8703080)
CCAT	Shares in Pearson Plc dropped on Wednesday after the company said its managing director Frank Barlow had sold 30,000 shares. The stock was down 15p at 714 by 1155 GMT.   Pearson said Barlow was left with a holding of 38,750 shares following the disposal. The media and leisure group, whose interests range from the Financial Times to waxworks museum Madame Tussauds, gave no reason for the sale. Pearson shares have risen sharply since touching a year's low of 595p on July 31, to reach a peak of 782p on October 30. -- David Holmes, London Newsroom +44 171 542 5106
MCAT	Mexican overnight Cetes rates ended up 60 basis points at 18 percent on Friday from an low unrepresentative previous close, traders said, adding that the rate had nonetheless closed below session highs on a strong peso and low U.S. long bond yields. "The market was very firm due to exchange rate stability," a trader said. The benchmark 48-hour peso ended 4.2 centavos stronger at 7.9070/7.9100 per dollar. The U.S. 30-year Treasury bond was up 15/32 to yield 6.88 percent.   Traders noted there was little volume during the session as many in Mexico were on vacation. Mexican financial markets closed on Thursday, May 1, for Labor Day and will close again to observe the anniversary of the battle of Puebla on Monday, May 5. "There was some dealing in the money market, but rates did not change for much of the day," another trader said. Dealers said rates also fell from initial levels on demand for paper ahead of forecast cuts in primary interest rates.   Money market analysts forecast rates on bellwether 29-day Cetes could fall by up to 75 basis points from a current 19.40 percent at next Tuesday's central bank auction of government securities. The central bank drained 1.055 billion pesos from the system through a combination of three direct Cetes sales and two repos. One of the repos was assigned at four days at a rate of 18.00 percent. Overnight rates on bank paper closed unchanged at 19.25 percent. June contracts for Cetes futures traded on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange closed up 23 centavos at 78.20 pesos. Liquidity of 1.725 billion pesos was scheduled to return to the system on Tuesday, the first working day of next week, from prior central bank participation. (( --Elena Vega, Mexico City newsroom +525 728-9554))
