ECAT	Russia will return to the Eurobond market next week with a jumbo issue for as much as two billion marks ($1.2 billion), a senior Deutsche Bank AG official said on Friday. Georg Krupp, the Deutsche board member responsible for Russia, told a news conference that paperwork on rescheduling $32 billion of former Soviet debt to Western banks was taking longer than expected but would be over in a few months. And in a further sign of Russia's growing creditworthiness, he said Germany's biggest bank had agreed to lend Russia's Gazprom  gas monopoly 1.5 billion marks to finance a new pipeline to Western Europe. Krupp said he had discussed the Eurobond with Finance Minister Alexander Livshits on Thursday. "He again confirmed, and we agreed, that Deutsche Bank has received the mandate to issue the first mark Eurobond for the Russian Federation with a volume of 1.5 to 2.0 billion marks," Krupp said. "We assume that we can go to market with the bond at the end of next week," he added, noting that Russia would hold investor presentations on the bond in Frankfurt and Zurich next week. Deutsche's investment banking subsidiary, Deutsche Morgan Grenfell, is leading the Eurobond with CS First Boston. Russia's debut $1 billion Eurobond last November marked its first return as a sovereign borrower to international capital markets since the Bolshevik revolution. The issue was heavily oversubscribed. It was the biggest ever debut sovereign Eurobond and strong demand from Western investors enabled Russia to raise two or three times more than originally planned. Demand is welling up for the mark offering, too -- Russian officials had been earlier talking of one or 1.5 billion marks. "The way market conditions are now, we can issue a bond of up to two billion marks," Krupp said. He refused to disclose the terms of the bond, which will be hammered out over after the Frankfurt-Zurich roadshow. But he hinted they could be finer than the terms on last November's 9.25 percent dollar issue, which was priced to yield 345 basis points over U.S. Treasury bonds. "It seems Russia has been rated pretty decently by the market since the dollar bond was placed and the rescheduling practically completed," he said. A 1.5 billion mark Eurobond this week from Argentina, which has similar or slightly worse ratings than Russia, was priced aggressively to yield only 195 basis points over German bunds. Krupp said the rescheduling of Soviet commercial bank debt assumed by Russia was almost complete. Under the deal agreed last November, the banks have rescheduled repayment of $24 billion of principal over up to 25 years and $8 billion of interest arrears over 20 years, with seven years' grace in both cases. But closing the deal is being delayed by detailed work of reconciling 30,000 individual loans, most of which have been traded in the secondary market, with their rightful creditors. "The process is running now at high speed. It will take a little more time. We hope that it can be completed in the next two to three months," Krupp said. Delays by the International Monetary Fund in paying out instalments of its $10 billion loan to Russia would not affect the final closure of the bank debt rescheduling, he said. Deutsche's confidence in the Russian market was underlined by an agreement to lend 1.5 billion marks for up to 10 years to Gazprom, which is building a new pipeline from the Yamal gas field to Western Europe, Krupp said. The credit is in addition to a $2.5 billion syndicated loan led by Dresdner Bank, signed in Frankfurt on Friday, to fund the same project. Krupp said the Deutsche loan would enable Gazprom to buy pipes from German engineering group Mannesmann AG. The bank was waiting for export cover from Germany's Hermes export credit insurance agency before signing the deal. ($ = 1.691 German Marks)
MCAT	U.S. T-bonds rose in London on Friday in thin holiday business with dealers saying the market was expected to be confined to range for the rest of the session. The benchmark 30-year bond was at 101-07 yielding 6.407 percent at 1054 GMT versus 101-02 at the Tokyo close. New York's closing price on Wednesday before the Thanksgiving holiday was 100-29. "The market has a positive bias, but should trade for the rest of the day in a pretty tight range," said one trader at a U.S. bank in London. The trader said there was not much interest in the market with so many people still on holiday, and data due on Friday afternoon was unlikely to make much impact. Trading will be abbreviated in New York this session, when the market will close at 1900 GMT. -- October personal income, which is forecast to be unchanged after a 0.6 percent rise in September, and personal spending for October, forecast up 0.3 percent after a 0.1 percent increase the previous month are due at 1330 GMT . -- International Bonds Unit +44 171 542 6176
ECAT	Total direct foreign investment in Romania since the 1989 end of communism rose to $2.2 billion at the end of 1996 from $1.6 billion the previous year, the Romanian Development Agency (ARD) said on Monday. It said the $608.4 million in foreign investment last year came from contributions of capital to newly created joint ventures, increases of capital of existing companies and investment in privatised companies. The largest single foreign investor in Romania is South Korea's Daewoo Heavy Industries Ltd, which last year put $53 million into a Romanian Black Sea shipyard, raising its investment in the Balkan country to $200 million. The South Korean company had previously bought a 51 percent stake in a local car marker, which it plans to expand further before the year 2000 on $1.0 billion investment. Romania hopes foreign investment, now at a paltry level compared with other East European countries, to pick up this year as the new centrist government pledged to support foreign investors by boosting facilities, including tax cuts and foreign ownership of land. Local economists say in order to attract foreign investors cash-strapped Romania will have to speed up restructuring and privatisation, secure a smooth run of the foreign exchange and capital markets and work out of a separate law on portfolio investment. Local media recently said a group of around 20 U.S. and British companies were expected in Romania early in February to look into investment opportunities in chemistry, the heavy and machine-building industries and in the capital market. Envisaged investment by those companies was $10 billion. -- Luli Popescu, Bucharest Newsroom 40-1 3120264
