CCAT	Russia has dropped London-based investment bank N.M. Rothschild as adviser on the sale of a stake in telecoms holding company AO Svyazinvest, the State Property Committee said on Tuesday. "By agreement of both sides, the financial consultants -- a consortium of investment banks led by N.M. Rothschild -- have completed their work on this project," a statement from the State Property Committee, Russia's privatisation ministry, said. The statement did not say who would take over as adviser, and a committee spokesman declined to comment. The London Financial Times said on Tuesday that Russia's Alfa-Bank and Most-Bank would handle the sale in future. The Russian Privatisation Centre, a Russian state fund, had been working with Rothschild on privatising Svyazinvest. The committee, expressing thanks to the privatisation centre and to Rothschild, made clear that both institutions were no longer working on the deal. The committee said that out of a series of options for selling Svyazinvest proposed by Rothschild and by the World Bank, the government had decided to transfer its 38 percent stake in national phone company Rostelekom to Svyazinvest. "In the opinion of (the committee) and the Telecommunications Ministry, the shares of the 'renewed' Svyazinvest will be more attractive to portfolio investors on the one hand, and on the other, privatisatising them will not have a damaging effect on national security," it said. Russia originally intended to sell 25 percent of Svyazinvest, which holds large but minority state shareholdings in 85 regional telecoms companies, to a single strategic investor. Italy's state-owned telecom holding company Stet SpA won a tender last year for this stake, in what would have been Russia's biggest privatisation and inward investment to date, but the deal fell through before completion. Officials had repeatedly said they would sell the stake this year, but the privatisation authorities are now planning to split it up and sell it to portfolio investors. The recent sale of Russia's debut Eurobond and American Depositary Shares in gas monopoly RAO Gazprom have demonstrated enormous interest from portfolio investors in Russian paper. But it remains to be seen whether the Russian authorities will be able to attract foreign investors to Svyazinvest in the way they want without a Western investment bank as adviser. The property committee said work was already underway on privatising Svyazinvest according to the new scheme. "If all sides agree in coordinating their work, it is expected that the first sales of shares of this company will take place at the beginning of next year," the committee said. At 1010 GMT Rostelekom was $2.33 in a weaker market after closing on Monday at $2.42. --Jonathan Lynn, Moscow Newsroom, +7095 941 8520
MCAT	U.S. West Coast crude prices added to early gains by 15 cents, but differentials for Alaska North Slope (ANS) stayed the same as traders failed to strike fixed deals. The West Coast market stayed quiet on Thursday, with players leaving businesses to attend a golf tournament, traders said. The discount for ANS remained $2.30 off November West Texas Intermediate (WTI). Recent strength in crude and weak margins soured them on current offers. Traders saw no effect from a fire at a Shell gasoline distribution terminal in Los Angeles.   Meanwhile, weak margins could force Ultramar to cut runs at its Wilmington, Calif., plant starting in late October. Ultramar said it refused to buy an ANS cargo for November, which would trim its crude input 12,000 barrels-per-day. Tosco Corp was also considering run cuts at its California refineries, traders said. Outright ANS prices rose 15 cents to $22.95/23.25 a barrel, in line with WTI. Bellwether WTI gained on supportive data from Thursday's Energy Information Administration (EIA) report, which showed crude inventories fell 3.3 million barrels last week compared to the API's 417,000 barrels.   Buyers claimed the Ecuadorian government's decision to cut prices for Oriente crude on Thursday would put pressure on ANS. The South American crude competes with ANS out West. Line 63 diffs remained unchanged at $3.20 to $3.00 under spot WTI for November delivery. ARCO will announce November shipping restrictions for the line next week, traders said. California heavy crudes remained flat. Kern River crude was $17.30/17.50 a barrel. Values for Wilmington crude stayed at $18.65/18.75 a barrel. -- David Brinkerhoff, Los Angeles bureau, +1 213 380 2014
CCAT	First Leisure Corp confirmed on Thursday that it planned to invest 55 million stg in new units in 1996/97. The bingo, bowling and nightclubs group said trading in the early part of its new financial year had generally been in line with the second half of last year. But it had been hit by cold weather in the important period just after Christmas. The company said it looked to the medium and long term with confidence and said new investments should underpin a significant growth phase into the next century.   First Leisure reported a nine percent increase in pre-tax profit to 43.7 million stg in the year to October 31. Excluding the benefit of asset disposals, pre-tax profits were up eight percent at 42.1 million stg. The company said it planned a major expansion programme in nightclubs with six openings lined up for this financial year. Its Health & Fitness development programme was reported to be making "significant progress" and contracts have been signed for eight new openings. Excellent results were reported from the Brannigans Music Bars and a significant expansion programme was continuing there. But trading in bingo and theatres fell below expectations. "These (record profits) are driven by excellent results in our three largest divisions where our previous investments have borne fruit as consumer confidence has recovered," chairman Michael Grade said in a statement. "Our developing Bingo business has not yet met our profit expectations but this has been balanced by accelerated progress in a number of other new areas, including the expansion of the Brannigans Music Bar chain and our Health and Fitness clubs." -- London Newsroom +44 171 542 8793
GCAT	Six astronauts boarded the space shuttle Atlantis on Sunday for a predawn blastoff on a mission that will take them to Russia's Mir space station. NASA officials said the countdown was ticking smoothly toward a 4:27 a.m. EST (0927 GMT) launch from Florida's Kennedy Space Centre. The astronaut crew, led by mission commander Mike Baker, began taking their seats aboard the $2 billion spaceship at about 1 a.m. EST (0600 GMT). Joining Baker were copilot Brent Jett and mission specialists Jeff Wisoff, John Grunsfeld, Marsha Ivins and Jerry Linenger. Atlantis was to drop off Linenger on Mir for a four-month stay and pick up John Blaha, who has been aboard the orbiting complex since September. Linenger, a 41-year-old Navy captain and medical doctor, is to spend four months on Mir, performing more than 80 experiments. Atlantis is due to return to the station in May to bring him home. Forecasters were predicting cool but fair weather for the night liftoff. They gave Atlantis a 70 percent chance of getting off the launch pad during its narrow seven-minute launch window. NASA launch commentator Bruce Buckingham said the shuttle's fiery climb to orbit on a northly trajectory should be visible along much of the U.S. East Coast. Atlantis is the first of eight launches planned in 1997. The year is due to end with the first shuttle mission to assemble the NASA-led international space station.
