ECAT	Russia needs to step up efforts to bring inflation within its goal of one percent per month, but it will not rely on money supply limits alone, Central Bank Chairman Sergei Dubinin said on Friday. "In the first quarter of this year there has been little appreciation of the real exchange rate, so we need additional efforts to control inflation," he told a conference on Central and Eastern European capital markets. Dubinin said annual inflation should be about 12 percent in 1997, down from about 22 percent last year when the increase in M2 money supply was about 34 percent. "Last year the depreciation of the rouble against the dollar was less than inflation," he added. He said monthly inflation in the first quarter of this year was averaging 1.5 percent, while depreciation of the exchange rate was less than one percent. Dubinin told Reuters that intermediate money supply targets, which have been a key weapon in the fight against inflation in recent years, would continue to be used. But he said a Lombard window had also been opened, allowing banks to borrow from the central bank using state securities, treasury bills and OFZ government bonds, as collateral. "We have stopped strictly controlling part of the money supply by volume," he said. "We are counting more and more on automatic regulation, because this money is received by banks at a rather high interest rate." Dubinin said this was a flexible market-based way of regulating the liquidity in the banking system and the economy as a whole. "What is important is not so much quantitative limits to M2 or other money supply aggregates but strict observance of market demand for money," he said. --Brian Killen, London newsroom +0171 542 4889
GCAT	The following are top headlines from selected Canadian newspapers. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy. THE GLOBE AND MAIL: - Prime Minister Jean Chretien rules out national tax relief: After deficit is erased, social programs should get any extra money, Chretien says. - Film law sparks federal cabinet clash: PolyGram Filmed Entertainment seeks exemption. - Dole hones attack on issue of ethics: Focus turns to political contributions on eve of second presidential debate. - Ontario Auditor criticizes lax welfare system: Revenue also lost on corporate taxes. - Newfoundland Premier Brian Tobin reveals secret pact on hydro: Quebec agreed in 1984 to discuss altering deal, Tobin says. - Market bullish on Canada: International money managers poured more money into the bond market yesterday in response to Canada's recent parade of positive economic news. Report on Business Section: - Cadillac Fairview Corp buys T. Eaton Co mall stakes: Developer and partners invest more than C$200 million in four regional shopping centres. - Wall Street takes a shine to Canada: Fiscal restraint seen as 'way ahead' of U.S.; bond spread hits 11-year low. - Bre-X faces more claims over gold mine: Partners vie for 40-percent stake. - Borneo Gold shares plummet: Lose 40 percent of value as trading resumes after month-long halt. THE FINANCIAL POST: - Vancouver Stock Exchange error lets Cam-Net trade: Mistake at VSE allows shares of the company, whose former CEO is wanted by the FBI, to change hands briefly. They are unlikely to trade again soon. - General Motors takes fight with CAW to court: GM has filed for court permission to move production equipment from two plants being struck by the CAW. -- Reuters Toronto Bureau 416 941-8100
