MCAT	Implied volatilities for U.S. Treasury bond options pulled back Tuesday in the wake of the Federal Open Market Committee's monetary policy meeting. U.S. central bankers left short-term interest rates unchanged amid continued evidence of moderate economic growth and low inflation. The key federal funds rate that banks charge each other for overnight loans stands at 5.5 percent. October bond volatility slipped to 8.25 percent at the session's end from 8.40 percent on the opening and 8.65 percent the previous session.   Volatility for September options, which expire at the end of the week, fell to 7.0 percent from 7.8 percent at the opening, while December edged down to 8.6 percent from 8.7 percent. Bond options activity was hushed as the market focused on the outcome of the Fed meeting, traders said. Expectations that bond prices are likely to be confined to a range near term also stifled interest in trading options, they said.   At the short end, Eurodollar volatilities eased substantially after heavy buying of December 94.25 calls and stock market jitters had pumped up values during the previous two sessions, brokers said. December fell back to 7.5 percent from 9.0 percent previously and March dropped to 10.8 percent from 11.5 percent. "I don't think vols are going to get much lower," said one Eurodollar options trader. "The market's shown that it can move every now and then."   A U.S. bank that had been a huge buyer of the 94.25 December calls outright and in spreads against sales of 94.25 puts in recent days turned around and sold 5,000 of the calls today, floor traders said. Other firms were noted buying 93.75/94.00 put spreads and selling 94.00 straddles in December, and one bank bought 1,200 June 94.00 straddles. Chicago Derivatives Desk ((312-408-8750)) E-mail: chicago.derivatives.newsroom@reuters.com
ECAT	Britain had its largest current account surplus for nine years in the second quarter of 1996 and its overall annual economic growth rate was revised up to 2.2 percent, the Office for National Statistics said on Tuesday. Official interest rates were left unchanged at 5.75 percent after Monday's monetary policy meeting between Chancellor of the Exchequer (finance minister) Kenneth Clarke and Bank of England Governor Eddie George. The current account deficit for the second quarter showed an unexpected 457 million pound ($712 million) surplus after a deficit of 786 million in the first quarter. Financial markets had expected a second quarter deficit of around 1.2 billion pounds. "This improvement was largely due to record surpluses on trade in services and investment income," the statistics office said. The current account surplus was the first for over a year and the largest since the first quarter of 1987. Gross domestic product (GDP) grew 0.5 percent in the second quarter, up from the 0.4 percent growth government statisticians had previously reported. Annual GDP growth was now put at 2.2 percent compared with the previous estimate of 1.8 percent. "The figures show a healthy and sustainable economic performance," Treasury minister Angela Knight said. City economists said the figures added fuel to Bank of England Governor Eddie George's argument that interest rates should be raised to counter the risk of a future resurgence in inflation as the economy gathers steam. "Monetary policy is clearly too loose," said Kevin Gardiner, an economist at Morgan Stanley. The central bank conducted routine money market operations at unchanged interest rates on Tuesday morning, indicating that Clarke, who has the final say on monetary policy, had ordered no change in official rates at Monday's policy meeting. The Chancellor has cut rates four times since December and, with a general election due by May 1997, is clearly reluctant to raise them again. He overruled the Bank of England's call at the July monetary meeting for rates to be raised to six percent. "The debate will now clearly shift from possible rate cuts to whether the government can resist pressure for a rate rise before the general election," said Ian Stewart, UK economist at Merrill Lynch. A breakdown of the balance of payments figures showed a surplus on investment income in the second quarter of 3.7 billion pounds, the highest figure on record. Services showed a surplus of 1.9 billion pounds while trade in goods showed a marginally lower deficit of 3.6 billion. The revised GDP figures showed construction and a broad range of service industries growing much faster than previously thought. Alex Garrard, an economist at UBS, said recent buoyancy in retailing and signs of recovery in manufacturing suggested economic growth would pick up in the coming months. "With only subdued inflation left in Clarke's stock of feasible excuses, further rate cuts are almost certainly off the agenda for the time being," he said.  ($1=.6420 Pound)
CCAT	Trading company Nissho Iwai Corp said on Tuesday it had filed a shelf registration with the Finance Ministry to issue up to 200 billion yen of corporate bonds, effective for two years from January 25.
GCAT	Moslem worshippers rose from their weekly prayers at Jerusalem's al-Aqsa mosque on Friday to fresh confrontations with Israeli soldiers. Within an hour, three Palestinians were dead and more than 60 wounded. A 30-year-old Palestinian man, his shirt stained with blood from the casualties he helped evacuate, cursed the Israeli prime minister. "Damn you (Benjamin) Netanyahu, what kind of peace is this?" shouted the man. The tiny clinic below the seventh-century Dome of the Rock mosque, Islam's third holiest site, was smeared with blood. Medics bandaged the wounded and sent them off in private vehicles to Jerusalem's Makassed hospital. Women screamed in horror as hundreds of Israel's paramilitary border police, wearing bullet-proof vests and helmets, stormed the mosque and charged demonstrators. Bullets flew in all directions as demonstrators fled for cover. "God take revenge on you, you beasts," an elderly woman shouted as Israeli police used batons on a group of women sheltering below an arched gate of the Dome of the Rock. One woman fell to the ground while the others rushed inside the building. The confrontation was the bloodiest at al-Aqsa since 1990 when Israeli security forces killed 17 worshippers during clashes with stone-throwing Palestinians. Friday's violence was the latest round of Israeli-Palestinian fighting that erupted on Wednesday after Israel opened a tourist tunnel adjacent to the al-Aqsa mosque compound. Palestinians say the tunnel weakened the foundations of ancient buildings surrounding the mosque and threatened the holy sites. Israel said the tunnel did not harm the site. At least 53 Palestinians and 14 Israeli soldiers were killed in three days of gun battles across the West Bank and the Gaza Strip. Israeli security forces, anticipating violence after Friday prayers, deployed thousands of security forces around the Old City of Jerusalem and at the gates to the mosque. Witnessess said the fighting erupted when a few young worshippers began throwing stones at Israeli security forces. Israeli officials said hundreds of rocks were thrown. Witnesses said the Israelis, stationed on buildings above the compound and at the gates, responded to the stones by unleashing barrages of live ammunition at the crowds. Many of the wounded were hit in the torso. Ayman Idkaidek, 28, took a direct hit to his head. Another man killed was also hit in the head while the third victim took a bullet in the chest. "Look. This is what Netanyahu is doing," said a 42-year-old Palestinian man at the hospital, displaying a piece of Idkaidek's shattered skull.
GCAT	A Japan-South Korea summit meeting had a stormy start on Saturday as Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto was forced to apologise for inflammatory remarks by his spokesman about Tokyo's use of sex slaves in World War Two. Noisy protests by hundreds of ultra rightwingers against President Kim Youg-sam's visit added to the tension at the one-day meeting which had been intended to showcase the good relations between the two countries. Other issues of national pride at stake include competing claims for islands. The rightwingers drove 150 trucks with loudspeakers through this resort loudly denouncing "unreasonable South Koreans demands" for Japan to apologise for World War Two actions. Hashimoto was on the defensive from the moment the summit opened because of remarks by Japan's Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama that there was a "social background" to Tokyo's use of sex slaves, or so-called "comfort women", in the war. About 200,000 captured comfort women from Korea, the Philippines, China, Indonesia and the Netherlands were forced to work in front-line brothels in one of the darkest chapters of Japan's World War Two past. "It is odd teaching them (Japanese schoolchildren) of the comfort women issue, without teaching the social background of an authorised prostitution system at that time," Kajiyama, the government's top spokesman, said on Friday. "When they (comfort women) went to the fronts, they got money. Among them, there were some who were drafted," he added in remarks made only to Japanese reporters but later reluctantly confirmed by shocked Japanese officials. In an opening summit lunch, Hashimoto wasted no time in distancing himself from the comments. "On the issue of comfort women, I am worried about the impact of reported remarks by Chief Cabinet Secretary Kajiyama," Hashimoto told Kim. "I am sorry. That (view) is not our real intention." Repeating remarks he made in a summit meeting in South Korea with Kim last June, Hashimoto said there was no way for Japan to defend itself on the comfort women issue. "At no other time has women's honour and dignity been hurt more than in this case," Hashimoto said. Kim, already angry at the rightwingers reception, told Hashimoto South Koreans were outraged by Kajiyama's remarks. "The timing of the reported remarks is unfortunate. Explanations must be given to satisfy the Korean people who were shocked by the remarks," Kim told Hashimoto. "This issue is very sensitive on the part of the Korean people." A decades-long row over Japan's failure to fully apologise and pay official compensation to the women flared again earier this month when the Asian Women's Fund, a private group set up in 1995 with heavy Japanese government support, paid money to seven ageing Korean women. South Korea does not want government-to-government compensastion but believes Tokyo should compensate the sex slaves directly. The island ownership issue is equally emotive. Japan calls the two small islands Takeshima and South Korea calls them Tokto. They are surrounded by rich fishing grounds. Tokyo has claimed the islands since it started its 1905 colonial rule of Korea. South Koreans say they have owned the islands for centuries.
MCAT	The coupon rate for the Philippines' five-year fixed-rate Treasury note fell to 15.0 percent from the previous auction rate of 15.625 percent, the Bureau of Treasury said on Tuesday.   The average rate slipped to 14.927 percent from the previous auction's 15.510 percent. The five-year T-notes are auctioned every other month. The auction committee accepted 3.0 billion pesos out of 7.136 billion pesos worth of tenders. - Manila newsroom 63 2 8418938 Fax 8176267
ECAT	Rural lobby group Federated Farmers, hurting from the high New Zealand dollar, called on Thursday for government spending restraint to ease inflationary pressures. Federated Farmers President Malcolm Bailey was speaking to reporters at an exporters' summit in Wellington to discuss the sector's difficulties with the strong currency. "There is a problem. We believe that the dollar has climbed too far, too fast, and that that is putting a lot of pressure on the export sector," Bailey said.   "It's impacting quite negatively on farmers' income. We are not seeing farms' input costs coming down like they should be, so we are caught in a bit of squeeze. We are saying the dollar is overvalued." Bailey said the solution was not to "throw out the baby with the bathwater" and make fundamental changes to the Reserve Bank framework, which targets 0-2 percent underlying inflation. "We think inflationary pressures are largely coming from the government sector. We are calling for restraint. We are saying whatever promises were made during the election campaign to increase spending should be set aside," Bailey said.   Bill Gallagher, representing the NZ Manufacturers Federation, said the rate of appreciation in the exchange rate was affecting profitability and investment and would eventually impact on jobs. "The export-led recovery appears to be stalling. It's essential to make the exchange rate lower for the exporters." Gallagher, who is also chief executive of the Hamilton-based Gallagher Group which makes electric fence equipment, said the summit would look at ways of adjusting monetary policy to the business cycle.   Asked if the Reserve Bank should intervene directly in the currency market, Gallagher said: "It's likely to be a short-term fix. Short-term fixes tend to have long-term consequences." Reserve Bank Governor Don Brash, arriving to address the meeting, said he recognised exporters were under "very considerable pressure". -- Wellington newsroom 64 4 473-4746
