GCAT	World Jewish Congress head Edgar Bronfman, who led the fight over unclaimed Jewish assets in Switzerland, was named on Wednesday to temporarily take a seat on the new Swiss Fund to aid Holocaust survivors. The executive board of the World Jewish Restitution Organisation (WJRO), which Bronfman also leads, made the decision after Nobel Peace Prize winner Elie Wiesel resigned from the seven-member Fund board, citing statements "made in the Swiss press." Wiesel, who had also been named international chairman of the Fund, bowed out after Swiss officials said his additional title would carry no power. WJC sources said there had been difficulty finding a permanent replacement as many potential candidates felt Wiesel had been insulted. Four of the fund's members are named by the Swiss government and three by the WJRO, which is a branch of the WJC. WJC Executive Director Elan Steinberg said Bronfman would serve only on an interim basis until a permanent replacement was found. He said he expected that a replacement would be named at a WJRO meeting in Jerusalem on June 2. "Mr Bronfman was asked to serve now so that the fund can begin its work," he said. Jewish sources said several guidelines have been set for the $190 million Fund that was set up with donations from Swiss banks and industries after a spate of international cirticism over the Swiss role in the Second World War as bankers for the Third Reich. The sources said that about 500,000 survivors would be eligible for money from the fund and that need would be the prime criterion rather than extent of suffering. Germany has come under criticism from Jewish groups for basing some reparation payments on the length of time a survivor spent in a concentration camp or a ghetto.
ECAT	Strict fiscal discipline and tight monetary policy have contributed to the current slowing in Israel's economy, but the country's Finance Minister said the slowdown is thought to be only temporary. "The slowdown in the economy is evident," said Dan Meridor, Israel's Finance Minister.  But he added: "I do believe it is temporary." Speaking to an Israeli investment conference here, Meridor told investors that Israel's economic growth could be less than 4.0 percent in 1997 but he added that the country's growth prospects will be clearer in about two to three months.   Meridor said he hopes the rate of inflation for Israel will come in between 7.0 to 10 percent in 1997. Turning to the budget deficit, Meridor said: "We succeeded in cutting the budget deficit...setting the target in 1997, which will be around 2.8 percent of GDP." But the Finance Minister added, "We still fight every day to keep the budget in line." In the way of reforms, Meridor said the government is planning to move ahead with about 25 structural reforms.   Of those, he said the government is beginning the liberalization of the public transportation bus company.  "We are in the process of opening this monopoly to competition. We are doing it gradually but it is a major change." He also said the government is looking to do more in the way of privatizations. He said the government's Bank Leumi shares are up for sale and also added that El Al, the Israeli airline, needs to be sold. "We have liberalized a lot and are still in the process." In addition, Meridor said that there will be new public sector wage agreements in 1997.   "This year will be a year of new wage agreements in the public sector and these will have a dramatic effect if not conducted in the right way in coming years," he added. As for the Middle East peace process, Meridor said it is important to build economic cooperation, economic stability and economic prosperity with Israel's neighbors. "There is difficulty in the political process. We need to overcome that but a better economic sitution may help us all," he added. (( --Diane Craft, 212-859-1946))
MCAT	Midwest direct cash hog prices Thursday were seen steady to $0.50 per cwt higher, supported by reduced hog marketings as producers continue to concentrate on harvesting, livestock dealers said. Clear weather in much of the Corn Belt was allowing ample opportunities for producers to get serious about harvesting. Top prices for Iowa and southern Minnesota hogs delivered at the plant could range from $58.50 to $59.00. Illinois buyers said top prices could range from $57.50 to $58.00 at the plant. Indiana and Ohio buyers said top prices at the plant could range from $58.00 to $58.50.   Interior Iowa/southern Minnesota actual marketings Tuesday totaled 101,000 head, below that day's estimate of 105,000, according to USDA. Wednesday's estimate was 100,000 head. The lighter marketings were reflected in USDA's lower hog slaughter estimate Wednesday of 348,000 head, compared with 367,000 a week ago. The week-to-date estimate was 1.074 million head, about 1.0 percent below a week ago, but 2.9 percent above a year ago. Support from the lighter supply was partly offset by weakening pork prices, with midday carlot pork prices showing declines in bellies and lean trimmings. --Bob Janis 312-408-8720--
