ECAT	Turkey's recent move to support small and medium factories (KOBI) by introducing new incentives would boost the Turkish economy in coming years, a state bank general manager said. Yenal Ansen, general manager of Halkbank which specialises in low-interest loans to artisans and KOBIs, said the decree defining loan limits to KOBIs and interest rates on them showed the government was intent on supporting KOBIs' activities. "The decree which took effect on October 16, shows KOBIs are fundamentals of the Turkish economy as they play an important role in raising exports, increasing employment and quality in production," Ansen told Reuters in an interview. There are more than 200,000 KOBIs in Turkey, half of which receive finances from Halkbank in their investments. Ansen said Halkbank which supplied 124 trillion lira of loans to artisans and KOBIs in January-October 1996, targeted 140 trillion lira for this year and double this figure for 1997. Loans to KOBIs stood at around 50 trillion lira in 1995. The bank, with 78 percent of its total loans channelled to artisans and KOBIs, named 1996 "the year of KOBIs" and speeded up fund allocation for them and introduced an information service to help increase efficiency in this sector. "We see the return of low-interest credits we provide to KOBIs in the form of a production increase in this sector and new value added to the overall economy," Ansen said. "If we think about making profit, then we cannot provide these low-interest loans. But without making loss, we will continue to support them as our loans return to the system through new machinery or a newly employed person," he added. Ansen said they gave priority to the manufacturing industry which contributes directly to economic improvement. The new government decree introduced upper loan limits for different provinces -- 25 billion lira at 20 percent annual interest rate per KOBI in underdeveloped provinces and 20 billion lira at 30 percent in developed regions. The loan maturity will be three years for both regions. Turkey's year-on year wholesale inflation stood at 82.8 percent in October. According to the decree, the Treasury will separately channel five trillion lira to KOBIs as a first tranche, with the amount to be raised in line with future demand. Ansen said he expected the Treasury's part to go much higher in the 1997 budget, currently being discussed in parliament. -- Istanbul newsroom +90-212-275 08 75
GCAT	A Greek appeals court has approved the extradition of a woman wanted in Germany in connection with a 1986 West Berlin disco bombing that killed three people and wounded 200, court officials said on Wednesday. The woman, identified as Andrea Hausler, was arrested while vacationing in northern Greece in October with her two-year-old son and a male friend. Greek police have said that Hausler is the sister of a key suspect in the disco bombing, in which scores of off-duty U.S. military personnel were hurt. Two U.S. soldiers and a Turkish woman were killed in the attack, which prompted a U.S. air strike against Libya. Court officials said there were no charges against Hausler in Greece and she would probably leave soon for Germany. Socialist Justice Minister Evangelos Yannopoulos will have the final say and must sign her extradition order. Officials said Tuesday's court recommendation had not reached Athens. On a number of past occasions In the past, Greece's socialist governments have refused to extradite guerrilla suspects for what were deemed politically motivated crimes and this was seen as a test case for new Prime Minister Costas Simitis. Hausler is the sister of a woman identified as Verena C., 37, who was detained in Berlin in early October and accused of planting the bomb in the disco. German prosecutors have given no details on what role they believe Hausler might have played in the bombing. Berlin prosecutors arrested Verena C. and her Palestinian ex-husband, Ali C., saying she was suspected of planting the deadly bomb at his request. The United States blamed Libya for the attack on the "La Belle" disco and responded by bombing the Arab state, killing at least 15 people, including an adopted 15-month-old daughter of leader Muammar Gaddafi and wounding more than 100. German prosecutors said they believed Verena C. had planted the bomb at the request of Ali C. and another suspect, Yasser Shraydi, who was extradited to Germany from Lebanon in May this year. They believe the attack was orchestrated from the Libyan embassy in East Berlin. They have also issued arrest warrants for three former members of the Libyan embassy in East Berlin -- identified only by the surnames Elamin, Keshlaf and Al Abani -- and a Libyan secret service member named Rashed. The prosecutors believe those suspects provided the explosives and helped organise the bombing but that they are now back in their homeland.
GCAT	A Sicilian  politician and former president of the Palermo soccer club was arrested on suspicion of collusion with the Mafia on Friday, police said. They said Liborio Polizzi, 48, a centre-left councillor for sport and tourism in the Palermo provincial government, was suspected of providing safe housing for self-confessed Mafia killer Salvatore Cucuzza. Cucuzza, who was arrested last year, has admitted he took part in several murders, including that in 1982 of Pio La Torre, leader in Sicily of the now-defunct Italian Communist Party and a former president of the island's regional government. Polizzi entered politics in 1996, a year after he was sacked as president of Palermo soccer club.
