MCAT	The following is a direct contribution from statistician F.O. Licht in Ratzeburg, Germany. Please address any queries to Helmut Ahlfeld on +00 49 4541 88920. COFFEE: World market for October 3, 1996 Robusta futures in London kept early losses up to the close as aggressive hedge selling by the origins met with very little roaster buying interest. The downside was supported by some scale-down manufacturer buying at the lows. November lost $17 to close at $1,495 a tonne. In New York arabica futures closed higher and the December/March spread widened again to 5.15 cents/lb. This is due to tight nearby supplies caused by the lateness of the crops which is making the period of tight supplies stretched out longer than would otherwise have been possible and is making some roasters and traders uneasy. Trade sources said that there seems to be very little coffee available for October/November even at steep premiums. Under the ACPC retention plan there should be 500,000 bags less of Central American exports but this was to be offset by 1 million more bags from Colombia. However, it is not yet sure whether Colombia can fill the gap due to transport problems. It was said that whatever milds are available are being taken by European roasters who are outbidding US counterparts. FUNDAMENTALS BRAZIL - Brazil's coffee farmers are looking ahead to 1997/98 and based on current flowerings, very early signs are that output in key states will be below the 1996/97 levels. However, a more precise assessment cannot be made before November, when the flowerings have begun setting, giving agronomists a more concrete idea of crop size. But the fact most regions will see an 'off' year in the crop cycle where there is a larger harvest every other year means even at this early stage, that agronomists expect a drop in output. Some predict falls of up to 50 percent in regions that have been hit by dry weather such as Espirito Santo and the Zona da Mata Region in Minas Gerais. Other traders are considering a worst/best case scenario of 21 to 24 million bags. UNITED KINGDOM - UK broker GNI said it expects world coffee production in 1996/97 to fall short of consumption by 4.486 million 60-kg bags. In its October commodity perspective report. GNI said world production in 1996/97 is likely to reach 94.663 million bags, while consumption will climb to 99.149 million bags. GNI added the production shortfall will see world stocks fall to 21.4 million bags at the end of the period, down from almost 40 million bags two seasons ago. However, GNI forecasts that the recent trend of deficit production years will be halted in 1997/98, when production should climb to 103.3 million bags, compared with consumption of 100.6 million bags. ICO - Coffee exports to all destinations by exporting members of the International Coffee Organization (ICO) during August 1996 totalled 5.460 million bags, down from 5.918 million bags exported the same month the previous year, preliminary ICO estimates show. This brought total exports in October/August 1995/96 up to 65.092 million bags, which compares to 59.234 million bags the same period in 1994/95. Brazil's market share in October/August 1995/96 dropped to 17 percent from 25 percent the same period last year, while Colombia's market share reached 15 percent, practically unchanged from last year. Indonesia's exports surged to 4.443 million bags, up from 2.641 million bags shipped the same period the previous year. NORWAY - Norway imported 52,895 bags of coffee in August 1996, 13 percent more than was imported the same month the previous year. That brought total imports since the beginning of 1996 up to 513,100 bags, 25 percent more than was imported the same period in 1995. Total imports in calendar year 1995 dropped sharply by 18 percent to 662,100 bags. Major suppliers of green coffee in January/August 1996 were Guatemala (71,600 vs 10,100 bags), Mexico (65,300 vs 54,300 bags), Brazil (104,300 vs 172,400 bags) and Colombia (111,300 vs 73,600 bags).
CCAT	The move by South Korea's two largest carmakers  to inject cash into a core unit of the troubled Kia Group signals  a joint effort by existing auto companies to block newcomer Samsung,  analysts said on Friday. Kia announced on Thursday that Hyundai Motor, the country's largest  carmaker, and unlisted Daewoo Motor Co had agreed in principle to  buy stakes in Kia Steel Co, a specialty steelmaker that is one of  Kia's weakest affiliates. Kia Group's flagship is Kia Motors Corp. Under the agreement, Hyundai, Daewoo and Kia would form a consortium  with each having equal stakes to run Kia Steel. A Kia statement said  the three companies had agreed to start working-level negotiations  to sort out details. Analysts said the agreement, which would ease pressures on Kia in  negotiations with creditors, underscored concerns about Samsung Group's  entry into South Korea's crowded car industry. "What this highlights is the growing alliance between the three companies.  There is a lot of bad blood between Kia and Samsung," said Hun Sok  Kang, auto analyst at ING Barings. Henry Morris, managing director of Coryo International (H.K.) Ltd,  said Hyundai and Daewoo made a key defensive move. "They wanted to keep Kia Motors from falling into the hands of Samsung.  This also gets the public used to the idea of them assisting Kia,  possibly paving the way for them to make a bid for Kia Motors," Morris  said. While Samsung has consistently denied any interest in acquiring Kia  Motors, it was a leaked internal Samsung report suggesting the need  for restructuring the country's auto industry that accelerated Kia  Group's current crisis. Samsung has said it would begin producing passenger cars from next  March with production reaching 80,000 units in the first year. Analysts said Samsung was still interested in acquiring Kia Motors  as a short-cut into the industry's top ranks, although public opinion  may cause it to delay revealing its interest. "Samsung is not going to give up. Right now Samsung is doing everything  it can to facilitate takeover of Kia," said Nam Seung-soo, auto analyst  at Daishin Economic Research Institute. "Given what has been happening, Samsung would want to wait for things  to quiet down," said Kang of ING Barings. The agreement on Kia Steel came on the eve of a crucial meeting of  Kia creditors to discuss steps on the fate of the embattled conglomerate.  Creditors were set to meet at 0600 GMT. Kia creditors failed to produce a detailed bailout plan at a meeting  on Wednesday after ruling that the group's self-rescue plans were  not sufficient. Creditors put Kia Group under their protection on July 15 after determining  that Kia affiliates were on the verge of defaulting on debt payments.  Kia's debts totalled 9.5 trillion won ($10.6 billion) as of the end  of May. Creditors have demanded that executives of the eighth-ranked business  resign and that Asia Motors, the group's commercial vehicle maker,  be sold. In a desperate move before Wednesday's meetings, Kia announced harsher  self-rescue measures, including a cut in the number of its domestic  units to five from the current 28 through sell-offs, mergers and spin-offs. Kia also said Asia Motors would sell off part of its assets before  being absorbed by Kia Motors to serve as assembly plants. But creditors  said they worried that the plan would worsen the financial status  of the flagship. ($1 = 890.80 won)
MCAT	CME live cattle futures held gains late, bolstered by the strong tone to cash cattle markets while feeder cattle finished steady to lower but off the day's lows, traders said. Live cattle closed up 0.050 to 0.275 cent per lb with June up the least at 65.225 cents as late fund rolling pared gains. Feeder cattle ended unchanged to 0.150 cent a lb lower with August off 0.025 at 76.925 cents after setting a new high of 77.100 cent. Live cattle moved higher, buoyed by recent gains in wholesale beef prices and this week's higher cash cattle prices. Traders shrugged off news that beef prices slipped at midday, with USDA quoting boxed beef cut-out values down $0.57 to $0.94 per cwt after several days of gains. Those gains pushed beef prices on Tuesday to their highest level since December 4, 1995. Overhead resistance and fund rolling clipped gains late in the live cattle pit, traders said. Start of the "Goldman roll", rolling of long June positions into August by various houses for Goldman Sachs added to overhead resistance from an expected break in cash markets going into summer. Expectations cash markets were at or approaching a near-term top kept a lid on the market, traders said. Retailers are almost finished booking beef for Memorial Day advertisements. As a result, beef prices could ease and bids could be pressured for fed cattle next week or the following week, some sources said.   Choice-type cattle sold at $69 per cwt Wednesday, the highest level since late February, and could reach $70 by next week before prices start a summer decline. Next week Friday's Cattle-on-Feed report is expected to confirm high on-feed supplies. Early indications on the report point to likely larger and possible record-large on-feed supplies, they said. No matter what the percent of placements during April, "the fact remains we have a hell of an increase on feed versus a year ago," said Chuck Levitt, senior livestock analyst for Alaron Trading Corp. "We are going to have increasing numbers into the summer period from the late spring." Cargill Investor Services, Refco, Dean Witter and FIMAT Futures USA notably bought August and sold June, traders said. ADM Investor Services, LIT division of First Options, R.J. O'Brien and ABN Chicogo Corp bought while RBH sold early. Losses were pared late in the feeder cattle pit as corn futures set back, traders said. Prices had been dragged down by local profit-taking early with commission house closing sell stops weighing on August late. This offset rolling of long May positions into August, traders said. Although the latest CME feeder cattle index slipped, overall demand for feeders remains strong, they added. The latest CME feeder cattle index was off $0.14 to $73.20 per cwt. However, feeder cattle prices at the key Amarillo market this week were up $1.00 to $2.00 per cwt, USDA reported and at Oklahoma City, prices were firm to $2.00 higher. Refco bought August at the close. R.J. O'Brien bought May early. E.D.&F. Man and LIT division of First Options spread long August/short May and Refco spread long October/short May, pit sources added. ((Jerry Bieszk 312-408-8725))
ECAT	The economies of the Pacific region will grow slightly faster in 1997 and 1998 while inflation will continue to decline, the Pacific Economic Cooperation Council (PECC) think-tank said in its annual forecast released on Tuesday. "The Asia Pacific region is forecast to achieve a weighted average real Gross Domestic Product (GDP) growth of 4.1 percent for 1997 and 1998, following four percent growth in 1996," the PECC said. "The best way to describe such an outcome would be as a high and sustainable plateau," it added. It noted much of the growth acceleration in 1996 was the result of stronger economic performances in Japan and the US. "Excluding Japan and the the U.S., real GDP growth is expected to jump from 5.0 to 5.5 percent in 1997 and to 5.7 percent in 1998." The forecast said the excellent inflation performance of 1996 was not a fluke. The weighted average rate of inflation fell to 3.6 percent from 5.2 percent, with Russia excluded, the PECC said. "Further improvement in inflation is forecast," it added. The PECC said there were some economic problems in the region, "But they appeared to have captured all of the media attention." Turning to individual economies, the PECC said, "Inflation is forecast to rise in both Indonesia and Vietnam, but the levels are well within the range that both economies have been able to manage in the past." But it said, "...the financial situation in Russia is so unsettled that price stability is not in view." "Monetary authorities can correctly claim victory against inflation, but they cannot end the fight. While they are responsible to prevent a resurgence, however, they are getting help from developments in the world econmy,' it said. The PECC is a non-governmental organisation devoted to economic cooperation in the Pacific Rim. The report covered 20 countries.
GCAT	The Immigration and Naturalisation Service said on Sunday it did not know that one of the men charged with plotting to bomb New York subways was a suspected Islamic extremist when he was released from custody in February. "We had no information whatsoever this man was a terrorist," INS spokesman Brian Jordan said. He also said that an immigration judge, who was not part of the INS, made many of the decisions in the case of Gazi Ibrahim Abu Mezer, including granting an asylum hearing and lowering his bail. New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani complained on Saturday that the INS should not have allowed Abu Mezer, 23, to be released after he asked for asylum on grounds that Israel would persecute him as a suspected member of a "known terrorist organisation." "I think it is appropriate to question why this person was allowed into the country announcing that he was part of a terrorist group in Israel," the mayor said. Mezer and Lafi Khalil, 22, were arrested in a Thursday morning raid of a Brooklyn apartment where five bombs were found. Police said they shot the two suspects in the raid as they reached for weapons. According to Jordan, the INS let Abu Mezer return voluntarily to Canada the first two times they caught him trying to illegally enter the country through the state of Washington. But the third time, in January 1997, they detained him. According to a U.S. Justice Department official, Canada refused to allow him to return because Abu Mezer had been convicted of using stolen credit cards and assault in Canada. Jordan said the INS then tried to deport Abu Mezer to a third country, but "for reasons we still can't understand" the immigration judge lowered his bail from $15,000 to $5,000. Another Middle Eastern man, who is in jail on unrelated charges, paid the bail, immigration sources told Reuters. In April, Jordan said, Abu Mezer asked for political asylum. The judge agreed to a hearing in January 1998, but in June Abu Mezer withdrew the request for asylum and was given a standard 60 days to leave the country, Jordan said. Whether the men were acting on their own or were supported by another group remains an important issue in the investigation. Law enforcement sources said the suspects were using phones in their local laundromat and grocery store to call the Palestinian resistance movement Hamas. Hamas denied any link.
