ECAT	British trade figures due on Wednesday will probably show the trade deficit with the rest of the world widened in December, according to a Reuters poll of economists. Their consensus estimate was for a December trade gap of 1.014 billion stg after a November shortfall of 959 million. The December global trade data will be released on Wednesday at 0930 GMT at the same time as January figures for trade with non-European Union countries. January trade with EU nations will be included in the January global figures due in March. Economists said last month's figures showed a surprise fall in exports. They will watch keenly to see if that phenomenon has continued. "While we do expect sterling's rise to depress export growth, this will take some time to work through," said Ciaran Barr, UK economist at Deutsche Morgan Grenfell. "Accordingly, we expect a modest rebound in non-EU export levels in this month's data." The Reuter poll has an estimate of 793 million stg for Britain's non-EU trade deficit in January, down from 844 million in December. The pound has risen about 16 percent on a trade-weighted basis since last August. A rising currency classically produces a "J curve" effect and this time is no exception. As a currency appreciates it cuts import prices and raises export prices. With trade volumes slow to react to price changes, the trade gap will narrow, in value terms, in the short-run -- the so-called J curve. But as price changes shift the dynamics of supply and demand, the strong pound will eventually force a deterioration of Britain's trade position as export markets shy away from the higher prices imposed by the pound. The reverse, of course, applies to imports which look ever cheaper to the now confident British consumer. "Once the beneficial impact of sterling upon export and import prices has washed through the system we anticipate a marked widening in the deficit as the loss of competitiveness feeds through into volumes," said David Philpotts, UK economist at Schroders. Barr agreed that the underlying trend in 1997 will be for higher trade deficits. For Britain's global trade gap, Philpotts said the fall in import prices was already being more than offset by an acceleration in import volumes. He noted that the non-EU trade deficit widened by 145 million pounds to 844 million in December and forecast a global trade deficit of 1.2 billion stg this time. Philpotts said evidence from the Confederation of British Industry suggested export volumes improved slightly in the New Year. The CBI's monthly industrial trends survey showed the balance of manufacturers reporting falling exports in December was minus 15 percent -- i.e. 15 percent more firms said exports fell than said they rose. That figure fell to minus eight percent in the January survey but widened back out to minus 12 in February. "With import penetration rising strongly, we are sceptical whether there will be any improvement in the non-EU trade deficit in January," Philpotts said. -- London Newsroom +44 171 542 5109
MCAT	The dollar closed moderately weaker against the yen on Monday after two senior Japanese politicians suggested interest rates in Japan might soon head higher, currency experts said. The Bank of Japan's (BOJ) official discount rate has been at a record low of 0.5 percent since September 1995. The remarks fueled demand for yen in Asia, which carried over when trade got underway in Europe and New York. "They're buying yen and selling everything that's been bought the last couple of weeks," said Ben Strauss, an assistant vice president at Bank Julius Baer and Co.   The dollar closed at 111.09/16 yen and 1.5304/11 marks, down from 111.40/45 yen and 1.5311/14 marks at the open. Shizuka Kamei, head of the Liberal Democratic Party press office, was quoted in news reports as saying on Monday that a rise in Japan's official discount rate will probably be considered after general elections. Elections are set for October 20. Separately, Ichiro Ozawa, head of the main opposition New Frontier Party or Shinshinto, also said on Monday that Japan's interest rate levels must be corrected. The BOJ declined to comment.   Although the politicians' comments jolted a foreign exchange market sensitive to signs that rates in Japan will climb, some analysts dismissed the comments as a ploy to please Japanese savers dissatisfied with the country's rock-bottom interest rates. "I view it mainly as political posturing ahead of the election," said Brian McCarthy, a market analyst at Ruesch International. "I don't think either party is serious about raising rates without economic justification for it," he added.   Growing optimism that the European Union will successfully launch a common currency as planned in January 1999 continued to pressure the mark relative to some other European currencies, currency experts said. The European Union's monetary committee meets on Tuesday to move forward on key factors including a budget stability pact for countries joining the single currency. "I think that there's no question the overall consensus of the market is that EMU (European Monetary Union) will go ahead and will go ahead on schedule," said William Marr, manager of foreign exchange at Credit Commerciale De France.   "It's just a question now of a little bit of jockeying in terms of what the market consensus is on who are going to be the first members," Marr said. The mark traded around 989.75/0.25 Italian lira and 3.3784/87 French francs in late dealings, down from 990.75/1.00 lira and 3.3817/22 francs earlier in the session. Expectations that Italy will soon re-enter the European Exchange Rate Mechanism (ERM) also bolstered the lira. "The market is reluctant to sell off lira with the possibility the French and Germans will insist on lira appreciation before ERM entry," Ruesch's McCarthy said.   The lira crashed out of the ERM during a currency crisis in September 1992. Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi requested last week that talks start quickly on the level at which the lira might re-enter the system. Elsewhere, the dollar closed at 1.2541/46 Swiss francs, off from 1.2562/72 at the open. The dollar ended little changed at Canadian $1.3530/35 compared with C$1.3531/36. The pound inched up to $1.5633/40 from $1.5628/35 and the Australian dollar rose to $0.7873/78 from $0.7861/66. -- Donna Sells 212 859 1668
