MCAT	CSCE coffee futures posted losses for the third consecutive session Wednesday, battered by a steady dose of commission house and speculative selling, traders said. Benchmark December futures fell 2.00 cents per lb on the day, to 112.20, having traded from 116.25 to 111.75. Second-month March lost 1.65, to settle at 103.55. Today's downturn came despite a substantial drawdown in U.S. consumer stocks last month. The Green Coffee Associaton of New York reported Tuesday that supplies of green coffee housed in U.S. warehouses declined in September by 205,000 60-kg bags, to 1,611,000 bags. Most traders had expected GCA stocks to fall by 100,000 to 200,000 bags. "Everyone knows there is a tight supply of coffee," said Merrill Lynch analyst Judith Ganes. "But this market has come up so much (that) a bit of a correction is to be expected. "The point is, if we had not trended higher the last two weeks, it may have responded to the GCA data," Ganes added." Nearby supply jitters carried the spot December contract to a six-week high of 116.30 cents on Friday -- up some 13 percent since the start of October -- and pushed out the December/March switch to a hefty 9.00 cents.   The nearby switch eased slightly Wednesday, ending at 8.65 cents compared to 9.00 cents at the close Tuesday. Dealers said the GCA figures did prompt a round of trade buying at the open, which carried the market to its intraday highs. But origin selling above 115.00 cents basis December quickly stemmed the gains and turned the momentum to the downside. Keen roaster interest was noted below the 112.50 level, but a late bout of local selling kept prices down, dealers said. Technically, traders said the December contract's ability to hold support at 111.50 cents today could be viewed as constructive. They put December's next downside target at 110.25. To the upside, strong resistance was noted at 118.50. On the fundamental side, traders continued to keep an eye on the trucker strike in Colombia, which entered its third day Wednesday. Exporters said the work stoppage has halted all shipments of coffee to Colombian ports. The day's turnover was relatively heavy, at an estimated 9,863 lots. --Patricia Avidan, New York Commodities Desk +1 212 859 1640
ECAT	Estonia's trade deficit rose to 1.6 billion kroons in March compared to 1.1 billion kroons the month before, the statistics office said on Monday. Estonia's exports were three billion kroons and imports 4.6 billion kroons in March, it added in a statement.   Exports rose by 7.1 percent and imports by 17.9 percent in March compared to February. The trade deficit with Russia increased from 61.6 million kroons in January to 373.8 million kroons in March. Estonia exported to 78 countries and imported from 106 countries, the office said. The European Union accounted for 51.3 percent and CIS countries for 20.9 percent of total exports. From total imports, the European Union had 56.2 percent and CIS countries 21.6 percent. The trade deficit was largest with Finland (573.9 million kroons) and the surplus the largest with Latvia (189.3 million kroons). -- Eva Palu, Tallinn Newsroom, +372 630 8400, reuters@reuters.ee
ECAT	South Carolina's gross state product grew 4.9 percent in the last year, more than twice the national rate of 2.3 percent, First Union economist Mark Vitner said Wednesday. He spoke at the Local Government Investment and Debt Training Conference sponsored by the state treasurer's office. Although the state economy is expected to slow in 1997, "We expect South Carolina to outperform the rest of the nation, with about a 4 percent growth rate," Vitner said. South Carolina would have done even better this year if not for the continuing downsizing at the Savannah River Plant and the layoffs at Charleston Naval Shipyard, he said. The state's private sector grew 6.2 percent for the year. Vitner said South Carolina's manufacturing sector continued to expand, although its growth rate slowed to about 2.3 percent in the past year because of declines in textiles and apparel. The state saw strong gains in machinery, transportation equipment and chemicals, partly because of export growth. Exports in manufactured goods rose 8.2 percent during the year. Tourism grew by 6.9 percent over last year. Regionally, Vitner said the Upstate, while bedeviled by 10 percent employment cuts in textiles and apparel, is expected to post 2.2 percent job growth this year. Columbia will come close, with growth of about 2 percent. Charleston will post growth of about 1 percent this year, as strong private sector growth has more than offset the shutdown of the Charleston Naval Base. Vitner said the strongest gains were in Hilton Head and Myrtle Beach, where job gains topped 5.2 percent due to tourism and migration from other states. Corporate relocations to South Carolina have also boosted the state economy, especially in Rock Hill, York County, Greenwood and Florence, he said. He predicted statewide holiday spending would rise by 8 percent over last year, with clothing accounting for a large part of purchases. He said computers and home electronics will do well, but their gains will trail prior years. --Jane Sutton, 305-374-5013
