CCAT	Three foreign bidders for a $450 million Mexican power plant project passed initial tender requirements on Tuesday, a spokesman for the Federal Electricity Commission (CFE) said. The three consortium passed technical prerequisites for the Monterrey II combined cycled power plant, Jose Luis Uribe Ortega told Reuters. Bidders for the plant are: Japan's Mitsubishi Corp, Japan's Marubeni Corp and a union between Japan's Nissho-Iwai Corp and Swiss-Swedish ABB Energy Ventures Inc., the CFE said. A decision on the winning bidder is due in the first two weeks of September, Uribe said. Monterrey II is due to come on line in 2000 with electricity generating capacity of 450 megawatts, he said. The estimated construction cost is $450 million, Uribe added. The plant is part of a national spree of power plant tenders for the second half of the year. The new plants are aimed at boosting Mexico's output in anticipation of growing domestic electricity consumption. In coming days a decision is also expected on the winning bid for the 100-megawatt Cerro Prieto IV power plant. Bids for the plant have come from Marubeni, Mitsubishi, Kanematsu-ICA Fluor Daniel, Ansaldo de Mexico and Ormet International-GEC Alsthom-Turalmex. ((--Timna Tanners, Mexico City newsroom +525 728-7903))
ECAT	Deputy Assistant Treasury Secretary Roger Anderson on Tuesday said that liquidity of the inflation indexed note was important and a consideration when deciding how much to sell and that he expected it to improve as more securities are issued. Speaking to reporters following remarks to a financial group, Anderson said "we hope the liquidity will improve the more securities we issue." The Tresury will sell $7.0 billion of 10-year inflation index bonds on Wednesday. "Index notes," he said "will probably never be as liquid as Treasury bills but then nothing else in the world is as liquid as Treasury bills."
