CCAT	Daimler-Benz Aerospace (DASA) is holding talks with French defence companies Matra and Alcatel aimed at possible future cooperation, a company spokesman said. Matra and Alcatel are interested in taking stakes in Thomson-CSF, which is about to be privatised. The DASA spokesman told Reuters talks were taking place, but said no conclusions had been reached. "Nothing has been decided at all," he said. The French government has said it will decide about the disposal of its 58 percent stake in Thomson by May 7. The Daimler-Benz unit has already made clear its intention to unify more of the German defence industry under its stewardship. DASA board member Werner Heinzmann has expressed interest in buying the defence electronics business of Siemens AG, and talks are also being held with Nuremberg-based Diehl about a takeover of its fuselage business. DASA's defence and civil systems division, with 9,000 employees, had sales of 2.6 billion marks in 1996, and aims to boost sales to 2.8 billion marks this year. -- Terence Gallagher, Bonn newsroom, 49-228-2609750
CCAT	It's no secret that many New Yorkers head over the border to New Jersey to shop since there's no sales tax on most clothes in the Garden State. They take to the bridges and tunnels and trains to escape New York City's 8.25 percent tax on coats, dresses, trousers, and the Empire State estimates it loses about $700 million a year from such cross-border shoppers. But now it's pay-back time. New York is fighting fire with fire. A one-week moratorium on sales tax on most clothing began on January 18 and will run for one week. New York City and State have decided to make shopping trips to the suburbs in New Jersey, Pennsylvania or Connecticut not worth the car, bus or train fare. For the week, New York state lifted its four percent sales tax, and all but seven of New York's 62 counties ditched local taxes on clothes, keeping most state residents from paying tax on any item under $500. The state's Metropolitan Transportation Authority also decided to put on hold its 0.25 percent tax for the week. New Yorkers pay varying sales taxes across the state, depending on local tax rates. Nassau County, on suburban Long Island, has the state's highest sales tax of 8.50 percent while Delaware County, on the state's Southern Tier, has the lowest with six percent. For New York State retailers, January is a rather slow month. It's hard to get terribly excited about annual white sales for bedding and other housewares. In terms of clothing, there are deep discounts all over town, but the wares are looking kind of shopworn about now. What better time to bring in some excitement. Actually, state officials originally wanted to have the tax-free week in December, but it was decided the loss to the state would have been too great. So rather than omit sales tax during the busiest time of the year, the experiment was put off until this week, risking $20 million in tax revenue to determine how much the tax really harms retailers, New York officials said. State and local spokesmen drew a blank when asked if other states had ever had a sales tax suspension like New York's. Is it paying off? While it's just midweek, retailers can't give a final tally whether people are buying. The New York City Department of Finance doesn't expect any definitive reports from retailers for a few months. From all appearances, shoppers are indeed coming in, at least to browse. Not only are retailers marking down clothes from 20 percent to 75 percent to clear the racks for spring fashions, but the suspension of sales tax appears to be the final sweetener. At Today's Man in Manhattan, store officials said sales were up 250 percent over the same week last year, keeping in mind that last year's January was one non-stop snow storm. "I expected a huge increase, but I didn't expect it to be as good as it was," store manager Greg Cabral said. As a customer said at Forman's of Orchard Street, a discounter of women's clothing, "I wouldn't be buying the Austin Reed outfit if it wasn't for no tax." At Loehmann's in Lake Success, on Long Island, sales associates said they had never seen so many shoppers on a Sunday. The line for the cashier was several minutes long. "It is long overdue," Walter Eisenhardt, store manager of Barneys New York in the World Financial Centre, said. "It is giving New Yorkers the opportunity to enjoy the same tax-free purchases as someone in New Jersey has been able to enjoy all these years." While only five states have no sales tax on clothing, a number have some exemptions on work clothes or childrens clothes, according to the Commerce Clearing House, a publisher of detailed tax data.
GCAT	Weeping mothers marched through downtown Bogota on Thursday, calling for the release of their soldier sons captured by leftist guerrillas more than a month ago. Thirty-five mothers paraded photos of their loved ones, who were among the more than 60 seized by the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC) as prisoners of war in the jungles of southern Colombia on Aug. 30. Some blamed the army for sending their sons, little more than raw recruits, into a combat zone. Others urged prayers for the FARC, saying the rebels' fight was with the government, not their boys. "This situation is destroying my heart. Only God knows the pain a mother feels when her son is kidnapped," said Hermencia Vargas, mother of 19-year-old Edwin Sierra from Florencia in southern Caqueta province. As the 1,000-strong march snaked past graffiti declaring "Long live Communism" and "Yanks go home," a flock of pigeons rose into the air -- would-be doves of peace. Communist guerrillas rose up in arms more than three decades ago in Colombia. But the attack on Aug. 30 in which more than 27 soldiers died caught the military off guard and signalled the start of the bloodiest rebel offensive in recent memory. The International Committee of the Red Cross is mediating the prisoner crisis. In line with the FARC's demands, President Ernesto Samper this week agreed to allow an international delegation to witness the eventual handover of the soldiers.
ECAT	U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on Friday warned Bosnia's Moslem, Croat and Serb presidents that they will be denied $100 million in IMF loans and more than $1 billion in private donations until they pass a budget, her spokesman said. Albright, leading a U.S. effort to increase international pressure on key parties to comply with the fraying Bosnia peace agreement, made her comments during a 15-minute meeting with the Balkan country's three chiefs -- Moslem Alija Izetbegovic, Croat Kresimir Zubak and Serb Momcilo Krajisnik. Although senior U.S. officials this week have made similar threats to Bosnia's leaders, this is the first time that Albright made the point to them directly. She will visit the Balkans this weekend to carry further her campaign for compliance with the 1995 U.S.-brokered Dayton peace accord. "The price of the $100 million is to pass a budget law," State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters. Albright "specifically asked them to work hard on a new law that needs to be agreed to further the Bosnian state", he said. He stressed that this was not a unilateral U.S. threat but a common International Monetary Fund practice to condition its assistance on reforms. The United States has an effective veto at the IMF. Albright told the presidents that an international conference on Bosnia, which is expected to raise an estimated $1.4 billion, could not go forward until the budget was enacted, Burns said. Under the Dayton peace accord, Bosnia is supposed to be a unified state with two separate entities, one for Serbs and the other a Croat-Moslem federation. But Bosnia's ethnic factions have resisted integration and some U.S. officials believe they are not truly interested in peace. Agreeing on a common budget is one essential tool of a unified state. The three presidents finally reached agreement this week on a law establishing a central bank and they have also finally agreed on a customs law, accomplishments Albright praised, Burns said. With 30,000 NATO-led stabilisation force (SFOR) troops in Bosnia that are due to leave next June, Washington and its allies are increasingly concerned that their time for ensuring that fighting does not re-ignite next year is running out. The major western powers involved in Bosnia -- the United States, Britain, Germany, France and Russia -- were to meet with the Bosnian parties in Sintra later on Friday following a NATO meeting. Burns said all three presidents "pledged to work together" to get the budget agreed. After Albright left the meeting, the Bosnian officials met with senior members of Albright's team, including new U.S. envoy Robert Gelbard, and Carl Bildt, the international envoy for Bosnia, to continue work on the budget and other issues. The spokesman described Krajisnik as having told Albright one half of the Bosnian Serb republic was eager for her to visit Bosnia and the other half "fears you". Albright was also to meet in Sintra with Biljana Plavsic, the president of the Serb republic. The United States has tried to work with Plavsic as part of the peace process but Bosnian Serb hardliners have sought to prevent her cooperation.
CCAT	A group led by Tweedy Browne Co LP, a New York-based broker-dealer, said on Monday it raised its stake in Ryland Group Inc to 1,244,020 common shares or 8.09 percent from 6.84 percent held last November. In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the group said its latest transactions include a net 37,865 common shares bought between December 3, 1996 and January 22, 1997 at prices ranging from $13.06818 to $13.875 per share. The group holds the stake for investment purposes, the filing said. Ryland is a Columbia, Md., based homebuilder and mortgage financing company.
MCAT	Pakistani cotton rates closed steady on Monday on low buying by spinners but they were expected to rise in the next few days on demand from exporters, dealers at the private Karachi Cotton Association (KCA) said. One dealer said spinners had slowed buying as they had enough stocks to last until the new crop arrives in early July in Sindh province, where it ripens earlier than in Punjab province. In the kerb market, NIAB-78 variety was quoted at 2,100/2,175 rupees per maund (37.32 kg), K-68 at 2,350/2,375 and MNH-93 at 2,380/2,400.
ECAT	Preliminary consumer price data from sample cities shows Italy's November annual inflation rate will be around 2.5 percent, down from 3.0 percent in October, state economic research body Isco said. An Isco report on the Italian economy said the average rate of inflation for 1996 was expected to be 3.9 percent, in line with government forecasts,but would fall to 2.6 percent in 1997. Isco said the economy is expected to grow 0.7 percent this year, against a government target of 0.8 percent, while gross domestic product growth in 1997 is seen rising 1.2 percent. But Isco said the increase in output in 1997 would not be sufficient to obtain "significant improvements" in the employment situation. It said a modest increase in the employment level would result in only a small reduction in this year's 12.1 percent unemployment rate to 11.9 percent next year. Regarding salaries, Isco said it had taken into account that in the renewal of contracts "contractual increases would be set in a way to incorporate a partial recovery of purchasing power, in line with contracts which have already been renewed". The institute said that it believed pro capita salaries in 1997 would increase 4.1 percent in the economy as a whole and 4.3 percent in the industrial sector, against 4.9 and 5.2 percent respectively in 1996. It said the cost of labour in the economy as a whole was expected to decrease from 3.6 percent in 1996 to 3.1 percent in 1997. --Rome newsroom +396 678-2501
GCAT	Albanian President Sali Berisha on Friday formally called general elections for the troubled Balkan state for June 29, his office said. He called the elections although most political parties have threatened to boycott the poll.   "The president of the republic...decreed today the dissolution of the National Assembly before the end of its mandate and the holding of new parliamentary elections on Sunday June 29, 1997," Berisha's office said in a statement. The early elections are seen the key element in restoring order in Albania after the country was torn apart by riots in February and March after the collapse of pyramid investment schemes bankrupted thousands of people. Most political parties are threatening to boycott the poll in a dispute over the election law, which they say favours Berisha. European Union envoy Franz Vranitzky seemed to have broken the deadlock on Thursday by persuading parliament to draft a new election law but the parties later said they still did not like the legislation.
GCAT	The trial of a pool mechanic charged in the gas poisoning of tennis star Vitas Gerulaitis began Tuesday with his attorney blaming the maker of a pool heating system and describing his client as a "scapegoat." Prosecutors have alleged that mechanic Bartholomew Torpey and his employer, East End Pools and Courts Inc., improperly rigged an exhaust pipe in the basement of a Southampton, Long Island, pool cottage where Gerulaitis slept. Gerulaitis, 40, was found dead Sept. 18, 1994, on the exclusive estate of developer friend Martin Raynes. Torpey was accused of failing to install the correct length of pipe from a pool heating system, trapping carbon monoxide gas near the room where Gerulaitis rested. Torpey was indicted on charges of criminally negligent homicide and the pool company was charged with second degree manslaughter. In opening arguments Tuesday in Torpey's trial in Suffolk County Court, attorney David Clayton charged that prosecutors, by allowing a key expert witness from manufacturer Teledyne Lars to testify before a grand jury, had given the expert immunity from prosecution. "In this case the District Attorney and the city let the big people take a hike and went after the smallest people on the face of the earth he could find," Clayton told the jury. He described Torpey as the "fall guy" and a "scapegoat". Clayton blamed Teledyne Lars and the expert witness, James Cosmano, whom he said was the last person in the pool cottage to work on the heater three days before Gerulaitis' death. Gerulaitis, who retired from the tennis circuit in 1984 but later returned to the game as a broadcaster, won 27 singles and nine doubles championships, including the 1977 Australian Open. He won millions of dollars but his career declined rapidly as he was treated for drug abuse. During his opening arguments, Assistant District Attorney Edward Helig slammed his hand down on the defence table and said, "the buck stops at this table right here. They're the people who did it, the people responsible for it." He told the jury that Torpey was not educated enough and did not care enough to make sure the pipe extended outside of the door. "When you see one item, the photograph of how this defendant installed and vented this heater, you don't need to be an expert to see the photograph and know and say 'that's wrong'," Helig said. "He just didn't care enough, didn't take the time to find out how to vent this thing." Gerulaitis' mother Aldona Gerulaitis has filed a $63 million civil lawsuit in Manhattan Supreme Court, citing nine defendants, including Torpey, the pool company and Raynes.
ECAT	Louisiana Bond Commission gave final approval Thursday to 16 state and local government bond issues totalling $231.4461 million. Issues approved were: --$34 million of Port of New Orleans Industrial Development Revneune Refunding Bonds, to refund 1982 bonds issued for Contentinal Grain Co. --$27 million South Louisiana Port Commission port facilities refunding revenue bonds to refund 1981 bonds issued for the Occidental Petroleum Corp. --$26 million of Louisiana Public Facilities Authority advance funding notes, to provide low cost financing for short term funding needs of local school boards. --$25 million of East Baton Rouge Mortgage Finance Authority single family mortgage revenue bonds and $15.575 million of single family mortgage revenue refunding bonds. --$19.5 million Parish of St. James pollution control facilities refunding revenue bonds, to refund 1981 bonds issued for Occidental Petroleum. --$15 million of Calcasieu Parish Public Trust Authority qualified mortgage credit certificates to provide loans for first-time home buyers. --$12 million of Iberia Parish Hospital Service District No. 1 hospital revenue bonds. --$11 million of Orleans Levee District levee improvement refunding bonds to refud the remainder of its 1987 series, and $3.5 million of Orleans Levee District public improvement bonds. --$10 million of Lafourche Parish Water District No 1 water revenue bonds. --$10 million Town of Delhi industrial development refunding revenue bonds, to refund 1982 bonds issued for the Tifton Aluminun Co --$8 million St. Tammany Parish Hospital Service District 2 hospital revenue bonds for renovations and upgrades at Slidell Memorial Hospital and Medical Center. --$7 million of St John the Baptist Parish sales tax district public improvement refunding bonds, to refund a 1990 series of public improvement bonds. --$5.6 million of Acadia Parish Police Jury sales tax road bonds. --$72,000 of Evangeline Parish Ward Four water district revenue bonds. --$541,000 of Town of Columbia sewer revenue bonds. --U.S. Municipal Desk, 212-859-1650
MCAT	Mexican stocks could not escape the wave of selling that washed over Wall Street on Friday, closing lower in a day where one of the few bright spots was an initial public offering by broadcaster TV Azteca. The leading IPC stock index fell below the key 5,000-point support level to 4,956.61 points, off 58 points on the day. Still, Mexican stocks held up well compared with a big sell-off on Wall Street, where U.S. stocks suffered their second-biggest point loss in history.   Azteca, Mexico's second largest broadcaster, issued shares on the Mexican and New York stock exchanges. Its CPO shares in Mexico rose from an initial offer price of 35.43 pesos to 36.80 pesos. ((--Mexico City newsroom +525 728-9565))
ECAT	The National Bank of Hungary's (NBH) surprise rate hike announced earlier this week will not substantially increase the debt service expenditures of the state budget, the Finance Ministry said on Friday. "The rate hike will stabilise interest rates temporarily, but will not affect state budget expenditures substantially," Deputy Secretary of State Csaba Laszlo told Reuters. The NBH raised the interest rate of its six-month deposit facility by 0.25 percentage points to 21.00 percent on Monday, shocking the markets which had expected the continuation of a one year long trend of declining interest rates and inflation. The NBH said its move was aimed at maintaining real interest levels so as to protect savings. Analysts welcomed the NBH move and said inflation was likely to move a little upward in March and April and may rise slightly further or stabilise by the end of the third quarter of the year, due to energy and food price rises. "Inflation may be higher in March and April," Laszlo said, adding that this would not change the underlying falling trend. "We expect interest rates to go down in line with declining inflation," he said. The Finance Ministry and the NBH expects inflation to drop to some 17 percent by December from 18.9 percent in January, while the forecasts of 15 analysts for December 1997 in a recent Reuters survey averaged at 18.39 percent. Yields on government securities rose slightly on the secondary market following the NBH rate hike, but turnover slumped as buyers demanded sunstantially higher yields with the supply side hesitating to sell and suffer losses. Traders were uncertain whether the NBH planned to keep its interest rates at current levels for the longer term. "The pessimistic version (for sellers) is that the NBH will keep its interest rates (at the current level) for as much as two months," a trader said earlier this week. "At that point even those who have not sold so far may do so." Analysts said the NBH interest rate hike may create some tension between the central bank and the Government Debt Management Agency, as it may increase the state budget debt financing burden. -- Budapest newsroom (36 1) 327 4040
GCAT	Afghanistan's Islamic Taleban militia appeared on Thursday to have suffered reverses at the hands of ousted army chief Ahmad Shah Masood, with a town south of previous fighting being prepared for assault. The Taleban were setting up anti-aircraft guns in the middle of the main road through Charikar, 60 km (40 miles) north of Kabul, which they took two weeks ago. The nearby village of Bagram, next to Kabul's military airport, was deserted but the base was still in Taleban hands. Shops in Charikar were closed and nervous local people on the streets said they heard small arms fire an estimated five km (three miles) north of the town on the road to Jabal-os-Siraj at the mouth of the Salang Pass, where Masood's men attacked on Tuesday and drove the Taleban back. In mid-afternoon, however, there was no sign of fighting in or around Charikar. But local people said they had seen many Taleban, dead and wounded, being ferried south towards Kabul. Other reports appeared to confirm the Taleban's opponents were on the move. U.N. sources in Islamabad, Pakistan, said Masood's forces attacked Taleban fighters at his old headquarters at Jabal os-Siraj and moved south to threaten the airbase. "All we know is that Masood has moved out of the Panjsher Valley, had a go at the Taleban in Jabal os-Siraj and Charikar, and has moved on Bagram," a U.N. source said. Earlier, travellers said the sound of heavy fighting was apparent just north of Jabal-os-Siraj, a 30-minute drive from Charikar, but there was no word on whether the town at the foot of the wall of the Hindu Kush had fallen. "It was very close to Jabal-os-Siraj," said one traveller who asked not to be identified. A Taleban source in Pakistan denied that Jabal os-Siraj had fallen, saying Taleban fighters had killed four of Masood's men and captured 47 in fighting there on Thursday. On Wednesday, the front line of the Taleban was 15 km (nine miles) north of the town, witnesses said. That was 15 to 20 km (nine to 12 miles) south of their front line before Masood's men launched a suprise attack on Tuesday. Confirmation of the reports was not immediately available. Western reporters were barred from travelling to the area. On Tuesday, the Taleban battlefield commander in the Salang, Maulavi Khairulla Haqani, told Reuters Television his men had stemmed the advance of Masood's ethnic Tajik fighters down the Salang. He said fighting had been fierce, but declined to comment on casualties. Western aid workers, however, quoted witnesses as saying they had seen at least 100 Taleban bodies and many more wounded being taken to Jabal-os-Siraj. The attack forced the Taleban, who have swept to control of three-quarters of Afghanistan since the movement was born in religious schools in refugee camps in Pakistan two years ago, to break off attempts to enter Masood's Panjsher valley fortress. They started the assault on Saturday, but by Wednesday evening not a single black-turbanned Taleban fighter was to be seen in Golbahar, a town 10 km (six miles) east of Jabal that sits astride the rocky gorge leading into the Panjsher. Days of heavy fighting had taken Taleban fighters only 500 metres (yards) into the gorge, which Masood blocked with landslides. In the Salang, there was no word on casualties among Masood's men, led by his former area commander, Basir Solangi, in an attack that cut off a large number of Taleban fighters, the aid workers said. When the largely ethnic Pushtun Taleban moved north after taking Kabul, Solangi retreated north into territory controlled by Uzbek chief Abdul Rashid Dostum, who talked with ousted president Burhanuddin Rabbani this week and said Masood was to join them. Also in the northern city of Mazar-i-Sharif, from which Dostum controls six of Afghanistan's provinces, was Karim Khallili, leader of the Hezb-i-Wahadat faction which controls territory to the west of Jabal-os-Siraj. The Taleban leadership in Kabul dismissed any possibility of an alliance between the groups, which have been enemies in the past.
MCAT	Spanish Economy Secretary Cristobal Montoro said on Friday that Spanish markets were behaving well and he added that the bourse was correcting after sharp and recent gains. "(Spanish) markets are not behaving badly. In this sense what happened to stocks has a lot to do with profit taking after a sharp rally," Montoro told reporters after a seminar. He added that the peseta showed a limited reaction as yields, which is showing "the calm of the Spanish economy". -- Madrid Newsroom, + 341 585 8340
