CCAT	U.S. Facilities Corp said Tuesday it was on track for increased revenues and earnings for the full year 1996 if present business trends continue. U.S. Facilities earned $2.42 a share on revenues of $151.2 million in 1995. The company today reported third quarter earnings of $0.62 a share, up from $0.60 a year earlier. The company said it expects to take no extraordinary charges for losses due to natural disasters such as Hurricane Fran and other storms during the third quarter.
CCAT	Shares in British alarm and emergency communication systems firm Tunstall Group were marked down on Thursday after weaker-than-expected full year results were released. At 1150 GMT the share price was quoted at 261p -- down 32-1/2p -- but no stock had been traded. Tunstall's preliminary results statement for the year to September 30 showed pre-tax profits static at 8.2 million stg while turnover increased to 78.0 million stg from 60.7 million. The figures disappointed analysts who had forecast pre-tax profits of 8.4 million stg on average.   Tunstall chairman Michael Dawson blamed lacklustre performance on anticipated orders not materialising and a lapse in control of overheads and margins which, he said, had now been rectified. --Catherine Bremer, London Newsroom +44 171 542 7717
ECAT	The Cahners Business Confidence Index (CBCI) fell 0.9 point to 66.6 in June versus May, Cahners Economics said. "The June CBCI revealed that manufacturers are feeling slightly less sanguine about the American economy than they did in May," a Cahners report said. Five of the seven CBCI components fell in June. The sharpest decline came from plans to increase marketing spending, which dropped 2.6 points to 64.5 in June. The employment component, which had recorded the sharpest gain during May, slipped 1.7 points to 68.9, the report showed. The product introductions measure posted the greatest gain, up 1.9 points to 72.7, while research and development rose a meagre 0.1 point to 64.0. "The June CBCI indicates that businesses are beginning to prepare for slower growth in consumer spending and business investment in the months ahead, following the exceptional 5.8-percent gain in first-quarter Gross Domestic Product (GDP)," noted Cahners economist Daryl Delano. "This should please the (Federal Reserve) and keep inflation -- and interest rates -- at bay," he said. (( -- N.A. Treasury Desk, 212-859-1660 ))
ECAT	Algeria on Wednesday forecast a current account surplus of $300 million by the end of 1966, reversing a forecast of a $2 billion deficit, an official statement said. The statement, carried by the official news agency APS after a cabinet meeting, said total imports in the first half of the year fell by 15 percent, giving a surplus trade balance of $1.3 billion. No figures were given for total exports for the period from the North African country which earns 94 percent of foreign income from oil and gas sales abroad. In June this year, official figures showed total exports, mainly of oil and gas, reached $10.240 billion for the whole of 1995 compared with $8.501 billion for all of 1994. Imports in 1995, according to the earlier figures, were put at $10.761 billion, against $9.365 billion in 1994. Wednesday's statement said non-energy exports rose by 53.4 percent to $366 million in the first six months of 1996. It said imports fell because of a good harvest, recession and stagnation in the industrial sector, and a drop in the purchasing power of Algeria's 29 million people. "The drop of costly food imports alone attained 29 percent compared with the previous year," the statement said. Non-energy industrial production fell by 7.4 percent in the first six months of 1996, compared with the whole of the previous year for which no figure was given. "The hydrocarbon sector in the first half of 1996  saw a growth rate of eight percent compared with the first half of the previous year, notably because of an increase of gas production -- up 8.1 percent -- growth of condensate production up 6.6 percent, growth of refined products up 3.7 percent, and the reinforcement of gas liquefaction, up 15.1 percent.
GCAT	Former Spanish prime minister Felipe Gonzalez on Friday urged Serbia's President Slobodan Milosevic to seize the chance to install "real democracy" in the country and end the current unrest. Gonzalez, back from a mission to Belgrade for the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), was speaking at a news conference after issuing a report saying the Serbian opposition won elections annulled by Milosevic.   "There exists an extraordinary opportunity for the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia to solve this concrete problem, to initiate real democracy in the country, and to reintegrate itself into the international community," Gonzalez said. This chance, he added, "must be seized by the authorities, by the opposition and the citizens of Yugoslavia." Outgoing OSCE chairman and Swiss Foreign Minister Flavio Cotti told the news conference he had telephoned Milosevic to tell him of the Gonzalez mission's findings -- which included an implicit appeal for opposition election victories to be reinstated. Cotti said he expected the Serbian leader to make his response known early next week. Danish Foreign Minister Niels Petersen, who takes over the OSCE presidency on January 1, said the body would hold a full Council meeting at the end of next week in Vienna to consider Milosevic's reply.
GCAT	Alger Hiss, accused of being a spy for the Soviet Union at a time when the United States was gripped by fears of Communist infiltration, died on Friday at the age of 92. Hiss died at Lenox Hill Hospital in New York City after a long illness, a hospital spokeswoman said.   Journalist Whittaker Chambers accused Hiss in 1948 of having given him U.S. government secrets to pass to the Soviets. Hiss sued Chambers for libel and Chambers produced classified documents, some of which he said were written in Hiss's handwriting and others typed on the Hiss family typewriter. Then Congressman Richard Nixon, who would later become president, led the prosecution case against Hiss. Hiss was tried for perjury. His first trial ended in a hung jury, but a second trial in 1950 ended in a guilty verdict. Sentenced to five years in prison, he served 44 months. While the question of his guilt or innocence was never fully resolved, a senior adviser to Russian President Boris Yeltsin said in 1992 that newly opened files showed no evidence that Hiss had spied for Moscow.
CCAT	The president of the executive and professional employees association of state National Bank was quoted as saying in a statement that the bank will raise its share capital by 50 billion drachmas by year-end 1997. Constantine Liakopoulos, the president of the executive and professional employees association, was speaking at a bank event on Saturday. The bank will also issue bonds worth between $150 to $200 million to be placed with foreign investors and restructure its portfolio and real estate holdings, he said. The restructuring will seek to improve returns, while the revaluation of fixed assets will boost the bank's equity by 14.2 billion drachmas. The bank will proceed with the issuance of a Visa card, Liakopoulos was quoted as saying. National Bank is expanding in the Balkans with the establishment of its National Insurance new branch in Bucharest, Romania, he added. --Margarita Sotiropoulou, Athens Newsroom +301 3311812-4
ECAT	Weak growth in Japan's money supply in June was largely due to sluggish demand for bank loans, economists said on Thursday. The Bank of Japan (BOJ) said earlier that Japan's broadly defined money supply average of M2 plus certificates of deposit (CDs) grew a preliminary 2.8 percent in June from a year earlier. M2 plus CD growth for May was revised up to 3.1 percent from a preliminary 3.0 percent. Economists polled by Reuters had expected the June figure to rise by 2.8 percent to 3.1 percent year-on-year. Most had forecast a rise of either 2.9 percent or 3.0 percent. The lower-than-expected growth in June was also due to technical reasons, said Mamoru Yamaguchi, an economist at Nikko Research Center. "The month-end coincided with a weekend in June 1996, while the last day of June this year was a Monday. So the slower year-on-year growth may have been due to this technical factor," Yamaguchi said. Weak demand for bank loans among big corporations and a cautious lending stance by banks towards non-manufacturers and small companies were behind the continuation of the slow growth in money supply, said Youchi Itoh, a senior economist at Daiwa Institute of Research. "Banks, still suffering from bad loan problems, are unwilling to lend to smaller companies. They are willing to lend to bigger companies but big firms prefer to issue bonds to procure long-term funds," he said. Itoh said he expects the year-on-year M2 plus CD growth rate to remain at slightly below three percent in the next few months. -- Tokyo Treasury Desk 81-3-3432-9780
CCAT	Venezuela's capacity to respond to U.S. Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary's call for more heating oil exports is limited by refinery flexibility, a top Venezuelan oil official said Wednesday. "There is a limited capacity to absorb this demand," Simon Antunez, director of technology at the Energy and Mines Ministry, told a news conference. The limited flexibility to raise distillate output is normally met from inventories, he added. Venezuela tends to produce more distillates at this time of year than at others, Antunez said. While not specifying Venezuela's distillates capacity Antunez said medium distillates account for between 15 and 20 percent of total refining capacity. Venezuela has a crude refining capacity of 1.2 million barrels per day (bpd) and shipped an average of 58,000 bpd of heating oil and diesel fuel to the United States last year, according to U.S. Department of Energy data. -- Maria Jose Gonzalez, Caracas newsroom, 582 505 2600
