ECAT	Hungary's deep structural reforms should help it avoid trade and current account problems which could arise from rising economic growth, Finance Minister Peter Medgyessy said on Monday. Medgyessy told Reuters in an interview that the economic restrictions which Hungary introduced two years ago were necessary to create conditions for sustainable growth, but alone were not sufficient to spark growth. "The restrictions are not sufficient, because if (they) do not come along with structural reforms, (economic) balance problems may return," he said. "That's why the government's decision (last week) about the pension reform has an enormous significance." He added that the decision also outlined reform measures in the health care system. The pension and health care reforms will be operational in 1998 and 1999 and guarantee that ecconomic growth is sustainable, Medgyessy said. -- Sandor Peto, Budapest newsroom (36 1) 327 4040
GCAT	Former two-times world  champion Carlos Sainz of Spain won the Acropolis Rally on Tuesday when he finished 17 seconds ahead of Ford team-mate Juha Kankkunen of Finland. Briton Richard Burns was third in a Mitsubishi, two minutes and seven seconds behind Sainz.
ECAT	Pakistan may be unable to meet an IMF-set target of cutting its budget deficit to four percent of gross domestic product by June, Sartaj Aziz, widely expected to become the next finance minister, said on Tuesday. "The four percent target may take another year or so, rather than June this year, but I think on the whole the IMF package would not be difficult to implement if business confidence is restored and we are able to accelerate the industrial growth and increase exports," he told Reuters Financial Television.   Aziz, who was finance minister in the last Pakistan Muslim League (PML) government led by Nawaz Sharif, said he would accept whatever role Sharif assigned to him in the next cabinet. He was speaking as results from Monday's national and provincial elections showed the PML sweeping to a landslide victory against ousted prime minister Benazir Bhutto's Pakistan People's Party (PPP). Aziz said the new government's priority would be to restore business confidence, revive the industrial sector and increase exports to stabilise the balance of payments. It would also seek to accelerate privatisation and economic reform. The International Monetary Fund agreed to resume and expand a stalled standby loan to Pakistan in December after the caretaker government promised to cut the deficit to four percent of GDP by the end of fiscal 1996/97 (July-June).
MCAT	The price of gold hung around the psychologically important $350.00 an ounce level in thin, trading on Tuesday, while the white metals showed more volatility. Bullion was fixed at $350.00 an ounce in the afternoon, virtually unchanged from $349.85 in the morning after trading in a tight range of around $1.70. "Gold certainly does not seem to be doing much today and trading is quite thin," a dealer noted. Dealers had said sharp losses on Wall Street on Thursday and Monday had helped to attract investors to gold, buoying prices. The effect was not likely to last much longer, unless the stock market saw further significant losses this week, they said. In contrast, silver, platinum and palladium have lost ground amid concerns about industrial demand in the aftermath of last week's hike in U.S. interest rates, dealers said. Silver started the day weaker after a slide below the $5.08 support line in New York on Monday triggered sell stops and sent prices lower. Further selling in early Europe, which dealers attributed to a New York investment fund, sent prices probing key support at $5.00 an ounce. But it bounced off lows and was last at $5.03/$5.05, off nine cents from Thursday's close. Still, some dealers said silver had acquired a downside bias and was vulnerable to the downside. "The $5.00 level has held for now, and $4.98 has been good technical support in the past. But longs have been getting out and we may be moving into a new, lower range," a dealer said. Platinum also came under pressure, and ticked lower after sustaining painful losses on Monday in New York. It was last at $368.50/$369.50, down $3.20 from Thursday's London close. But palladium came off its lows and was last indicated virutally unchanged at $146.25/$147.25. The market was still waiting for fresh news on Russian supplies of platinum group metals to Japan, which have been on hold since the beginning of the year. Industry officials have said they were waiting for a government decree to authorise shipments. --Lida Poletz, London newsroom +44 171 542 2936
ECAT	Israel's November consumer price index (CPI), due to published on Sunday, will show a rise of 0.4-0.6, economists predicted on Thursday. If inflation is 0.5 percent, the year-on-year inflation rate will be 10.9 percent (corrects from 9.6 percent). "By itself, the November inflation rate is within the government's target," said Shauli Katznelson, chief economist at Israel Discount Bank. But, he added, the shekel's weakening against the dollar in recent weeks will feed into higher consumer prices in the next two months. "The situation in November doesn't reflect what the indices will be in December and January," Katznelson said. Irit Oren, economist at the Federation of Israeli Chambers of Commerce, said the Federation was expecting a lower CPI figure of no more than 0.4-0.5 percent. She said the major factor was housing prices. She predicted they would show a rise of no more than 0.5 percent in November. Home prices are customarily denominated in dollars and therefore rise when the dollar strengthens. But this factor has been offset by the weakness of the property market, Oren said. She added that the Federation expected housing prices to continue cooling inflation over the near term. As a result, the Federation is expecting continued low indices over the next few months. Discount, on the other hand, is expecting the CPI to show a relatively high 10 to 11 percent increase in the coming 12 months. Nevertheless, Katznelson said he expected that the Bank of Israel would lower the short-term interest rate at the end of December from the current 15.2 percent. Many analysts have said the central bank will not cut rates until the debate now going on in parliament over the 1997 budget is over. Parliament is expected to vote on the budget by December 31, a week after the Bank of Israel announces its monthly monetary programme. But Katznelson said the central bank would not wait. "Without relating to the budget, there is room to cut interest rates this month 0.5 percentage point," he said. Real interest rates are now six percent or more, which Katznelson said was "unreasonable" in a slowing economy. "I think that in a situation like this, you can't have a real rate of interest like you had this year in an overheated economy," he said. Katznelson said that over the next three months the central bank to lower rates a total of 1.2 percent point. - David Rosenberg, Tel Aviv newsroom, 972-3-537-2211
ECAT	Lithuania will likely tap the international capital markets with a second 1997 bond issue in September or October, Finance Finister Algirdas Shemeta told Reuters in an interview.   "We will have a second issue in September or October...we have some preliminary thoughts on it," Shemeta said. Lithuania has already announced its intention to issue a $200 million eurobond this year which will be led by JP Morgan Securities. That bond will probably be launched in late spring or early summer, after the country acquires a credit rating from Standard and Poor's. "It is too early to disclose the amount of the second bond," Shemeta said. "It depends on the market conditions and rating, which we hope will be investment grade," he said. "It is too early to discolse the amount, but it could be higher than our first this year," he added. He also said that the ministry was mulling the idea of a yankee instead of a eurobond. --Ed Stoddard, Vilnius newsroom +370 2 22 35 18
ECAT	Russia is sticking to the conditions set out in its $10 billion International Monetary Fund loan program and will continue to do so, Economy Minister Yevgeny Yasin said on Tuesday. Asked about talks with Fund leaders held during this week's IMF-World Bank annual meetings, Yasin said, "we were able to state that the basic conditions of this program are fundamentally being fulfilled."   Yasin said Fund officials had congratulated Russian ministers on economic successes, especially lowering inflation. Yasin said Russia's monthly inflation rate was 0.3 percent in September after a 0.2 percent fall in prices in August. He said prices usually rise in October and November. "Evidently, we will see that, but I do not expect inflation to exceed one percent," he said.   Yasin also said Russia supported an initiative to reduce the debt of some of the world's poorest countries but could not join in the plan unless it was admitted to the Paris Club of creditor states. "We are prepared to adhere to these conditions but for them to be equally and mutually beneficial, Russia must be a member of the Paris Club," Yasin said.   Russia earlier this year reached agreement with the IMF on a three-year Extended Fund Facility loan but it is subject to strict monthly monitoring. Russia must meet certain monetary targets, which incldue the budget deficit and net reserves. Yasin said it could be difficult to meet the reserves target as it was sometimes necessary to use them to support the rouble, which is in a crawling peg against the dollar.   Central bank chairman Sergei Dubinin said last month that Russia spent $1.6 billion to support the rouble, when a faster than usual decline against the dollar made short-term Treasury bilol yields unattractive.. However, Yasin said Russia could meet the IMF conditions. "On the whole I think we will be able to," he said. A tranche of $330 million was held up in August because of concern over the low level of tax collection and Russian officials acknowledge the revenue side of the budget is a difficult problem.   Yasin said the tax and revenue issue had been discussed during the talks with the IMF. "Of course they expressed anxiety but it was recognised that the government is working very energetically to resolve these problems," he said. The International Monetary Fund and World Bank this week launched an initiative to offer poor, heavily indebted states relief on up to 80 percent of their debts, against the 67 percent relief currently on offer.   Yasin said Russia, which inherited the debts and assets of the former Soviet Union, was owed $140 billion. This exceeded the money it owed to, among others, the Paris Club. Russia wasnts all debts it is owed, including credits to buy military equipment, recognised and wants them to reflect the exchange rate at the time they were granted. Yasin said Russia was excluded from talks with some debtor states as it was not a member of the Paris Club. Many of Russia's debtors are African countries which were granted credits, often at artificially low rates, but are now unable to repay them. Russia has reached an agreement on rescheduling its own debts to the Paris Club and has been pressing for admission as a creditor. --Nigel Stephenson, Washington newsroom +1 202 898 8329
ECAT	A senior International Monetary Fund envoy said on Wednesday he needed assurances that the new Bulgarian government to be elected next month would follow the policies set out in any agreement reached now. "I need to be convinced of a widespread agreement on the continuity of policies in the programme. This is what we will be trying to ascertain over the next few days," IMF Europe One department director Michael Deppler told reporters. "I am hopeful that we can arrive at an arrangement, but we have not," said Deppler, who arrived in Sofia on Tuesday. IMF negotiators started talks with Bulgaria's interim government last month on a funding agreement linked to implementation of a fixed exchange rate system to help stabilise the crumbling economy and repay foreign debts. Speaking after meeting President Petar Stoyanov, Deppler said they had agreed on all general policies, but he needed assurances that the new government to take office after the April 19 general election would be committed to the reform programme being agreed now. "I am also equally concerned about a clear commitment and the continuity of policies on these issues that are important," said Deppler. He said he planned to seek guarantees of continuity in meetings with the main political parties. The favourite to win a majority in the new parliament is the Union of Democratic Forces and its coalition allies, whose mass protests ousted the ex-communist Socialist government in February two years before the end of its term. The UDF has shown clear commitment to market reform, liberalisation of trade rules and accelerated privatisation, all needed to haul the country out from economic collapse. But disagreements with the Fund over practical steps still remain. "There are still some points on which there is need for agreement, there are points for which there is no agreement, and there is also a need for the Fund to be assured of the continuity of policies," said Deppler. Different approaches to bank privatisation are one of the setbacks that is halting the agreement, said a local banker, who declined to be named. The IMF recommends to sell four ailing banks by year-end and seek reputable foreign institutions to manage two other big state banks. But local bankers would like loans to re-capitalise the ailing banks and then offer them to investors. The agreement, which Bulgarians officials still hope to sign by the end of this week, would include the interim government's programme on how to solve the grave banking and currency crisis, and this year's budget and structural reform plans. The programme will also contain legal amendments to bank laws designed jointly with the IMF to enable the introduction of a currency board in June. The currency board system would require levs in circulation to be matched by central bank reserves, severely curbing the financial powers of the government and the central bank, thus preventing the printing of money. Deppler, who plans to stay until the end of this week, said there were no practical obstacles in reaching a funding agreement with the interim cabinet by April. -- Sofia Newsroom 3592 981 4145
