GCAT	Indonesian customs officials have detained two Singaporean traders after 16,527 Ecstasy pills were discovered at Jakarta's international airport, a customs official said on Monday. "The pills were wrapped in packets of M&Ms (multi-coloured chocolate sweets)," Nifsu Chasbullah, head of customs and excise at Soekarno-Hatta International Airport, told Reuters by telephone. Chasbullah said the two Singaporeans, whose names were not released, had travelled to Indonesia from Amsterdam via Hong Kong on a Cathay Pacific flight which landed on Sunday morning. "Customs officers became suspicious after the baggage of the two men was X-rayed," he said, adding there was a strong suspicion the two men were working together as the pills were wrapped in an identical fashion. There was no immediate estimate of the street value of the drugs. He said the men were due to be handed over to police in metropolitan Jakarta later on Monday. Earlier this month, two other Singaporeans were caught at the same airport allegedly trying to smuggle 70,431 Ecstasy pills estimated to be worth $1.8 million in the largest single haul in Indonesia. At the time, customs officials said they had seized 239,048 Ecstasy pills since March this year. Ecstasy has gained widespread popularity in Indonesia's cities in recent years and the government has recently legislated to increase penalties for trafficking in and using it.
GCAT	Russia's communist-dominated parliament plans to debate an emotional call on Thursday to President Boris Yeltsin not to move the mummified corpse of Vladimir Lenin from its mausoleum on Red Square. The State Duma lower house, whose tsarist predecessor was abolished by Lenin when he installed the dictatorship of the Communist party after the 1917 revolution, voted overwhelmingly on Wednesday to debate the non-binding resolution entitled "Prevent an Act of Vandalism!". Emotions were stirred by a remark by Yeltsin last week about a possible referendum on the issue, although in 1990 he came out against evicting Lenin from Red Square. The communist legislators who drafted the motion quoted Jesus Christ and the head of the Russian Orthodox Church at the time of Lenin's death in 1924 to back up their argument that re-interring the body would be tantamount to sacrilege. "In a civilised society, it is accepted that historic memorials should be preserved and the burial sites of its leading figures not touched, that national shrines should be honoured," the resolution said. Democrats say Lenin should be re-interred. Historians say Lenin himself wanted a modest burial in St. Petersburg. The communists said forces around the president wanted to "re-write history" and "wipe from the national memory everything linked to the Soviet period, its relics, memorials and shrines". They also invoked UNESCO, saying the mausoleum from which generations of Soviet leaders reviewed parades on Red Square was an integral part of the U.N.-protected Kremlin heritage site. Lenin's successors virtually deified the founder of the Soviet state and placed him at the centre of a communist system of values that functioned as a quasi-religion for seven decades. However, rarely if ever would Soviet communists explicitly have called the tomb a "shrine". Today's nationalistic communist party has reconciled itself with the Orthodox Church, whose priests and believers were persecuted in Soviet times. Once visited by millions, Lenin's tomb is still open to the public but draws smaller crowds. Since January, it has been closed while embalmers give the mummy its regular maintenance.
