CCAT	The Bank of France said on Thursday it made a 1996 net profit of 1.21 billion francs, compared to 1.37 billion in 1995. The central bank made a gross operating profit of 2.84 billion francs, compared to 3.23 million francs in 1995, it said in a statement. It paid tax on 1.27 billion francs of profit. The reduced profit was mainly due to lower interest rates in money market tenders. The central bank also continued a policy of provisioning started last year, it said, but gave no figure for 1996. It made provisions of 1.20 billion francs in 1995. The Bank was made independent from state control in 1994.
MCAT	Wall Street stocks hovered slightly off their session highs in midafternoon activity on Wednesday, with the Dow holding solidly above the 7000 level. The Dow industrials were up 64 points at 7026 and the Standard & Poor's 500 was eight higher at 802. Index-arbitrage trading curbs remained in effect on the New York Stock Exchange.   Analysts said the advance, which extended gains achieved during a near-record session for blue chips on Tuesday, was evidence that the mood on Wall Street, at least for now, has turned optimistic once again. "This market is truly manic depressive," said Scott Bleier, chief investment strategist at Prime Charter Ltd. "We've gone from euphoria to despair and back to euphoria again." The rally remained broad, with advancing issues holding to a two-to-one edge on active NYSE volume of about 385 million shares. Technology stocks were sharply higher. The Nasdaq Composite jumped 19 points to 1261. ((-- Wall Street desk, 212-859-1730))
ECAT	Yugoslavia's government will not rely on the central bank funding to finance its public sector needs, the newly appointed Yugoslav Finance Minister said on Thursday. "I will immediately forget the central bank as a source of financing budget deficits," Bozidar Gazivoda, told Reuters in an interview. "Public sector needs must be financed from real sources only. We must forget any budget financing through the central bank," he added. "This is not easy in an economy which had been brought to a halt with four years of sanctions. But we must raise output, open to the outside world and observe international rules of the game." -- Gordana Filipovic, Belgrade newsroom, +381 11 222 4254
