MCAT	The Bank of Canada said on Thursday it is considering changing the rules governing federal debt auctions in Canada to prevent manipulation and maintain investor confidence. The new rules under consideration were included in a discussion paper released on Thursday which asks market participants for their views on the changes. The central bank said the new rules are designed to avert so-called squeezes, which take place when just one or a few investors buy up an entire bond or T-bill issue. These investors then hike the price for resale to other investors who need to own the issue. "It is very important that the confidence of direct participants and end-investors in the auction process be sustained. Auctions should be free of, and be perceived as being free of, manipulation," the bank said in the paper. Under the new rules dealers and customers bidding at auctions would have to dislose their holdings of the debt issues being bid for. Bidding limits would also be put in place for customers buying through dealers. Penalties would be imposed on those who break the new rules. The central bank also said it would step up its surveillance of bond and T-bill auctions. Analysts said the push for new regulation is being prompted by a variety of factors, including a decline in the federal government's borrowing requirements. Canada's budget deficit has shrunk since Finance Minister Paul Martin took office and it is expected to decline further in coming years. As a result the amount of debt being auctioned will also shrink, increasing the likelihood that entire issues may be bought up by one or just a few market participants. The growing size and influence of many market players, as well as the consolidation of the major banks and investment dealers also increase the need for the new regulations, the central bank said. "These things taken together point to a need to clarify and strengthen the rules. This has not just come up out of nowhere. It's been under discussion for some time," said a Department of Finance official. The official noted there has also been an increase in anecdotal reports of squeezes, particularly with T-bills, which mature in one year or less. The Canadian government has reduced the size of its T-bill tenders over the past several months and has shifted more of its borrowing into the less volatile bond markets. "The T-bill sector is the area in which we've experienced the most frequently reported problems, although it has also been in the bond market," the official said. The Bank of Canada is asking market participants for comments on the proposed rules by March 31, 1997. More discussion papers are expected in the new year, and new regulations would likely be put in place by this time next year, the official said. ((Reuters Toronto Bureau (416) 941-8100))
GCAT	These are some of the main stories in Sofia newspapers today. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy. STANDART -- Bulgaria's President Petar Stoyanov said he had asked for an official meeting with Russia's President Boris Yeltsin to clarify Bulgaria's position on the eastward expansion of NATO. -- Bulgaria's Trade and Industrial Chamber (BTIC) has proposed to the interim cabinet to ban street trade in foods, BTIC chairman Bozhidar Bozhinov said. @ -- Bulgaria's Black Sea resort Albena is expected to invest some $5 million in reconstruction and development of its facilities by the beginning of May, Albena's executive director Krassimir Stanev said. -- Bulgaria's Trade minister Daniela Bobeva left for Brussels to attend a meeting on standartisation of trade ministers from the European Union countries and EU associate members, private Balkan news agency said. -- Bulgaria's President Petar Stoyanov discussed speeding up privatisation in the country with the visiting chairman of the global investment firm Goldman Sachs Peter Sutherland. @ 24 CHASA -- The Russian Rosneft oil company is interested in buying a stake in Bulgaria's biggest oil refinery Neftochim, Rosneft's vice president Favoris Davletyarov said. -- Bulgaria is expected to start using in the next few weeks a 100 million mark commodity credit, extended by Germany in 1992, Agriculture minister Roumen Hristov said. TRUD @ -- Introduction of a currency board system is part of the measures to restore confidence in Bulgaria and statements to the contrary could have a destasbilising effect, Bulgaria's Union of Democratic Forces leader Ivan Kostov said. -- Bulgaria's year-on-year inflation in February was 1,839 percent, National Statistics Institute figures showed. PARI -- Bulgaria's Privatisation Agency said it had sold a 80 percent stake of bankrupt electronic components maker Mikroelektronika to Sofia-registered Secury Mark for $704,870. @ -- Thirty-two percent of Bulgarians trust the European Union and another 27 percent have a conditional confidence in the EU, Bulgaria's Noema polling agency said. -- Sofia Newsroom, (++359-2) 981 8569
ECAT	The International Monetary Fund said on Wednesday it has approved credits totalling $430 million for Romania, giving a boost to the new centrist government's economic reform programme. An IMF statement said the 13-month standby agreement was approved on Tuesday at an Executive Board meeting in Washington. The first instalment of about $86 million was being made available immediately, it said. Four additional quarterly instalments of the same size were "subject to observance of performance criteria and a review of the exchange rate policy". Two reviews of economic performance would be conducted in mid-August and mid-February 1998. The government and central bank had viewed IMF approval as the gateway for increasing foreign investment levels --among the lowest in ex-communist eastern Europe. "Foreign investors are reassured by recent developments in Romanian politics and this support from the IMF confirms that Romania is likely to pursue an economic policy attractive to foreign investors," one analyst said by telephone from London. Another analyst welcomed the news as positive for Romania's international image. There was "a strong appetite", she said, for future Eurobond issues. The IMF suspended credits to Romania last year after saying the leftist government had overspent and hobbled foreign exchange markets ahead of elections it lost last November. The poll defeat ended seven years of rule by ex-communists. The new government, committed to narrowing the gap in living standards with ex-communist Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic, launched talks with the IMF and other international lenders immediately after taking office. To prove its mettle ahead of the IMF decision, the government rammed an austerity budget through parliament in record time and secured approval of laws on bank privatisation and ownership of land by foreigners. It also proceeded with a decision to close dozens of loss-making farms and factories. The Fund's statement said the main objectives of the government's reform programme were to reduce monthly inflation to about two percent in the second half of the year, cut the current account deficit to $1.4 billion from last year's $2.3 billion and increase foreign exchange reserves. It has set a budget deficit target of 4.5 percent of gross domestic product, down from last year's 5.8 percent. The statement acknowledged the need to "cushion the most vulnerable part of the Romanian population" by increasing social security spending to 10 percent of GDP. The government launched its stabilisation programme in February, introducing tough monetary policies and freeing prices on staples and utilities which pushed monthly inflation to over 30 percent last month. An IMF mission in Romania this month said the government's 1997 inflation target of 90 percent was feasible but ambitious after posting 76.5 percent in the first quarter alone.
