GCAT	Jesper Parnevik curled in a 60 feet birdie putt at the last hole to snatch a one shot lead from holder Colin Montgomerie in the third round of the Lancome Trophy on Saturday. The Swede's four-under-par 66 was matched by the Scot, who appeared set for first place himself until he bogeyed the 209 yards final hole after his tee shot left him with a bad lie in a greenside bunker. Then Parnevik, playing behind, rolled in his swinging putt from just off the front of the green for his nine-under total of 201, one better than Montgomerie. Ian Woosnam, Montgomerie's rival for the European Order of Merit title, could only manage a 70 and was four shots off the lead after sharing it overnight. With Woosnam on five-under were fellow Britons Jamie Spence, the first round leader who carded a 67, and Ross Drummond, who shot 69. Parnevik, now a U.S. Tour player, is ineligible for Ryder Cup points in Europe but Montgomerie insisted that he will be needed for next year's defence against the Americans. "I'm mightily impressed by Parnevik. He's one of the top five players in Europe," Montgomerie said.   Montgomerie pointed to this weekend's President's Cup in which the Americans lead an International team containing no Europeans by 7-1/2 points to 2-1/2 to justify his support for Parnevik. "The international team is as strong if not stronger that we are and they're getting thrashed. We will need our strongest team," he said. "He should be in the Ryder Cup team, definitely." Parnevik responded by saying he would like to think he was one of the leading Europeans, "but it's all down to politics, like anything else". The Swede, runner-up in the 1994 British Open, has committed himself to playing predominantly on the U.S. Tour rather than trying to qualify in Europe. Parnevik said he was surprised at his score because he was up all night with food poisoning. "I'd have taken a 70, especially after a bogey at the second hole," he said. "I felt I played sloppy golf today. I was very tired." But he birdied the next two and the eighth and ninth, lost a shot at the 14th before a birdie at 16 set up his glorious final putt. Montgomerie was quickly out of the blocks with birdies at the first two holes, which he bogeyed in Friday's round, and the fourth, where he made a 30-foot putt. He made further birdies at the 10th and 17th before his dropped shot at the last. "One behind is fine. I'm quite confident in what I'm doing," said the Scot, who regained the Order of Merit lead from Woosnam with his record-breaking victory last Sunday in the European Masters. Woosnam has been troubled by a bad back but said that had no bearing on his round. "I just didn't drive the ball well today," he said.
GCAT	Three Slovenian rightwing parties, which won half the seats in parliament in a general election, said on Thursday they had agreed a cooperation pact to improve their bid to form the next government. The rightist "Slovenian Spring" alliance of the conservative People's Party, centre-right Social Democrats and Christian Democrats together won 45 out of 90 parliamentary seats in the November 10 election. They missed out on an absolute majority by just one seat in Slovenia's second general election since declaring independence from former Yugoslavia. "The agreement, that will result in tight cooperation between the three parties in parliament, could be signed before the first session of the new parliament on November 28," Christian Democrat spokesman Valentin Hajdinjak told Reuters. The parties are attempting to unseat Prime Minister Janez Drnovsek, whose centre-left Liberal Democrats emerged as the single biggest party in the election, winning 25 seats. The alliance was seeking to form a goverment with People's Party leader Marjan Podobnik as premier and, if successful, would swing Slovenian politics firmly to the right. The People's Party, which won big support from farmers suspicious of Ljubljana's bid to join the European Union, is the strongest of the alliance parties with 19 seats. The alliance has already approached the Liberal Democrats, offering them a place in government if Drnovsek steps down as premier. But the Liberal Democrats have refused, saying they will only take part in the next administration if Drnovsek remains government leader. Hajdinjak said the "Spring" parties were confident of gaining enough support among other smaller parties to form a working government even if Liberal Democrats refused to join in. The cooperation pact has made Drnovsek's task of forming the next government much harder. He has to prise one or two of the "Spring" parties out of the alliance to have any chance. President Milan Kucan said on Tuesday he would choose a candidate for prime minister within 30 days of the first parliamentary session, during which time he would hold consultations with the leaders of all parties in parliament. Kucan was likely first to call on Drnovsek to try to form a coalition government but may be forced to turn to Podobnik if the Liberal Democrats fail to break the rightist alliance.
GCAT	Hungarian soccer club Ujpest plans to become the first club in Eastern Europe to go public, with a flotation on the Budapest Stock Exchange (BSE). Club president, former Olympic fencing champion Bence Szabo, said he plans a radical overhaul of the club's structure in order to attract foreign investment. "Football is no longer just a sport," Szabo told Reuters. "It has become part of the entertainment business." Currently the soccer team is part of a larger sports club with 15 sections including water-polo and fencing. Szabo said he wants to create an independent football club, owned by a public limited company which will float on the BSE. Ujpest's 70-member executive will hold a general meeting on Monday to vote on separating out the football activities and debate the move to a new structure. "Clubs don't live only from ticket receipts but from merchandising and a whole range of business activities. We need to change and my generation sees that Hungarian football has to be built on solid business foundations," said the 35-year-old Szabo, who won gold for Hungary in Barcelona in 1992. "Going to the stock market would also allow small businessmen and supporters to have a stake in the club," he said, adding that the move could also attract much-needed foreign investment. The club is currently in talks with French club Metz and Szabo said he hoped that others would show interest as Hungary lines up to become one of the first new members of the European Union. Szabo would not be drawn on whether Ujpest would sell a majority share in the initial public offering. The move is another sign of the increasingly important role private investors are taking in Hungarian football. Two years ago, current champions MTK were bought by a Hungarian company Sportinvest, owned by Hungarian Gabor Varszegi, CEO of consumer goods retailer Fotex . After winning promotion to the first division in 1995, MTK used Varszegi's cash to recruit many of Hungary's top players and this season won the league and cup double. Brian Sturgess, of ING Barings in London, a media analyst who specialises in football stocks, said he welcomed Ujpest's plans. "In Eastern Europe there is a move away from the communist-era model of the giant sports club financed by a ministry and there is a clear move towards private capital. This will accelerate, especially with the certain increase in the value of TV soccer rights in the region." Sturgess said he believed an Ujpest flotation could be successful provided it attracts larger investors. "Of course there will be local interest from small investors but to really succeed they need to attract institutional investors. "The traditional emerging markets investor may stay away but I am sure that the communication funds and leisure funds would be interested." Ujpest, known as Ujpest Dozsa during the communist era, when they were backed by Hungary's Interior Ministry, are one of Hungary's most successful clubs. They have won the Hungarian championship 19 times and in 1969 reached the final of Europe's Inter-Cities Fairs Cup - the forerunner of the UEFA Cup. But following the change of system in 1989 the club struggled and in 1993 had to win a play-off in order to stay in the first division. Last season, however, they finished second in the league earning a place in the UEFA Cup.
MCAT	Dated Brent traded on Thursday at the equivalent of the lower end of Wednesday's range, traders said. A Dec 17-19 cargo was sold at Dated Brent evens based on the balance of this week's published quotes, which traders said was equivalent to Jan Brent +35/+40 cents. The seller bought the cargo at Jan Brent +35 cents on Wednesday. A Dec 19-21 cargo sold later that day for Jan Brent +49 cents to a Wall Street trader collecting barrels for a transatlantic trip. Two Brent cargoes were due to turn wet on Thursday, traders said. -- London Newsroom +44 171 542 7930
MCAT	Australian bond futures extended Tuesday's consolidative sell-off in after-hours trading as U.S. Treasuries also posted a modest correction. The September 10-year bond futures contract ended SYCOM at 92.900, down from Tuesday's 92.925 pit close and having dipped to 92.875 at one stage. The month's steep rising trendline, and last leg of the rally from 91.700 in April, is being put under pressure at 92.880, and the market needs to close above this level to maintain the bullish trend, analysts said.   The 10-year bond, through the now-expired June contract, touched a 3-1/4 year high on Monday of 93.090. The corrective pullback across the curve has brought the market back from its extreme overbought levels of over 80 percent on relative strength indices to just under 75 percent. Local data for Wednesday remains thin with only Westpac's leading index for April due for release, leaving the market vulnerable to movements in offshore markets. The easier tone in the U.S. ended a three-day run of price gains with a benign CPI report for May having been largely built in after the rally which followed Friday's weak PPI.   -- Colin Brinsden 61-2 9373-1800
MCAT	The overnight interbank rate closed at 5.5 percent on aggressive lending by foreign banks long on ringgit, dealers said on Wednesday. The lending started late in the day after the overnight had earlier stabilised around 6.5/7.0 percent after opening at 8.0 percent, they said.   "It was quite sudden and the banks were lending all the way down from 7.0 percent. It was last taken at 5.5 percent," said a dealer with a Malaysian bank. "Foreign banks were long on ringgit and had little choice but to offer back to the market due to the curbs on swaps transactions," he said. Bank Negara announced on Sunday that local banks would have to limit their non-trade related currency swaps to $2.0 million with each overseas customer, from Monday. It said the move was to help control interest rates more effectively. The central bank has in the last two weeks been trying to lower interest rates in an effort to boost domestic economic activity. Dealers said the overnight rate also fell ahead of the return of some funds at the end of the week. There will be a maturity of Bank Negara bills worth one billion ringgit on Friday. -- Syed Azman (603-201 4813)
MCAT	U.S. Plains feedlot cattle markets Monday were at a standstill, with no sales of slaughter steers or heifers reported, feedlot sources said. Packer bids from $63.00 to $64.00 per cwt were passed by owners pricing cattle at $65.00 to mostly $66.00, they said. Feedlot cattle prices this week were expected steady to $1.00 higher, compared with last week's sales at $64.00, the dealers said. Prices were seen lifted by firm beef demand on Friday. Prices also were seen underpinned by lighter-weight cattle, compared with a year ago, and the ability of feedlots to remain current in their marketings, they said.   Support this week also was expected from only slight increases in this week's showlists, sources said. Texas Panhandle and western Oklahoma showlists were pegged near 81,000 head, up 2,000 from a week ago, sources there said. Kansas showlists were estimated near 78,500, up 700 from a week ago. Nebraska's showlist was estimated near 82,000 head, down 1,000 from last week. Support in fed cattle prices could be offset by lower to Monday's sharply lower CME live cattle futures and slow beef sales, versus active sales at higher prices on Friday, market sources noted. ((Bob Janis 312-408-8720))
GCAT	Israel, fearful of more bombings after last week's suicide blasts, was on heightened security alert on Sunday as the deadline passed for an Islamic militant ultimatum. Police said they were taking every precaution as tension rose in the light of a demand that Israel free all Palestinian prisoners by 9 p.m. (1800 GMT). Shortly before the deadline passed, police reported that a Palestinian was found shot dead near Carmel Jewish settlement in the West Bank, not far from Hebron. The circumstances of the man's death were not clear. Palestinians said he was shot by a Jewish settler in a passing car. Police said they had two separate reports from the area: of shots fired by unidentified gunmen in a car and a body found. "We don't know if there is a connection," a police spokeswoman said. The demand for the freeing of Palestinian prisoners was made in a leaflet claiming Wednesday's double suicide bombing, which killed 13 people and wounded 170, in the name of the Islamic militant Hamas group. Some Israeli and Palestinian officials voiced doubts, however, about the leaflet's authenticity. Israel announced no plans to free anyone. The leaflet did not spell out what would happen if the ultimatum was refused. Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu told his cabinet that Israel would not honour peace deals it signed with Yasser Arafat unless the Palestinian leader cracked down on militants. "If Arafat honours his commitments in the agreement, chiefly to fight terrorism, the agreement will survive. If he doesn't, we will not keep up our part of the bargain unequivocally," an official statement quoted Netanyahu as saying. He later told CBS-TV's "Face the Nation": "The whole peace is at stake. Arafat must make a choice and make it now." But top Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat, in an interview on CNN television network, said Arafat had offered to join Netanyahu in fighting militants and had been spurned. "Mr Netanyahu, instead of accepting President Arafat's offer to join him in fighting terror and the enemies of peace, he declared a series of collective punishment measures against the Palestinian people," Erekat said. Israeli U.N. Ambassador-designate Dore Gold, with Erekat in the studio, asked if Netanyahu had spurned Arafat's offer, said: "Well, I don't think that's exactly correct". Gold did not elaborate but said that prior to the attack on Wednesday, Palestinian security officials were making cooperation in the fight against militants conditional on Israel making "certain tangible concessions". Palestinians have demanded Israel halt Jewish settlement of occupied Arab lands which they say pre-empts peace talks. Troops overnight arrested another 37 Palestinians in the West Bank suspected of involvement in Islamic militant groups, bringing to 116 the number arrested since the bombing in the main Jewish street market. Israeli Police Commissioner Assaf Hefetz, asked if Israel had specific information about more attacks, told army radio: "It's more than just an estimate. We have a series of...details that point to this possibility." He said after four days of investigation, officials were still uncertain who carried out Wednesday's attack. Thousands of Israeli police guarded shopping malls, bus stations and other places where crowds gather in Israel's main cities, and stopped cars for inspection along key roads. The suicide bombing revived memories of a bombing spree last year in which Islamic miliants struck four times in nine days, killing 57 people. Israel suspended already dormant peace talks with the Palestinians as a result of Wednesday's bombing and sealed off the West Bank and Gaza Strip, barring tens of thousands of Palestinians from reaching their jobs in the Jewish state. Palestinians accused Israel of imposing collective punishment on Palestinians and expressed hope U.S. Middle East envoy Dennis Ross, due later this week on another mediation mission, could put peacemaking back on track. U.S. Republican Speaker Newt Gingrich told Fox Television he backed Israel taking action if necessary on Palestinian territory and condemned Arafat for not fighting militants. Top Israeli security officials met their Palestinian counterparts overnight to discuss the investigation into Wednesday's bombing, security sources said. But Jibril al-Rajoub, the head of the Palestinian preventive security in the West Bank, said the meetings did not constitute a renewal of security cooperation. Arafat is to go to Jordan on Monday for talks with King Hussein on the deepening crisis, his office said. Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy's office said he would go to Egypt on Tuesday for talks with President Hosni Mubarak.
CCAT	Two of Switzerland's top financial groups, Credit Suisse Group and Winterthur Group, Monday announced plans to merge and create one of the world's leading financial service providers. The deal catapults Credit Suisse Group into the position of undisputed leader among Switzerland's Big Three banks, taking place amid deep structural changes in global financial markets and fierce competition in the insurance industry. "The merger is a powerful, forward-looking response to developments in the financial services market," said Lukas Muehlemann, chief executive of the combined group. The stock market reacted positively to the announcement and industry analysts were also in favour of the move, noting it is likely to put pressure on Union Bank of Switzerland UBS and Swiss Bank Corp. SBC to meet the challenge. "I think this puts pressure on the other big Swiss banks," said Thomas Della Putta of private bankers Pictet & Cie. The merger comes after months of intense speculation about Winterthur and only days after financier Martin Ebner said he wanted to acquire a majority of the insurer. One analyst questioned whether the timing of the merger was dictated by the stake amassed in Winterthur by Ebner's BZ Group. The combination of Credit Suisse, currently Switzerland's second-largest bank, with Winterthur, the third-largest insurer, should result in gains of 300 million to 350 million Swiss francs ($199 million to $232 million) within three years from higher income and cost-cutting. A maximum of 500 jobs worldwide will be lost due to attrition, but the companies said in a joint statement that there would be no layoffs. "The two companies are now in an even better position to provide their personal and corporate customers with attractive financial products combining the advantages of banking and insurance solutions," the companies said. Shareholders of both companies will be asked to approve the deal on Sept. 5. Assuming approval, Credit Suisse Group will offer Winterthur shareholders to swap one of their shares for 7.3 Credit Suisse shares. Winterthur will then become part of the Credit Suisse Group, boosting its total assets to around 700 billion francs ($463 billion), giving it a market capitalisation of more than 50 billion ($33 billion) and around 700 billion francs ($463 billion) in assets under management. The merger illustrates the blurring distinction between banks and insurance companies, where market position and market presence is becoming increasingly critical. "Strategically, this makes sense for Credit Suisse. The general trend in Europe clearly goes toward bancassurance. It's not the insurance companies that need the banks, it's the banks that need the insurance companies to be more competitive," said Della Putta. "The merger will allow the group to exploit to the full the advantages of being a banassurance provider in all customer and market segments," the companies said. Credit Suisse Group, reporting its half-year results early due to the merger announcement, said preliminary figures showed net profit surged 70 percent to around 1.41 billion Swiss francs ($933 million) in the first half of 1997. Net profit growth was at the high end of growth estimates, which had run between 45 and 90 percent.
ECAT	Statistics New Zealand is laying the ground for a five-yearly review of the consumers' price index, a process which almost certainly will result in debate about the index's influence on monetary policy, the New Zealand Press Association reported on Tuesday. Deputy government statistician Ian Ewing said the composition of an advisory committee, including international experts in the composition of consumer price indexes, was currently under discussion with Statistics Minister Maurice Williamson.   Once established, the committee would complete consideration of papers and conceptual issues before rebalancing of the CPI got under way in the second half of next year. Ewing told NZPA uses of the CPI had changed over the years, and representation on the committee would reflect those changes. While employer and union groups had been major users in the past, that had dwindled with the demise of centralised wage fixing after 1984, and the Treasury and Reserve Bank interests would be present on the committee given the importance of the CPI in monetary policy.   represent producers, consumers, employers and employee groups, major government policy agencies, in particular the Reserve Bank and Treasury, and possibly other groups within the community who may be affected by government policy as it affects prices," Ewing said. "Papers are presented to the committee for advice and guidance and, as a result of that, we carry out a five-year rebase of the CPI, and the extent of that is governed in part by the committee."   Ewing said rebalancing of the CPI would involve considerations such as changes in spending behaviour in the last five years. Households, for instance, have been spending less on clothing due to the impact of deregulation of the industry reducing prices, while imports of used Japanese cars have reduced transport costs and, thus, overall spending. Statistics New Zealand's household economic survey had also found that people were spending less of their income on housing, Ewing said.   However, the treatment of housing is likely to come in for some solid debate with the Reserve Bank seen as arguing to have interest rates removed from any measure of its cost. Ewing said there were opposing schools of thought on whether house ownership should be treated as an item of shelter or as an investment. If it was accepted that housing was a consumption rather than an investment good, then there were issues of how housing was priced.   "Do you assume the cost is what you would get if you rented the house out, as against the actual costs of owning the house -- interest paid on mortgages, that sort of thing," Ewing said. But even if elements of the CPI were removed for monetary policy purposes, a broader-based index could be more appropriate than one confined to measuring the impact of inflation on households, he said. However, another index for monetary policy purposes would do little to allay Reserve Bank concerns about the CPI's impact in setting inflationary expectations, he suggested.   "The CPI has been the most prominent, well-known measure of inflation... even though it may have some technical limitations as a tool for measuring inflation," Ewing said. -- Wellington newsroom 64 4 4734 746
