ECAT	An official from the National Association of Purchasing Management (NAPM) characterized as steady the overall price picture in the manufacturing sector of the economy, depite a near four-point jump in manufacturing prices in September. Speaking to reporters in a teleconference after the NAPM released its monthly report on manufacturing, Ralph Kauffman said, "I would say it's fairly steady right now.  We are seeing some increases in some areas; a lot of them seem to be related to oil and natural gas input." Kauffman is chairman of the NAPM business survey committee.   As for growth in manufacturing, Kauffman said factory owners may wish to grow at a slightly more rapid pace, but he noted that they are aware of the risks of too much growth. "I think they might like a little bit more growth, but they are aware of problems that would come from too much growth," Kauffman said. Going forward, Kauffman said future indicators point to continued steady growth in manufacturing near term. "I think continued steady growth at approximately the level we've seen recently is probably indicated for the very near term," he added.   Steady growth near term would continue a trend that has been in place over the past six months. Kauffman said it would be fair to characterize manufacturing growth over the last half year as "steady." "Our index has kind of fluctuated a bit up and down, but all within the range indicating growth," he said. Turning to the backlog of orders index in September, Kauffman said that component hinted that production will not fall dramatically over the short haul. "I think what it (the backlog of orders index) says is that production is not going to drop drastically," he said. The NAPM's index slipped to 51.7 in September from 52.6 in August.  Prices were up almost four points to 51.2. -- N.A. Treasury Desk, 212-859-1660
ECAT	The Clinton administration, preparing for next week's presidential trip to Mexico, Central America and the Caribbean, is defending its trade record, but analysts warn that the United States is losing ground because it still lacks "fast track" authority for trade deals. "I think this administration's trade record in the first term has been a very strong one, including the passage of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA)," said President Bill  Clinton's special adviser for Latin America, Thomas McLarty. McLarty, a former White House chief-of-staff, also pointed to the 1994 Summit of the Americas Clinton hosted in Miami, where the 34 countries represented launched a project of forging a hemispheric free trade agreement by 2005. At that summit the three NAFTA partners, the United States, Mexico and Canada, offered Chile the chance to become the fourth member. The United States, however, has not been able to make good on that invitation because it lacks "fast track," a key authorisation from Congress to negotiate new trade deals. Treaties signed under that legislation cannot be amended by Congress, which must vote them up or down in a short time. U.S. analysts argue that the lack of "fast track" has kept the United States on the sidelines and strengthened the hand of Brazil, the leading voice in the MERCOSUR South American common market agreement. While NAFTA has not expanded since it started in 1994, MERCOSUR has struck deals with Chile and Bolivia and is in talks with other South American nations and the European Union. "If we drop the ball, the United States' credibility will be shattered," said Richard Feinberg, dean of the University of California at San Diego's Graduate School of International Relations and Pacific Studies. "That will result not only in stalling integration but it will also affect all other areas of cooperation, because trade is the grease of this process," said Feinberg, who was Clinton's Latin America specialist in the National Security Council. C. Fred Bergsten, director of the Washington-based Institute for International Economics, noted that Brazil has always had a strong domestic constituency rooting for protectionism and economic dominance in South America. "If the United States falters," said Bergsten, "the paradoxical result of the summit of Miami will be the enhancement of Brazil's leadership." While the White House acknowledges that the stakes are high, it argues that having "fast track" at this point is not as crucial as it will be in October, when Clinton is due to visit Brazil and Argentina, Mercosur's main partners, and Venezuela. McLarty pointed out that Mexico already is in NAFTA and the third biggest U.S. trading partner, while Central American and Caribbean nations are more interested in the Caribbean Basin Initiative, a pact that grants preferences to their exports to the United States. Nevertheless, he said Clinton will be speaking frequently about the need to expand trade, hammering on the fact that the United States must hold natural markets like Latin America. In the meantime, his negotiators like U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky will continue to hold talks with the Republican majority in Congress to try to find common ground on "fast track" authority. "Our approach is to build a critical mass, a bipartisan consensus that will support 'fast track' legislation," McLarty said. "I hope we will be successful, I think we will be". Republicans, however, voiced doubts about the administration's intentions and wondered if Democratic presidential politics were not muddling the process. House of Representatives minority leader Richard Gephardt, a potential contender for the Democratic nomination together with Vice President Al Gore, has spoken against expanding NAFTA. Championing two key Democratic issues, the White House has long insisted on including the authority to negotiate labour and environmental issues in "fast track" legislation. Republicans said they now agree to include any trade-related issues, but complained that the administration still has not come forward with a proposal. Arizona Republican Representative Jim Kolbe, a leading free trade advocate, warned that the window of opportunity for approving "fast track" was growing narrower. "We can't expect to get 'fast track' this year if we don't get it by the August recess," Kolbe told reporters.
ECAT	A year after he was sacked, Argentina's former economy minister Domingo Cavallo said Sunday the country's economy has developed very much as he predicted. "The economy is going well, just as I had predicted would happen," Cavallo said in an interview with daily La Nacion. Asked if Argentina is converting itself into an Asian-style tiger economy of Latin America, Cavallo said: "Argentina already is, together with Chile, a kind of tiger." "If we look at the performance of the 1990s, growth is impressive, it is of the magnitude achieved by the Asian tigers in the 1960s and 1970s," he said. Cavallo predicted growth would probably reach eight percent this year. The former minister said there were still necessary changes required in the economy, such as labor market reforms to help bring down unemployment. Among policies still needed to reduce the jobless rate, Cavallo said more work was needed in sectors like health and education. He also stressed that policies are needed to support the growth of small and medium-sized companies, so that they in turn will create more jobs. All the same, he characterized his successor, Roque Fernandez, as "a good administrator". ((-- Axel Bugge, Buenos Aires Newsroom, 541 318-0668))
GCAT	The Mars rover rolled down a ramp from the Pathfinder space lander late on Saturday onto the surface of the "Red Planet", U.S. space officials said. The six-wheeled buggy-type vehicle named "Sojourner" was scheduled to begin exploring the surface of Mars on Sunday, analysing its rocks and soil for at least one week.   The successful deployment came after a day of suspense at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory here where space officials had feared the scientific aspects of the $266-million mission might be hurt by a communications glitch. However, communications between the lander and Sojourner were later restored, allowing signals from mission control to get through to the rover's on-board computer. After a ramp was lowered, the rover was told to "stand-up" from its stowed position and once the wheel bogeys were locked in place, the tiny 22-pound (10 kg) vehicle -- looking like a workbench or microwave oven on wheels -- slowly moved down the 35-degree slope onto the Martian surface. Officials confirmed at 10.59 p.m. PDT (0559GMT Sunday) that the rover was on the planet's surface. During its exploration, the solar-powered rover will navigate with the aid of laser beams, will take 3-D photographs with its twin-lens camera and will be able to pick up and analyze samples of rocks and soil and transmit the data to Earth.
