MCAT	UK gilts could struggle to maintain the new highs reached late last week after a U.S.-inspired rally, with little of the upcoming week's domestic data likely to be supportive, analysts said on Monday. "Gilts are looking a little vulnerable and a chunky retail sales number on Wednesday could reverse their recent good performance," said Kevin Adams, gilts analyst at BZW. Analysts said the yield spread between 10-year gilts and U.S. T-notes of 100 basis points in particular looks unsustainable.   "That spread is as narrow as it has been for a while. Given the feeling now prevalent that the U.S. economy has slowed down of its own accord, that spread could push back out," Adams said. U.S. Treasuries forged ahead on Friday after a muted increase in retail sales activity and consumer prices in August eased fears of a near-term U.S. rate rise. U.S. bonds gained nearly two points and gilts a point. "Gilts were dragged up by the U.S. on Friday, but unless we get some good news of our own I can't see it lasting," said a gilts salesman. August PSBR data due on Tuesday offers most hope, he said.   "The market got a very good figure for July and is expecting something less favourable this time, but I think it may be pleasantly surprised." The consensus forecast suggests a borrowing requirement of 4.1 billion stg in August after July's repayment of 1.7 billion. But the rest of the week's data may underline the British economy's strength, especially in the consumer sector, and give gilts a rough ride. August retail sales data is forecast to show a 0.5 percent rise and a year-on-year rise of 3.5 percent compared with 2.2 percent in July.   And M4 figures due on Thursday are forecast to show broad money growth stuck stubbornly at 9.0 percent in August, the upper limit of the government's monitoring range. But BZW's Adams said the market may get some support from Europe even if the data and survey's show renewed economic strength. The German ifo survey due later this week will be a focal point. "Bond markets could react positively to a strong figure because of Germany needs to see stronger growth to ease its fiscal problems," said Adams.   The meeting this weekend between EU finance ministers in Dublin will help focus the markets' mind on the Maastricht convergence criteria for European monetary union. Among the issues addressed will be the stability pact on fiscal decifits and the possibility of automatic fines for divergent economies. Gilt futures clung to Friday's gains in early Monday trading, the December contract stood at 108-00. But the gilts salesman said if the future breaks above 108-00, he has a batch of sell orders to place in the market.   "There are a lot of investors seeking to move a bit shorter and 108-00 is the level they want to sell at," he said. The yield curve has been steady over the last week with only the five-year area cheapening slightly. But one trader at a GEMM said the best area remains 10-years. "That will avoid any problems at the short end if interest rate expectations radically alter after the retail sales data," he said. And the gilts market could be undermined further if the FTSE index of 100 leading shares continues to make new record highs. "There has been a lot of shifting out of gilts and into equities over the last three months and that shows no signs of abating," the salesman said. -- London Newsroom +44 171 542 7715
ECAT	Following is a summary of the views on monetary policy of the six members of the UK Treasury panel of independent forecasters: KATE BARKER, CONFEDERATION OF BRITISH INDUSTRY "During (the period) since 1992, there has still been a tendency towards conflict between the Chancellor (of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke) and Governor of the Bank of England Eddie George which has at times called into question the credibility of policy. The concern is that this would be more damaging when the economy moved into an above-trend period in which the inflation threat were more severe. Serious consideration should be given to moving towards greater independence for the Bank of England in the setting of interest rates. The CBI recommendations for this year's budget therefore include a slight tightening of fiscal policy, with tax reductions of at most one billion stg (and arguably nil, if the PSBR data does not show a clear improvement from the prior year), including some reduction in business taxation, as the personal sector is already in robust short-term health." She forecasts GDP growth of 3.1 percent in 1997 and a 3.5 percent increase in domestic demand, with RPIX falling to 2.4 percent.   PROFESSOR TIM CONGDON, LOMBARD STREET RESEARCH "The achievement (of medium-term financial stability) of the early and mid-1990s is in jeopardy. The economy is once again on the threshold of a business cycle which will lead to higher inflation in the late 1990s. The period of stability has come to an end. The right answer on the monetary front is to raise interest rates and to sell government debt exclusively at the long end (ie. away from the banking system).On the fiscal side, the PSBR should be reduced by tax increases and /or expenditure cuts. The monetary measures are far more important than the fiscal, as fiscal action has probably has little effect on national income except in the short run." He forecasts GDP growth of 4.2 percenrt in 1997 with domestic demand growing by 4.6 percent. RPIX will hit 2.5 percent in 1996 but edge up to 2.9 percent by 1998, he said.   GAVYN DAVIES, GOLDMAN SACHS "There is a prima facie case for tightening macro policy now. Ideally this should be done through fiscal policy, but it is not realistic in present political circumstances to expect a tightening greater than 0.4 percent of GDP built into the pre-budget baseline; indeed it is questionable whether even that can be delivered. Thus, the main burden may well fall on the monetary side. There must be a strong presumption that base rates will need to rise in the next 6-12 months, if not sooner. The eventual extent of the rise depends partly on timing, but is unlikely to be any less than the 150 basis points which successfully stabilised the inflation rate in 1994-95." Davies forecasts GDP growth of 3.4 percent in 1997 with domestic demand growing at 3.2 percent. RPIX will fall to 2.4 percent in 1997 and edge up to 2.6 percent in 1998.   PROFESSOR PATRICK MINFORD, LIVERPOOL UNIVERSITY "All this talk (of rate rises) is entirely premature. Consumer spending is growing moderately well...the problem remains in manufacturing. The case for cutting interest rates now remains. If in due course the economy returns to rude growth, thoughts can then turn to raising them. But we are months if not years away from that situation. We should push tax rates as low as possible consistent with "sustainable' public finances: effectively public borrowing steady at about 2.0 percent of national income. That bald arithmetic implies taxes could in principle be cut by 12 billion stg. Given the uncertainties surround public spending plans (particularly those of a possible Labour government) any such figure is too large. However, it could reasonably underpin a rolling programme of planned tax cuts by this government, committed as it is to these spending plans. A 4.0 billion stg tax cut and a standard rate of 22 pence would be a sensible start to such a programme this year." Mindford forecasts GDP gowth of 3.1 percent in 1997 with domestic demand growing 2.9 percent. He forecasts RPIX at 2.0 percent in 1997 and 2.2 percent in 1998.   BRIDGET ROSEWELL, BUSINESS STRATEGIES LTD "We have incorporated into our baseline forecasts an increase in interest rates in the second quarter of 1997 of 0.25 percent (this is based on rates standing at 5.75 pecent) followed by further increases through the rest of the year leaving base rates at just over 7.0 percent by the end of 1997. This outome...is the sort we think appropriate. It seem to us not necessarily to be desirable to try and force inflation down below the current rates that we are forecasting in what is likely to be the fastest growth year in the current cycle and therefore one in which inflation is likely to be accelerating. We have assumed that the most likely outcome is that there will be tax cuts in this budget of around 2.5 billion stg, although in our view there is little justification for such cuts. This is especially the case in the area of consumer spending where growth is likely to be strong." She forecasts GDP growth of 3.3 percent in 1997 with domestic demand growing 3.6 percent. RPIX will fall to 2.4 percent in 1997 and edge up to 3.1 percent in 1998, she said.   MARTIN WEALE, NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF ECONOMIC AND SOCIAL RESEARCH "Our forecast shows a chance of about 45 percent that inflation will be 2.5 percent per year or less by the end of next year, and beyond that the situation is likely to deteriorate. It would be a pity to put up taxes and then find that they had to be reduced again. But the risk is the other way round. To leave taxes unchanged in the hope that the fiscal position can be corrected in other ways over the medium term can easily turn into an excuse for doing nothing about the budget deficit; this would let debt and interest payments increase, adding to the magnitude of the eventual adjustment. Provided interest rate policy is set with fiscal adjustment in mind, there is no reason why tax increases should lead to a slowdown in economic activity." He forecasts GDP growth of 3.4 percent in 1997 with domestic demand growing 3.4 percent. RPIX will be 2.7 percent in 1997 and edge up to 3.0 percent in 1998. -- Rosemary Bennett +44 171 542 7715
ECAT	The Bundesbank said on Wednesday that although German economic growth had paused in late 1996, this was not a change in trend and conditions for continued growth appeared good. In its February monthly report the German central bank said structural reform was now needed to give the economy a boost. Proposed reforms to the German tax system were a step in the right direction but had to be implemented quickly. The bank rejected suggestions that it could itself take more action to stimulate the economy. A more economy-oriented policy would hurt the central bank's credibility, unsettle markets and leave structural problems unresolved, it said. "The stimulus within the German economy did not continue towards the end of 1996," the Bundesbank said in its economic review of the winter months. "However the calming in economic activity is not to be seen as the same thing as a change in the trend," it added. Noting that the demand and production patterns seen could at first glance appear similar to the economic weakness which took hold in the second half of 1995, the central bank said that this was not the case as general conditions were much improved. "On a closer look it becomes clear that the important economic environment has improved considerably since then," the report said. "This is particularly true for exchange rates, wage agreements and for interest rates, which are now at a historically low level. This gives justification for the expectation of an acceleration in growth in 1997." The central bank welcomed government steps to improve the competitiveness of German companies through tax reform and reform of welfare payment systems and urged Bonn to implement such reforms quickly to help stimulate investment. Noting that investment was the weakest element in the current economic upturn, the Bundesbank said, "The early creation of certainty (on reform) could help considerably to increase the willingness of companies to invest and thus to create new jobs." It added that any such changes would of course take some time to feed through into the labour market. The German central bank noted that the current historical lows in capital market rates had raised the risk of volatility on bond markets, as developments since the end of last year had shown. "In this environment it is important not to allow any doubt to arise as to the firm stability orientation of monetary policy and as to the lasting consolidation of state budgets ... so as not to provide a floor for speculative exaggerations" the centr al bank said. The Bundesbank also noted that a more reactive monetary policy, as had been urged upon it as a means of combating unemployment and weak spending, "could on the other hand easily prove itself counter-productive because it could lead to loss of credibil ity and higher capital market rates." "Quite apart from that, the current economic problems in Germany, which are overwhelmingly structural in origin, can only be solved by economic and political reforms and not with a policy of cheap money," the report concluded.
CCAT	StaffMark Inc said it is acquiring Baker Street Group, a professional staffing company based in Houston in a merger deal. Terms of the transaction, which will be accounted for as a pooling of interests, were not disclosed. Baker Street Group, with 1996 revenues of approximately $11 million, is its thirteenth acquisition, StaffMark said.   StaffMark, a staffing services company with more than 160 offices in 20 states, Canada, and the United Kingdom, said its latest acquisition will have a positive impact on its earnings per share for 1997. StaffMark, which went public in the last week of September 1966, was up 1-3/8 to 24-7/8, a new high, in midday trading on the Nasdaq.
GCAT	Following are penpix of leading contenders in Thursday's Cheltenham Gold Cup: - - - - IMPERIAL CALL - Last year's winner, heads powerful Irish challenge. Trainer: Fergie Sutherland Jockey: Conor O'DwyerOdds: 9-2 favourite Strengths: Proven over course and distance and a tough perfomer at the highest level. Weaknesses: Has been below his best this season and yet to win in three races (fallen once, slipped up on the flat in another race). Beaten by Danoli last time out, but finished with cut leg. - - - - COOME HILL - Impressive chaser who goes from strength to strength. Trainer: Walter Dennis Jockey: Jamie Osborne Odds: 11-2 Strengths: Has done very little wrong this season apart from an uncharacteristic fall at Sandown. Very impressive on his most recent outing. Weakness: Yet to prove himself at this class, meeting top performers at level weights. - - - - DORANS PRIDE - Second of the Irish challengers and sure to carry plenty of support. Winner of 1995 Stayers Hurdle at Cheltenham Festival. Twice nearly died of colic. Trainer: Michael Hourigan Jockey: Shane Broderick Odds: 6-1 Strengths: Has been brought along quietly in novice chase company winning five in succession, although fell last time out. Weaknesses: Lacks experience at highest chase level and not suited by fast or firm going. Horse may not run if ground becomes too quick. - - - - DANOLI - Third of the Irish and sure to bring the house down if he wins. A great favourite among the Irish and carries a local priest's blessing. Enjoyed brilliant hurdling success in 1994 and 1995, recovering from broken fetlock. Trainer: Tom FoleyJockey: Tommy Treacy Odds: 13-2 Strengths: A class performer as a hurdler, looked every bit a Gold Cup winner last time when beating previous Cheltenham heroes Jodami and Imperial Call. Weaknesses: Jumping is not 100 percent reliable. Has fallen twice this season. Still a novice. - - - - DUBLIN FLYER - Exciting front-runner with plenty of class. Trainer: Tim ForsterJockey: Brendan Powell Odds: 10-1 Strengths: Brave, spectacular jumper who invariably sets the pace. Weaknesses: May be too old at 11 and not guaranteed to last the three mile two furlong (5.2 km) trip. Disappointed in last year's Gold Cup. - - - - ONE MAN - Handsome grey horse; heads the four-strong team of trainer Gordon Richards. Flopped when hot favourite last year.Trainer: Gordon Richards Jockey: Richard Dunwoody Odds: 10-1 Strengths. Arguably the best chaser in Britain after winning the King George VI chase at Kempton in December for the second time in succession. Weaknesses: Big disappointment in last year's Gold Cup, prompting suggestion he neither likes the track nor the distance.
ECAT	Hong Kong's economy is expected to grow  at a healthy clip into 1998, with any negative impact from measures  taken by the post-handover government to cool the property market  likely to be modest, analysts said. "The property market will definitely have an impact on consumption,  and this year the economy has been mainly driven by the domestic sector,"  said George Leung, economic adviser to Hongkong Bank. But the impact  should be mild, he said. Economists polled by Reuters on average expected the territory's gross  domestic product (GDP) to increase by 5.64 percent in 1997 and 5.57  percent in 1998. Consumer prices were expected to rise 6.59 percent  this year and 7.0 percent next year. The forecasts compare with GDP growth of 4.7 percent for all of 1996,  and inflation of 6.0 percent the same year. Hongkong Bank said in a report issued on Thursday that while both  investment and consumer spending were expected to expand strongly  in the second half of the year, growth may be slower than in the first  quarter due to a cooling off in the property market. In its report, Hongkong Bank raised its forecast for 1997 GDP growth  to 5.4 percent from 5.2 percent, based on a better-than-expected performance  in the first quarter driven by strong domestic demand. It trimmed its inflation forecast to 6.4 percent from 6.8 percent,  owing to a sharp drop in food prices in the first half of the year. Economists have estimated first quarter growth of about six percent.  Government figures will be released on Monday. "Spending is going to remain on an uptrend with moderating inflation  and rising real income and that is going to offset the external drag  from the trade deficit," said Chi Lo, regional economist at Deutsche  Morgan Grenfell (Singapore). In his first policy address following the July 1 handover, Hong Kong  Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa announced plans to boost housing supply  as a way to moderate real estate price rises and make homes more affordable. Hong Kong returned to Chinese rule on July 1 after more than 150 years  of British colonial rule. Economists said that as long as the government used supply-boosting  rather than demand-crimping measures to deal with the housing problem,  the effect on growth should be slight. "We expect the government to pursue increasing supply as the main  measure for curbing the market rather than using any tax measures,"  said DMG's Lo. As a result, "the underlying trend for asset markets in Hong Kong  which include the property and the stock markets, is still up, and  that goes into our baseline assumption for GDP growth," he said. Ken Chan, senior economist at Nikko Securities, said a modest decline  in property values would be welcomed. "If the decline is limited to 10-15 percent it is kind of healthy  so you wouldn't expect a negative impact on next year's growth," he  said. The economist said Nikko has forecast slightly lower growth  in 1998 because of an expected decline in private consumption. HSBC's Leung said that barring the adoption of any draconian measures  to curb speculation, he expected property prices to rise again next  year, though by a smaller magnitude than in 1997. Property values had risen 30 percent during the first half of 1997. Leung said his forecast of 5.3 to 5.7 percent growth next year assumed  that the government will stick with a long-term policy of increasing  housing supply. "If we see a lot of drastic moves in October, then the forecast would  be another story," he said. Chief Executive Tung will deliver an address  to the legislature in October, when he is expected to elaborate on  his housing goals. The economists also said they expected the Hong Kong dollar to be  little changed at end-1997, despite recent volatility in the wake  of currency instability in the rest of Asia.
GCAT	Cyclone Gretelle uprooted trees and cut power lines on Tuesday in the Mozambican capital Maputo as it passed close to the country's Indian Ocean shores. Powerful winds reaching 56 km/hour hit the southernmost Maputo and Gaza provinces, the National Meteorological Institute reported. In the capital gale-force winds brought down trees in the streets and caused power cuts, but there were no reports of injuries or large-scale crop losses. The institute cautioned however that wind speed could rise to 76 km/hour later in the day. "Precautionary measures should be taken," the institute said in its warning. Cyclone Gretelle has reportedly left more than 30,000 people homeless and more than 100 dead or missing in Madagascar, west of Mozambique, and has been labelled the worst there in living memory. South African weather forecasters warned on Monday that the cyclone would cause heavy rains and high seas along the southern African coast.
