CCAT	Binariang Sdn Bhd said on Wednesday that it expected its Maxis Mobile digital cellular network subscriber base to reach 300,000 by year-end, the national Bernama news agency reported. Bernama quoted Binariang chairman Mohammed Hanif Omar who said that Maxis Mobile currently has over 170,000 subscribers. Hanif said: "Our take-up rate has been increasing from 700 subscribers per day to 1,331 subscribers per day." Company officials were not immediately available to confirm the report. Hanif said Binariang had captured 10 percent of the total cellular telephone market and 38 percent of the digital cellular telephone market. On its fixed-line fibre network, Hanif said Binariang has sealed some 200 contracts as of late last year for the provision of services. Binariang is progressing well in fulfilling the contracts, with some 700 km of fibre-optic cables already in place to connect the various development projects to its services, he added in the report. Binariang's fixed-line services market has about 9,000 lines, Hanif said. -- Kuala Lumpur newsroom (603 230 8911)
CCAT	Operating profits at Japan's 10 biggest commercial banks are expected to fall in the current financial year, partly due to lower profits from bond sales, the chairman of the Federation of Bankers' Associations of Japan said on Tuesday. The 1996/97 financial year ends in March. Shunsaku Hashimoto, who is also president of Sakura Bank Ltd, one of the nation's biggest banks, told reporters that plans to separate the Finance Ministry's inspection and supervisory functions seemed to be gaining support. Japanese politicians are currently working on bills to reform the Finance Ministry, which has been criticised for its lax handling of the banking industry.   Hashimoto said the Finance Ministry's planning and supervisory functions are different from the inspection function. "If inspection is to be separated (from the supervisory function), it is important to consider how to maintain closer relations between the inspection function and the planning and supervisory functions," he said. Finance Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka said earlier this month that the government would aim to have its bills on ministry reforms pass through parliament at the next regular session, which begins in January. The ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and the Social Democratic and Sakigake parties have agreed to spin off the supervisory function of the Finance Ministry into an independent body. A ministry source said recently that MOF wants a bank inspection body that is semi-independent and not totally outside its jurisdiction. On the banks' forecast earnings, Hashimoto said: "When we see the commercial banks' earnings on an annual basis, operating profits are expected to be lower (for 1996/97) from a year earlier because of a decline in profits from bond sales and (low) interest rates."   Last Friday, the 10 biggest commercial banks announced their interim earnings. Their combined operating profits -- pre-tax profits from banking business -- fell 36 percent from a year earlier to 1.19 trillion yen in the first half of 1996/97.
ECAT	Albania said on Tuesday it wanted to meet donors and international investors as soon as possible in a bid to kick-start an economy throttled by months of anarchy. Finance Minister Arben Malaj said he had had recent meetings with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank. "We have it confirmed from Italy that it will invite donors, possible donors and others to an international conference," he said at the annual meeting of the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development in London. He did not specify the likely timing of the meeting. An Italian-led multinational force, 6,000 strong, began deploying in Albania on Tuesday to protect aid convoys to the impoverished country. About 300 people have died in months of violence since the collapse of the get-rich-quick pyramid schemes which wiped out the life savings of many ordinary people. But Malaj said there were signs that normal civic life was returning to the country. "Soon Albania will be an attractive country for investors," Malaj said. The government would give priority to encouraging foreign investment in the oil and gas sector, chromium mining, tourism, textiles, agriculture and infrastructure, Malaj said. While a sharp slowdown in the economy as a result of the fighting meant financial compensation to foreign investors in the country was not possible, the government was hoping to pass a law soon which would allow the import of plant and equipment free of duty and tax. Weeks of looting and violence have led to widespread damage to buildings and businesses in the country and the breakdown of government authority. Private foreign investment had reached $95 million by the end of last year from $45 million three years earlier, Malaj said, adding that the country had enjoyed good support from international investors since the collapse of communism in the early 1990s. The EBRD, set up in 1991 to assist central and eastern Europe in the transition to market economies, said the projects it had been supporting in Albania before violence erupted had been carefully chosen and had not suffered unduly to date. "They have not been fundamentally interrupted either physically or in terms of cashflow," said Olivier Descamps, the Bank's representative for Albania. He said the international financial community wanted to start negotiations involving the IMF, World Bank, the European Union and Italy and Greece as soon as law and order had been restored in Albania. "The aim is to stabilise the economic situation and gather bilateral grant money for the short-term needs of the Albanian people. They will then need aid and rebuilding money, a Bosnia-type effort," Descamps said. Malaj said the EBRD was backing eight projects in Albania, three in the state sector and five in the private sector. It had committed 60 million European currency units ($53 million) of funds to date.
