MCAT	Croatia's benchmark call money rate fell 50 basis points to 10 percent on Thursday on the unusually high supply of kuna funds, dealers said. "We've seen a strong rise in supply of kuna funds, and because of that the interest rate on call money loans fell to 10 percent from 10.5 percent," Jasenka Blagaic told Reuters. Blagaic said there was over 85 million kuna of fresh funds on offer against the demand of 13.5 million, which was fully met in the morning trade. Of those, call money loans accounted for 13 million, and the rest was one two-month loan granted to a savings bank at 18 percent a year. The overnight trade totalled 30.2 million, as one bank borrowed to maintain its mandatory reserves and one had shortfalls. -- Davor Huic, Zagreb Newsroom, 385-1-4557075
MCAT	Thai financial markets ended a stormy week on a positive note on Friday as some investors appeared to digest a major revamp of the troubled finance sector and withdrawals from weak finance companies slowed. But analysts cautioned that despite the turnaround after four successive days of hard knocks, the road ahead remained rocky. "It could well drag on for a few more months. We might see some Thai macroeconomic indicators improve, but this is a different microeconomic problem that will linger on until investors are totally convinced," said the head of research at a foreign brokerage who declined to be named. The stock market finished up 2.19 percent as bargain hunters bought cheap banking and finance stocks that brokers said may have been oversold this week. The baht firmed late, rising to 25.920/930 against the dollar from 25.948/970 earlier in the day. "In the afternoon, there was a lot more selling of dollars as the market became more settled in response to measures taken to help the finance sector. People feel the action might do good," said a Siam Commercial Bank dealer. In a sweeping restructuring, Thai authorities on Monday ordered 10 finance firms, hard-hit by a liquidity crunch, to raise capital by a total of 8.25 billion baht ($317 million). They also told banks and finance companies to raise provisions for bad loans, primarily to the depressed property sector, to 115 percent and 120 percent respectively from 100 percent. Some analysts said a statement by IMF managing director Michel Camdessus expressing confidence in Thai authorities' handling of the economy had helped. "I see them taking steps to address one of the vulnerabilities of the Thai economy... I am confident that the measures and the programme for the future will have the potential to carry the economy back on track for sustainable growth," Camdessus said in Hong Kong. Camdessus's words were "a strong and encouraging statement", a Hong-Kong based Peregrine Investment executive said. A run on deposits this week from the troubled finance firms slowed to about 3.5 billion baht in withdrawals on Thursday compared with a total of 10.4 billion baht cleared on Tuesday and Wednesday, he said. "The market seems to have calmed down, and investors have come to realise that the measures imposed by the Bank of Thailand will eventually strengthen the sector," a central bank official told Reuters. Analysts said the bitter pills prescribed to financial institutions would be hard to swallow, but had the potential to cure the illness. "The measures, especially on the sub-standard assets, will usher a long and painful adjustment period. But at the end, we think the authorities did the right thing," said Suphavudh Saicheau of Phatra Thanakit Plc, one of Thailand's biggest finance and securities firms. "Many finance firms might see zero profit for this year and next. And those small companies who cannot meet the requirement will eventually be taken over, leading to a more solid and healthy sector," he said. The troubles were exacerbated by slow economic growth and a liquidity crunch caused by the Bank of Thailand's policy of maintaining high interest rates to deter speculation in the baht, which was hit by devaluation rumours last month. Finance Minister Amnuay Viravan said on Friday that his ministry would issue zero-coupon bonds to raise funds to help sick finance firms. ($1 = 26 baht)
CCAT	Iomega Corp. said Thursday it plans to apply its computer storage technology to handheld consumer electronics in a way that could lower the cost of saving and transfering data to such devices. The reusable data storage system, to be known as "n-hand," could be used in digital cameras, computer game devices, cellular phones and handheld personal computers known as digital assistants. In cameras, for example, the technology could function as a removable "digital film" that would replace existing chemical photographic film. "Our n-hand technology ... has the potential to change the way consumers use portable electronic devices," said Kim Edwards, president and chief executive of the Roy, Utah-based company, in a statement. "We are bringing personal computer-like storage to portable devices," added George Meyer, Iomega's director of marketing for new business, in a telephone interview. The n-hand disks are expected to be priced at less than $10 for a 20-megabyte disk, and could be available by the second half of 1997. Iomega said the n-hand disks are about half the size of a business card. Several industry analysts said they believe Iomega's technology could help propel digital cameras into the consumer mainstream within a matter of years, by freeing users from the fixed capacity of existing flash memory storage and by substantially reducing the overall cost of such cameras. A digital camera could store from 50 to 80 images on a single $10 n-hand disk, Iomega said, depending on image resolution. Consumers now pay hundreds of dollars for a flash memory card capable of holding the same number of images, it noted. Jim Porter, a data storage analyst with market research firm Disk/Trend Inc. of Mountain View, Calif., said the Iomega technology could cut the cost of storing photographs by a factor of 20 times. A Kodak digital camera costing $499 currently could be priced as low as $300 within a matter of years, he said, reflecting the elimination of more costly digital storage methods. Iomega's plans pose a theat to makers of flash memory chips that are used to store digital information in such small electronic devices currently. Leading makers including Sandisk Corp., Intel Corp. and Toshiba Corp. In addition, the Iomega system could help accelerate the current digital transformation of the camera industry, leading to a decline in revenues that cameramakers receive from conventional silver halide-based photo film and equipment. "With 'n-hand' you have a digital camera that you can treat like a regular camera," Meyer said, referring to the replaceable nature of the Iomega high-density floppy disk system. "This technology can make digital cameras much more competitive with regular ones," he said. Besides lacking a low-cost removable storage medium, digital cameras offer inferior picture quality but image resolution is improving rapidly, analysts said. This could lead to explosive growth of the new cameras in coming years. Shares of the company closed up $1.375 to $25.375 on active trading on Nasdaq. On Friday, Iomega's stock will begin trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
ECAT	Spain's Industry Ministry predicted an economic pick-up in the second quarter, Minister Josep Pique said on Tuesday. "We can be assured of a recovery in industrial activity in the second quarter (when) industrial production will grow 4.8 percent year on year," Pique told a press conference. He said the recovery shown in the last industrial survey extended over all subsectors, along with an increase in capacity usage. Production capacity use in the first quarter was 77.4 percent, versus 77.1 percent in the previous three months and 76.1 percent in the first quarter of 1996. Pique said this figure may rise to 80 percent in the next few months.
MCAT	Spot power prices in the most of the U.S. West lost ground Thursday due to a lack of buying interest from utilities, trade sources said. "A lot of marketers are long, but no utilities are buying," said one trader. He noted that recent high natural gas prices led many utilities to hold off from selling forward. "They wanted to run as little gas as possible and to max-out their coal, nuclear, and hydro resources." Next-day Palo Verde firm, peak power was last trading near $23.00 per megawatt hour (MWh), down from $24.00-25.00 on Wednesday. Firm, off-peak Palo Verde was quoted near $13.25. Northwest prices, however, were said to find support from the Bonneville Power Administration's decision to raise next-day offers by $1.50 to $2.00 per MWh for Friday. Next-day California-Oregon border firm, on-peak power was last quoted $25.00-26.00 per megawatt hour (MWh), unchanged from Wednesday. Off-peak COB was quoted near $18.50. Mid-Columbia firm, peak was quoted $23.50-24.00, down from $25.00-26.00 on Wednesday, as some Northwest utilities sought to undercut Bonneville's offers. Cash COB for December was quoted $25.40-25.80, compared with $23.00-$23.50 on Wednesday. Palo Verde for December was quoted $24.00-24.50, up from $21.75-$22.25. --Los Angeles bureau + 1 213 955 6761
GCAT	A peaceful end to Peru's hostage crisis remained elusive on Monday, as the Peruvian government and rebels failed to reach agreement despite a Cuban offer of asylum for the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA) guerrillas. Government negotiators met MRTA representatives at a Red Cross safe house for the eighth time since the siege began 76 days ago, but talks guarantors said afterward both sides were just digging in behind their bargaining positions. "The commission of guarantors can indicate that both sides are completing their proposals, which without encompassing agreement will clearly establish their positions," Canadian ambassador Anthony Vincent -- one of three guarantors -- told reporters in a prepared statement after the meeting. The downbeat communique was a dash of cold water after a surprise trip by President Alberto Fujimori to the Dominican Republic and Cuba raised the possibility of a Caribbean asylum for the 20-odd hostage takers in a deal to end the siege. The MRTA's European spokesman provided further pessimism by saying the rebels were not interested in asylum. Monday's meeting was carried out in a "cordial" atmosphere, Vincent said, but MRTA leader Nestor Cerpa did not attend. He was represented by his second-in-command, Rolly Rojas. The presence of Cerpa was seen as a positive sign when he first left his stronghold in the captured Japanese ambassador's residence to take part in the fourth round of talks. The talks will continue on Wednesday, Vincent said. Fujimori earlier told a news conference in Havana that Cuban leader Fidel Castro had agreed to grant the guerrillas asylum if all sides agreed to a way out of Latin America's longest-running hostage siege. "Cuba is willing to cooperate in the framework for this asylum but not to participate as a mediator," Fujimori said. Peruvian media reported the Dominican Republic may take six rebels. But the MRTA's international spokesman said the guerrillas would not be lured out of the residence by promises of asylum. "We are not thinking about leaving Peru," spokesman Isaac Velasco told reporters in Pamplona, Spain, where he was attending a book presentation. The heavily-armed Tupac Amaru guerrillas stormed a cocktail party at the residence on Dec. 17. They captured hundreds of hostages, but released most of them to keep 72 heavyweight bargaining chips. Their main demand is the release of 400 jailed comrades. Fujimori has ruled this out, but hinted at other concessions.
MCAT	Brent crude futures dipped in late trading on Friday, following the direction set by NYMEX, brokers said. July Brent was last traded at $20.10 per barrel, down eight cents from London's overnight settlement of $20.18. Just 11 lots were traded by 0830 GMT, although 20 lots of August/September were crossed. NYMEX July crude was last traded on the after-hours ACCESS system at $21.80 per barrel, down six cents from New York trading. Brokers said Brent was keeping in line with NYMEX ahead of the London opening in the absence of other news to direct trading. -- Singapore Newsroom (+65 870 3081)
CCAT	India's political crisis will hit a keenly-awaited $350 million issue of global equity by the country's largest refiner, Indian Oil Corporation (IOC), as crucial reforms are put on hold, analysts said on Thursday. "The Indian government will need to address two key issues before IOC can tap the GDR market -- settlement of oil pool dues and a reforms agenda for the downstream oil industry," said analyst Avadhoot Sabnis at securities firm James Capel B&K. "Given the current political scenario, no action is likely in the immediate future, and the GDR looks delayed until the third quarter of 1997/98," Sabnis said in a note to investors. India was plunged into political chaos on Sunday when the Congress party withdrew crucial support for the ruling coalition. Prime Minister H.D. Deve Gowda, who heads the 10-month-old United Front government, is due to face a vote of confidence in parliament on April 11. "The government is not taking a decision on the price hike. Unless you do that you cannot launch the issue," said Jaspal Bindra, head of corporate finance at UBS Securities. Analysts say an oil price hike is unavoidable to reduce the oil pool deficit, a subsidy the government pays oil firms to compensate them for selling oil in the domestic market below global prices. The oil pool deficit is currently estimated to total around 158 billion rupees ($4.4 billion). Analysts said IOC's issue -- which was due to be launched soon after last month's jumbo offering by the state-run Videsh Sanchar Nigam Ltd -- would be the only significant casualty of the government's ambitious divestment plan. "If things settle down and the budget gets passed I don't see the divestment programme taking a hit," Bindra said. "It all depends on how quickly the political crisis gets resolved. The only one to suffer immediately will be IOC." India plans to raise $1.3 billion in 1997/98 (April-March) by selling shares in state-run firms including IOC, Gas Authority of India, Modern Food Industries and India Tourism Development Corporation. "From a policy perspective, the one near-term issue which will be affected is that the petroleum price hike will be delayed," said Arup Raha, senior economist at U.S. investment bank Lehman Brothers in Hong Kong. Raha said it was unlikely that the country's economic reforms programme which marked India's gradual conversion to a free-market economy would be affected. "The current situation is more of a conflict between personalities rather than policies," he said. "If you take a step back and look at the overall picture, regardless of which party comes to power, the economic agenda is set." ($1=35.85 rupees)
