GCAT	North Korean leader Kim Jong-il celebrated his 55th birthday on Sunday, but the occasion was overshadowed by the surprise defection of his top adviser, talk of a power struggle and a worsening food crisis. North Korea's state-run media heaped praise on Kim Jong-il and state television, received in Hong Kong, showed happy crowds attending firework celebrations, apparently on Saturday night. Tokyo-based Radiopress news service, which closely monitors North Korean broadcasts, said earlier it detected no "festive mood" in Pyongyang with no major events planned except a gymnastics display by several thousand young people. North Korea's state-run radio stations abruptly cancelled their scheduled live coverage of the event without explanation. Korea watchers in Tokyo believe Kim was forced to scale down birthday functions mainly because of severe food shortages caused by two consecutive years of flooding. "There has been some bad news for North Korea, such as the defection of a top official. But more than anything else, food shortages must be the biggest factor," Shinya Kato, an expert on North Korea at Radiopress, told Reuters. Other analysts say the North Korean leadership could risk a backlash by staging lavish events for the birthday. "It's dangerous to invite tens of thousands of hungry citizens to the North Korean capital," said Nozomu Akizuki, professor of Northeast Asian diplomacy at Tokai University. "You have to remember that people down there are really starving. They could even challenge Kim Jong-il," he said. The defection of top Pyongyang ideologue Hwang Jang-yop has only added to the reclusive Stalinist state's woes. Hwang, 73, was a pillar of the North Korean establishment and a senior aide to Kim Jong-il. He and an aide took a taxi to South Korea's consulate in Beijing on Wednesday and asked for asylum. Hwang remains trapped in the compound as negotiations continue to bring him to Seoul. The defection -- Pyongyang has called it a kidnapping -- has dragged China into a heated row that has bred fears of renewed tension on the Korean peninsula and possibly a disastrous collapse of the communist North. The climate worsened on Saturday when another North Korean defector was shot and seriously injured near Seoul and South Korea said it suspected North Korean agents. A senior Japanese government official said Hwang's defection could set off a power struggle that would lead to more defections, a refugee flight and the ultimate collapse of the communist regime. "Now everyone in North Korea's ruling structure is going to be suspicious of everyone else, as well as their own future, and that could prompt a really destructive power struggle," the official said. Meanwhile, the North Korean media lavished praise on Kim Jong-il and tacitly denied that there was any power struggle in Pyongyang. "Political stability (in North Korea) is founded upon the lofty power of our comrade Kim Jong-il whose leadership position is trusted and supported by our people," North Korea's official newspaper Rodong Sinmun said in Sunday's editorial. Although North Korea's domestic media made no mention of Hwang's defection, a top North Korean official suggested that there were "separatists" in North Korea. "He (Kim Jong-il) has guided all the patriotic forces at home and abroad..., containing the line of confrontation, war and division pursued by the domestic and foreign separatists with the line of independence, peaceful reunification and great national unity," Kim Ki-nam, a top ruling party official, told a Pyongyang meeting late on Saturday. Kim Jong-il, supreme commander of the country's 1.1-million-strong military, has yet to be formally confirmed in two key posts held by his late father Kim Il-sung -- general secretary of the ruling Workers' Party and state president.
GCAT	The United States late on Friday vetoed a Security Council resolution drafted by its European Union allies calling on Israel to abandon plans to build a new Jewish neighbourhood in mostly Arab East Jerusalem. The vote was 14 in favour, with only the United States voting against. As one of the council's five permanent members, its negative vote killed the resolution, drafted by Britain, France, Portugal and Sweden. The veto followed a council debate on Wednesday and Thursday in which virtually all the nearly 50 speakers condemned Israel's plan to build 6,500 homes for Jews on a tree-covered hill between East Jerusalem and Bethlehem that Israel captured during the 1967 Middle East war. The site is called Har Homa by Israel and Jabal Abu Ghneim by the Palestinians. Israel regards the entire city of Jerusalem as its undivided capital while the Palestinians see East Jerusalem as the capital of a future Palestinian state. U.S. ambassador Bill Richardson criticised the Israeli action, both during the debate and after casting his veto, saying it undermined trust and confidence so badly needed in the Middle East peace process. But he said the council was "not an appropriate forum for debating the issues now under negotiation between the parties." "Furthermore, this resolution makes sweeping statements concerning the legal status of Israeli settlements, which the parties themselves have agreed are to be treated as a 'permanent status' issue in the talks that are about to resume," said Richardson, whose country is the main sponsor of Mideast negotiations. "I am sorry to say that this resolution would not help move us forward towards our common goal," he added. The veto was the 71st by the United States in the 52-year history of the United Nations. It was the first cast by Richardson, who last month succeeded Madeleine Albright, now U.S. secretary of state, as the American U.N. representative. Richardson told reporters earlier he had tried to get the council to reach consensus on a statement, which carries less weight than a resolution, but that "regrettably, one member of the council did not even permit a discussion of that alternative option." A council source said the member was Egypt. The Palestine Liberation Organisation's U.N. observer, Nasser al-Kidwa, speaking after the veto, said: "In view of the failure of the council to fulfil its obligations, we would request from the members of the United Nations to agree to a meeting of the General Assembly in an emergency session." There is no veto in the 185-member Assembly, whose decisions are not binding. The council resolution would have called on "the Israeli authorities to refrain from all actions or measures, including settlement activities, which alter the facts on the ground, pre-empting the final status negotiations, and have negative implications for the Middle East peace process." It would also have called on Israel to abide scrupulously by its obligations under the Fourth Geneva Convention on the protection of civilians in time of war, which bars settlements in occupied territory, and would have urged all parties to press ahead with the peace process. The last U.S. veto was in May 1995, to block a resolution calling on Israel to rescind the expropriation of 131 acres (53 hectares) of Arab land in East Jerusalem. The last time any of the five permanent council members cast a veto was in January this year when China killed a resolution to send U.N. peacekeepers to Guatemala. China objected because of Guatemala's ties with Taiwan, but at a later meeting allowed the peacekeepers to be dispatched. Russia has used its veto 116 times, Britain on 30 occasions, France 18, and China 3.
CCAT	Rank Group Plc said on Monday that it regarded the potential returns on a proposed deal with Trump Hotels & Casino Resorts Inc as inadequate and did not plan further talks on the issue. Trump Hotels said earlier that it had ended talks with Rank to purchase an equity interest in and to change the theme of Trump's Castle in Atlantic City.   "We explored the possibility of rebranding Trump Castle with Hard Rock branding, but having explored fully, frankly the returns as we perceived it just weren't going to meet our criteria," Rank spokeswoman Susan Donovan said. "So we decided not to pursue it any further," she added. Trump said it has pursued alternative re-theming options for Trump's Castle and a decision was expected shortly. --Brian Killen, London newsroom 44 171 542 7972
