ECAT	India must speed its reforms prgramme in order to attain high growth and attract investment, a senior official of the World Trade Organisation (WTO) said on Friday. "If India is to attain the growth path of seven percent and to receive $10 billion in direct investment...it appears that renewed emphasis needs to be given to the reform programme," WTO deputy director-general Chulsu Kim told an international conference on Asian economies.   "The acceleration of reform would be necessary to overcome the recent slowdown of exports and industrial production, and overcome the serious infrastructure bottleneck faced by Indian companies," Kim told the conference. He recommended an elimination of quantitative restrictions on consumer goods imports and a further liberalisation of the foreign investment regime. Finance Minister P. Chidambaram, who unveiled a market-friendly budget a week ago, said in a newspaper interview on Friday that liberalisation of consumer goods imports would help boost India's "sluggish" import growth and increase customs revenue. "It is viable and necessary to open up consumer goods imports. Opening up of imports is good in itself. It is an advance on trade policy," he said.
GCAT	President Bill Clinton said on Tuesday he had decided to postpone a trip to Latin America scheduled for May until later in the year because of his injured knee. Speaking at a White House event on health care, Clinton said he would visit Mexico, Barbados and Costa Rica in May. He had been due to visit Mexico April 11-12, but the Mexican foreign ministry said Tuesday this had been moved to May 6-7.   Clinton's visits to Barbados and Costa Rica, originally scheduled for the extended Latin America trip in May, would be combined with the Mexico trip and take place May 6-10, the White House said in a statement released after Clinton spoke. Clinton, who tore a tendon in his right knee on March 14, will visit Brazil, Argentina and Venezuela Oct. 12-17, the statement added. The Latin America trip had been scheduled for May 6-13. "Later in the year, we're going to go to South America and do that trip when I'm somewhat more mobile," added Clinton, who is on crutches as he recovers from knee surgery. "Among other things we're going to Argentina and Brazil, they're big countries, there's going to be a lot of moving around and I need a little more physical mobility," he said. "Besides, I'm hoping to ride horses and do some other things and I'm not quite ready for that as you can see."
